summary: Paul Merson reignited his feud with Andros Townsend by mocking the player's brief seven-minute appearance for Tottenham against Burnley on Twitter. This follows a previous dispute where Merson criticized Townsend's inclusion in the England squad, a comment he retracted after Townsend scored a great equalizer for England against Italy. Townsend had previously responded to the initial criticism on social media after his England goal.

Chelsea have made a formal offer to sign FC Tokyo's 22-year-old forward Yoshinori Muto. If the transfer is completed, Muto will immediately join Chelsea's partner club Vitesse Arnhem on loan. FC Tokyo's president confirmed the bid and stated that Chelsea's interest is not related to their recent major sponsorship deal with the Japanese company Yokohama Rubber. Muto, who has 11 international caps for Japan, has not yet decided whether to accept the move but called the offer an honor.

A large-scale study published in Pediatrics found that babies given antibiotics in their first six months are more likely to be overweight as toddlers, with repeated prescriptions before age two further increasing the odds. The research, which did not prove causation, suggested a possible mechanism where antibiotics kill gut bugs, freeing up more food for the body and potentially increasing appetite. The lead author warned that such antibiotic exposure may be a contributing factor to the childhood obesity epidemic and emphasized the need for judicious use of these drugs in infancy. Boys appeared to be more affected, showing a greater propensity for weight gain and slightly increased height.

A Buckingham Palace guard slipped on a manhole cover and fell during the Changing of the Guard ceremony, an incident witnessed by hundreds of tourists and captured on video by a holidaymaker. The guard, who dropped his rifle, quickly got up and appeared very embarrassed. The Ministry of Defence declined to comment.

A&E Networks is remaking the 1977 miniseries "Roots" for a 2016 simulcast on A&E, Lifetime, and History. The new version, described as contemporary, will draw more from Alex Haley's original novel and involve scholars for authenticity. LeVar Burton, the original star, and Mark Wolper, son of the original producer, will be co-executive producers. The remake aims to introduce the powerful story of Kunta Kinte to a new generation of viewers.

Police are investigating a former royal footman's claim that in 1978, aides at Clarence House attempted to force him into an orgy, pinning him down and groping him on his first day. The footman, Christopher Lawler, reported the incident that day but his complaint was allegedly met with an angry response. He left the job immediately. Decades later, after hearing about a probe into historical abuse, he contacted the palace again. His complaint was initially rebuffed but was eventually passed to police months later. A retired royal aide was interviewed and denied involvement. The Royal Household has stated it will cooperate with any police investigation.

An Oregon couple, Jesse and Melissa Meek, announced Melissa's pregnancy in a parody rap video set to the theme song of "The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air." The video, which has been viewed over 1.7 million times on YouTube, features the couple rapping about their life and the process of trying to conceive. It ends with them sharing a sonogram of their unborn child. The couple made the video to share the news with distant loved ones and were surprised by its viral success.

A dress worn by Vivien Leigh as Scarlett O'Hara in the 1939 film *Gone With the Wind* sold for $137,000 at a Heritage Auctions event. The gray jacket and skirt ensemble, which has faded from its original slate blue-gray color, was worn in several key scenes. It was part of a collection of over 150 items from the film owned by James Tumblin, who originally bought the dress for $20 to save it from being discarded. Other notable sales included a hat worn by Leigh for $52,500 and a suit worn by Clark Gable for $55,000.

A two-year-old boy fell into a cheetah exhibit at the Cleveland Metroparks Zoo after his parents dangled him over a railing. The boy suffered minor injuries but was not attacked by the cheetahs, which did not approach him. The child was rescued by his parents and listed in stable condition. The zoo plans to press child endangerment charges against the parents, and the exhibit was closed following the incident.

A non-operational speed camera in Handsworth, Birmingham, which has been inactive for over two years, was found pointing at a house. The camera, along with around 300 others in the West Midlands, was switched off in 2013 due to obsolete technology. Enforcement is now done with mobile units and motorway cameras. Birmingham City Council is aware of the repositioned camera and will send an engineer to the site, with removal being a possibility. The camera will not be part of a new pilot program for digital speed cameras.

Usain Bolt will compete for Jamaica at the IAAF/BTC World Relays in the Bahamas on May 2 and 3. He stated he is fit, healthy, and ready to run, aiming to make his country proud. The JAAA confirmed his selection, and the full team list will be announced soon.

Neymar and Dani Alves attended a Barcelona basketball game where Barcelona beat Real Madrid 85-80, though Real Madrid remains top of their Euro League division on points difference. Before this, Neymar captained Brazil to a 1-0 win over Chile in a match where he faced rough challenges. Prior to the international break, Barcelona's football team had won their El Clasico to go four points clear in La Liga, and they next play Celta Vigo as they pursue a treble.

Italy is facing a surge of migrants from Africa and the Middle East crossing the Mediterranean, with 8,480 rescued in a recent four-day period. Save the Children reported a potential incident where a boat carrying 550 capsized, leaving 400 missing, but the Italian coast guard has not confirmed this, finding no evidence. Over 10,000 migrants arrived in Italy in the first three months of 2015, with at least 480 dying this year due to bad weather, overcrowded boats, and smugglers abandoning ships.

Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger is glad Alexis Sanchez chose his club over Liverpool, though he does not know the exact reason for the decision. Wenger was aware of Liverpool's interest, suggesting it may have been leverage in the Luis Suarez transfer to Barcelona. Sanchez, a £32 million signing, has made a top-level impact with 19 goals, praised for his efficiency, work-rate, and ability to revitalize the team. Ahead of a match against Liverpool, Wenger also downplayed transfer speculation about Raheem Sterling and praised Liverpool manager Brendan Rodgers for his work.

Cyclist Sir Bradley Wiggins will attempt to break the UCI Hour Record on June 7 at the London Olympic Velodrome. The current record of 52.491km is held by Australian Rohan Dennis. Wiggins, a four-time Olympic champion and Tour de France winner, is preparing for this as part of his return to track cycling, with the goal of winning an eighth Olympic medal in Rio 2016. Tickets for the event go on sale on April 19.

Serena Williams described her difficult three-set Fed Cup victory over Sara Errani as an "eye-opener," revealing she is not as prepared for the claycourt season as she thought and must adjust her hard-court style of play. Despite Williams' singles win, the U.S. team lost the tie 3-2 and was relegated to World Group II after she and Alison Riske lost the decisive doubles rubber. U.S. captain Mary Joe Fernandez said the team must work harder to return to the elite World Group next year.

River Plate are interested in re-signing striker Radamel Falcao from Manchester United, where he has struggled on loan, scoring only four Premier League goals. The club's vice president stated they "dream of Falcao" and that "the doors are open." Falcao previously played for River Plate for eight years, scoring 34 goals in 90 appearances. His future is uncertain as it is unclear if Manchester United will keep him or if he will return to his parent club, Monaco.

In 2015, X Factor finalist and pop star Ella Henderson became the official face of the dry shampoo brand Batiste for its 'Ready For It' campaign. This was her first brand endorsement. The international campaign included images of Henderson with various hairstyles against a city background and a TV advertisement featuring her song "Mirror Man." Henderson expressed excitement for the partnership, stating she regularly uses the product.

In Kenosha, Wisconsin, a billboard featuring Officer Pablo Torres, who fatally shot Aaron Siler, was erected by the police union, causing shock and anger among Siler's family and friends who called it disrespectful. The police association stated the billboard was intended to thank the community for its support. Torres shot Siler after a vehicle and foot pursuit; Siler was wanted on a felony warrant. This was the second shooting involving Torres in a short period; he had previously shot and wounded an armed man in a separate incident, which was later deemed justified. The investigation into Siler's death is ongoing.

Eight Iranian border guards were killed in a clash with militants who crossed into Iran from Pakistan near the town of Negur. The militant group Jaish al Adl claimed responsibility. Iranian forces killed three militants and have asked Pakistan to apprehend the survivors. Jaish al Adl is a Sunni group that targets Shiites and has conducted previous attacks in Iran. Pakistan condemned the attack and stated it is investigating, promising to apprehend the militants if they entered its territory.

Japan's Defense Minister Gen Nakatani stated the country's Air Self Defense Force has never encountered an extraterrestrial UFO. The statement was in response to a question from lawmaker Antonio Inoki, who asked if fighter jets were ever scrambled to meet alien threats. Inoki, a former wrestler, claims to have personally seen a UFO.

A 35-year-old passenger, Jin Pai, was hospitalized with deep cuts requiring dozens of stitches after a toilet he was squatting on at Hefei Xinqiao International Airport broke. He was standing on the rim because he was worried about cleanliness. The porcelain toilet collapsed, shattering and leaving him injured. He initially told friends he was squatting but later told police he was sitting, possibly to avoid compensation. Authorities deemed it an accident but reminded the public that toilets are for sitting, not standing.

Kevin Rebbie, 56, of Limerick Township, Pennsylvania, was arrested for allegedly sexually abusing a girl from age 9 to 13 and for using a hidden camera in a bathroom to film her and other juveniles, including close-up images, over a four-year period. He faces multiple charges including aggravated indecent assault and invasion of privacy. The investigation began when the 15-year-old girl found the camera. Rebbie admitted to purchasing the camera specifically to record her. He is being held on $500,000 bail with a preliminary hearing scheduled for May 1.

Japanese photographer Yûki Aoyama's series features portraits of daughters standing po-faced next to their fathers, who are leaping into the air in dramatic poses while wearing sharp suits. The images, from his book "Daughter and Salary Man," aim to show the serious-acting fathers expressing a fun, heroic side. The families are photographed in front of various Japanese landmarks, and the curious pictures are generating significant online interest.

The dismissal of England's managing director, Paul Downton, has shifted focus to Kevin Pietersen's potential return to the England cricket team. Pietersen, who was controversially axed in 2014, has rejoined Surrey for the new County Championship season. His participation in Surrey's team photo session, where he appeared jovial and reflective, is seen as a step towards a possible international comeback, with England hoping to regain the Ashes this summer.

Ceahlaul Piatra Neamt has sacked its Brazilian coach, Ze Maria, for the second time in a week following a 2-0 loss. He was initially fired and then reinstated by the owner before being dismissed again. The club is 16th in the standings and six points from safety. Ze Maria will be replaced by Serbian coach Vanya Radinovic.

Nabil Dirar believes Radamel Falcao regrets his loan move to Manchester United, where he has struggled, scoring only four goals. Dirar states Falcao was unhappy in Monaco but would have played more and been in the Champions League had he stayed. Manchester United are unlikely to make the transfer permanent for £46 million.

New Zealand police are seeking public assistance to identify a very tall man who robbed a Christchurch dairy, stealing a cash register till and approximately $1500. The offender, who wore a distinctive cartoon mask and a fluorescent orange sweatshirt, demanded cash from the owner's daughter. No weapons were seen, and the man remains at large.

Kaitlyn Granado, a 24-year-old math teacher at MacArthur High School in Irving, Texas, has been arrested twice. Her first arrest was on March 19 for an inappropriate relationship with a 15-year-old student, to which she admitted kissing and letting him touch her breasts. She was released on bail, suspended, and placed on administrative leave. A second arrest followed after another 15-year-old student accused her of having sex with him on two consecutive nights in January. Granado was booked into jail again and released after posting a $50,000 bail. The school district confirmed she was placed on administrative leave.

A crocodile in the tourist marina of Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, was filmed swimming with a dead pet dog, belonging to a local bike shop owner, locked in its jaws. The video, viewed over half a million times, shows the crocodile holding the dog for hours. A tourist witness explained the dog approached the water's edge from a crocodile sanctuary 200 meters away. While social media users reacted with horror, crocodiles are common in the area due to urbanization encroaching on their mangrove habitat.

Despite a 2-0 loss to Southampton, Hull City manager Steve Bruce is convinced his team will avoid Premier League relegation. Hull is only two points clear of the drop zone with six difficult games remaining. Bruce attributes their season-long struggles to failing to meet heightened expectations and suffering long-term injuries to several key players. Meanwhile, Southampton moved up to fifth in the table, but manager Ronald Koeman must address an internal issue after Sadio Mane broke team rules by attempting to take a penalty.

Teacher Ian Guffick was banned from teaching for at least two years after he altered pupils' SATs exam answers and allowed them to make changes outside of test conditions at Mitton Manor Primary School. This resulted in the Department for Education annulling all of the school's 2014 SATs results. Guffick admitted to the allegations and a professional conduct panel found his actions constituted unacceptable professional conduct, though they were deemed not to be fraudulent.

Manchester United goalkeeper Anders Lindegaard, who has made few appearances for the club, is married to Swedish-Albanian model Misse Beqiri. The couple, who have been dating since 2012 and have a son together, married in a beach wedding in Mauritius. Lindegaard is United's third-choice goalkeeper and has been told he can leave the club.

The 13 iconic, 10-foot-tall blue letters from Yankee Stadium failed to sell at a Sotheby's auction, receiving no bids despite a pre-auction estimate of $300,000 to $600,000. The current owner, Yankees Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson, had purchased them after the stadium's final game in 2008. In contrast, a New York Mets bullpen car, estimated at $20,000-$30,000, sold for $112,500.

Liverpool manager Brendan Rodgers has spoken to Raheem Sterling and Jordon Ibe about their professional responsibilities after Sterling was pictured inhaling nitrous oxide and both were seen with shisha pipes. Neither player will be disciplined, as Rodgers wants to move on. He also has Steven Gerrard available for the FA Cup semi-final against Aston Villa but has not confirmed if he will be recalled. Rodgers believes that past near-misses in competitions are part of the journey to eventual success.

After returning from international duty with Germany, where he played in a 2-0 Euro 2016 qualifier win, Arsenal's Mesut Ozil is focusing on an upcoming Premier League match against Liverpool. Having missed Arsenal's previous game due to illness, he is expected to start. Ozil claims he is now perfectly adjusted to the demanding schedule of English football and has been in fine form since returning from a longer-term injury, scoring and assisting multiple goals since January.

Barcelona president Josep Maria Bartomeu insists the club is very happy with manager Luis Enrique and has no plans to replace him, refuting speculation to the contrary. He praised Enrique's work and commitment, noting his contract runs until 2016 and that Barcelona is still in contention to win three trophies this season. The summary is supported by details of a recent victory over Valencia.

Jordan Henderson has agreed to a new long-term contract with Liverpool, worth around £100,000-a-week and running until 2020. He is the third key player, after Daniel Sturridge and Philippe Coutinho, to sign an extension. Henderson, who has shown significant improvement, is a candidate to replace the departing Steven Gerrard as club captain. Meanwhile, talks with Raheem Sterling over a new contract are paused but are expected to resume at the end of the season.

Filipe Luis intends to stay at Chelsea until his three-year contract ends, despite interest from his former club Atletico Madrid to re-sign him. He states he is happy at Chelsea, where he has struggled to secure the left back position. Manager Jose Mourinho is demanding full focus from his league-leading team for their nine remaining difficult Premier League games.

Nathan Hughes's three-match ban for a collision with George North was overturned on appeal. The appeal panel concluded the incident was accidental and not an act of foul play, reversing the original ruling of recklessness. Hughes is now free to play immediately. North was knocked unconscious, his third concussion in two months, and was advised to take a month off.

A fiery sunset in Washington, captured by a photographer, was caused by smoke from wildfires in Siberia. The fires, started by farmers, grew out of control due to strong winds, destroying villages. Smoke particles carried by winds across the Pacific filtered out shorter wavelengths of sunlight, allowing only intense red and orange colors to be seen, especially at sunrise and sunset. As the smoke dissipates, the sunsets will lose their red hue and air quality will improve.

A Missouri woman's new 2015 Ford Fusion was stolen from her driveway. Police recovered the car after a tip, and it was returned with modifications including red rims and detailing. Instead of being upset, the owner humorously thanked the thieves on Facebook. The car required professional cleaning due to cigarette and marijuana smells. The woman is also creating a smoothie at her restaurant to honor the man who helped locate her car.

Manchester City players face losing £500,000 each in bonuses, totaling around £12 million, if the club fails to qualify for the Champions League. The incentivized contracts are designed to comply with financial fair play rules. After a recent defeat to Manchester United, City sits in fourth place, just four points ahead of Liverpool, with the top four Premier League teams qualifying for the Champions League. Manager Manuel Pellegrini admitted the team's season has disintegrated after a strong start, with seven losses and early cup exits. This situation could also hinder their ability to attract world-class transfer targets like Paul Pogba.

Manchester United's Under-18s beat rivals Manchester City 1-0 in a "mini-derby." The match, held at Altrincham's Moss Lane, was a contrast to the senior fixture, featuring many local English players and free entry. United's winning goal was scored by Callum Gribbin with a well-taken free-kick. The victory places United two points behind league leaders Middlesbrough with a game in hand, while City lost their second play-off match. The game showcased significant skill and commitment, suggesting several young players on both teams may deserve first-team opportunities in the future.

England goalkeeper Joe Hart, after earning his 50th international cap, praised Italian goalkeeper Gianluigi Buffon as a "legend of the game" and an inspiration. Hart, who is 10 years younger than the 37-year-old Buffon, stated he is still learning and looks up to the veteran, who earned his 147th cap. Hart expressed pride in his own milestone and his desire to continue earning caps for his club and country.

Chipotle is entering the $70 billion food delivery market by partnering with the Postmates app to deliver orders in 67 cities. The service includes a 9% charge in addition to Postmates delivery fees starting at $5. Other chains like Starbucks, Taco Bell, McDonald's, and Burger King are also developing or testing delivery services.

The parents of the youngest victim of the Boston Marathon bombings, Bill and Denise Richard, whose 8-year-old son Martin was killed and daughter Jane severely injured, have publicly pleaded with the Justice Department to drop the death penalty for the convicted bomber, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev. They argue that a life sentence without parole would end the case and avoid years of painful appeals that would force them to relive the tragedy. They believe this would allow their family and Boston to move forward.

A mystery billionaire spent £400 million to convert a Boeing 747-8 jumbo jet into a luxury private home over three years. The plane, which normally carries 600 passengers, has been customized for the owner and dozens of guests. It features a dining room with an adjoining kitchen, multiple lounges, a master bedroom, a conference room, and an "aeroloft" with eight beds. The interior is designed to resemble a luxury hotel rather than a traditional aircraft cabin.

SpaceX launched a Falcon 9 rocket carrying a Dragon cargo spacecraft to the International Space Station. The launch was successful, but the attempt to land the rocket's first stage on a floating barge failed, as the rocket landed too hard and tipped over. This was the company's second failed attempt at such a landing, and they aim to master the technique to reduce spaceflight costs through rocket reusability. The Dragon spacecraft will deliver over 4,300 pounds of supplies to the station and later return to Earth with over 3,000 pounds of cargo. This was the sixth SpaceX mission to the ISS.

Priscilla Presley will be a witness for a contest-winning couple's wedding at the new Elvis Presley's Graceland Wedding Chapel in Las Vegas' Westgate Hotel on April 23. The winners, announced the following Monday, receive a reception, a two-night hotel stay, airfare, and tickets to an Elvis show. Priscilla collaborated with the Today show on the contest and emphasized the chapel is a first-class, non-joking endeavor with no impersonators. The chapel is part of the first permanent Graceland exhibit outside Memphis. Contestants had to submit videos or photos explaining why they deserved to win.

Liverpool vice-captain Jordan Henderson believes his team can still catch Manchester City in the Premier League, despite being four points behind. This follows a 2-0 win over Newcastle United, a vital result after recent disappointing performances. In the match, Raheem Sterling scored early and Joe Allen added a second goal late. Henderson and goalkeeper Simon Mignolet equalled the record for most appearances in Europe's top five leagues this season.

Roma defeated Napoli 1-0 in Serie A, ending a four-month winless streak at home. Miralem Pjanic scored the winning goal from a counter-attack in the 25th minute. Goalkeeper Morgan de Sanctis made several key saves to secure the victory. The win moved second-place Roma four points ahead of rivals Lazio, while Napoli's winless run extended to five matches. Security was heightened for the match due to past fan violence, but no incidents were reported.

Doncaster Rovers and Fleetwood Town played a goalless draw in a poor League One match. Due to the lack of action, Doncaster's media team created a match highlights video of only 27 seconds, containing just 14 seconds of footage showing the kick-off, a goal kick, and the final whistle.

A man has developed a remarkable relationship with his blood parrot cichlid fish, which enjoys being stroked and massaged by his hand inside the tank. The fish, captured on video, repeatedly swims away but returns to rest calmly in the man's fingers for massages and even follows his hand to the surface. The owner, Roland Giroux, hand-feeds the fish and plays with it for at least 15 minutes daily. He removed two other fish from the tank for bullying this pet, and after he began interacting with it, the fish became sociable and now expects daily interaction. The blood parrot cichlid is a hybrid first bred in Taiwan in 1986.

Ben Stokes is a fiery, aggressive cricketer whose character is seen as a positive asset for an England team that can sometimes lack personality. His return to the Kensington Oval is a reminder of his past indiscretion, like punching a locker and breaking his wrist, highlighting the need to channel his aggression properly. While his feistiness is valued, it requires careful management, as shown when coach Peter Moores successfully advised him after a clash with Marlon Samuels. The key is to control his aggression so that it produces runs and wickets without being quashed. England is committed to playing him regularly to help him reach his full potential.

Wales' crucial Euro 2016 qualifier against Belgium at the Cardiff City Stadium is a 33,000 sell-out. Both teams lead Group B with 11 points, though Belgium is ahead on goal difference. Wales' recent 3-0 win over Israel has raised expectations for qualification. The match will not be moved to the larger Millennium Stadium due to UEFA rules prohibiting venue changes within 120 days, and the Welsh squad reportedly prefers the smaller Cardiff venue.

England coach John Peacock has named his defending champion squad for the UEFA European Under-17 Championship in Bulgaria. The team, which qualified with a perfect record, is in Group D with Holland, Italy, and the Republic of Ireland. The squad includes players from various Premier League clubs, with Arsenal's Stephy Mavididi and Chris Willock receiving their first call-ups, and Liverpool's Herbie Kane and Trent Arnold earning a recall. England's first match is against Italy on May 7.

Manchester City are pursuing a transfer for 14-year-old Anderlecht playmaker Evangelos Patoulidis, who is considered a top talent. Arsenal and Barcelona are also interested, but Patoulidis previously rejected a move to Barcelona's academy at age 12. City have held discussions with Anderlecht's chairman to agree on a compensation package as manager Manuel Pellegrini aims to build for the future.

Vanessa Santillan, a 33-year-old transgender escort from Mexico, was found strangled and beaten to death in a Fulham flat at the end of March. A 23-year-old man was arrested in connection with her death and has been bailed pending further questioning. Police are appealing for anyone who had contact with her in the hours before her death to come forward.

A woman named Dawn, who had suffered seven miscarriages, appeared on The Jeremy Kyle show after £207 saved for a gravestone for one of her babies, Daniel James, was stolen. She accused her housemate and friend, Jamie, a convicted burglar. A lie detector test on the show confirmed Jamie had stolen the money. It was also revealed Jamie had sent Dawn a Facebook message confessing to the theft but blaming his girlfriend, Carol. Dawn expressed feeling betrayed, as the money was meant to be a final gesture of love for her son.

ISIS released over 200 Yazidi captives, primarily women, children, the ill, and elderly, with the help of Arab tribal leaders. The freed individuals were received by Kurdish Peshmerga forces. This follows ISIS's 2014 attacks on northern Iraq, which caused a major humanitarian crisis for the Yazidi minority, who faced mass killings, enslavement, and displacement, prompting international airstrikes and aid.

Harry Kane, nominated for both PFA Player and Young Player of the Year, is featured in an animation by Copa90. The video, released ahead of the awards ceremony, uses layered still photographs to showcase his best goals and celebrations from his breakthrough season, including strikes against Chelsea and Arsenal and his England debut goal.

Jamie Carragher believes Brendan Rodgers is still the right manager for Liverpool despite a season with no trophies and an expected finish outside the top four. He argues a manager's future should not be determined by one game and that new signings have not yet fully settled in. Carragher states Rodgers must identify areas for improvement and make the right signings to compete for trophies and a top-four finish next season. The article also notes Carragher received a Beacon Award for his community work with under-privileged areas on Merseyside.

At East Midlands Airport, a four-year-old boy, James Hayward, had his brightly colored plastic Nerf gun confiscated by security because it was deemed to resemble a prohibited item. His father criticized the staff as "over-zealous" for the pat-down and confiscation, which forced them to leave the toy to avoid missing their flight. The airport apologized and offered to post the toy back, but defended its actions by stating that government regulations prohibit any items that resemble weapons. The family later bought the boy a replacement toy.

A man from Humpty Doo, Australia, posted a Gumtree ad seeking a girlfriend or wife. He listed requirements for his "dream girl," including being a non-drinker, fit, attractive, reliable, honest, loyal, good at domestic tasks, and "great in bed." In return, he offered benefits like accommodation, a company car, a phone, a laptop, and a gym membership. He described himself as a 31-year-old, tattooed, athletic, financially successful, and well-endowed man who does not drink or smoke. He stated that "all reasonable offers will be considered" but that former partners should not apply.

FA Chairman Greg Dyke has the backing of five former England managers—Graham Taylor, Glenn Hoddle, Kevin Keegan, Sven-Goran Eriksson, and Steve McClaren—for his radical proposals to increase the number of home-grown players in club squads. The plan is to raise the minimum from eight to twelve and redefine "home-grown" as players trained in England for three years before age 18, rather than 21. The former managers warn that without these changes, the pool of English talent will continue to shrink, hindering England's chances in international competitions. They argue that while promising young players are emerging, they lack sufficient opportunity to play at the top level.

In the upcoming episode of Poldark, Demelza gives birth to a daughter, solidifying Ross Poldark's devotion to her. However, the show's timeline is criticized for being unrealistic, as Demelza's pregnancy jumps from the initial announcement to eight months pregnant and then to childbirth almost instantly. This rapid progression mirrors a previous pregnancy on the show and has been noted by fans on social media.

Leicester City manager Nigel Pearson is urging his team to remain focused on their own performance and not be distracted by the results of their relegation rivals. Despite being bottom of the table, consecutive wins, including a last-minute victory against West Brom, have brought them within three points of safety. Pearson emphasizes that their future is in their own hands and that they must concentrate on winning their own remaining games, rather than relying on other teams' results or external optimism.

A North Pacific gray whale named Varvara set the mammal migration record by swimming nearly 14,000 miles from Russia's Sakhalin Island to Mexico. Scientists suggest her journey to known eastern gray whale breeding grounds indicates she may actually be an eastern gray whale, not the endangered western gray whale she was thought to be. This challenges previous genetic differentiation between the two groups and could mean the population of western gray whales is even lower than the estimated 150.

A section of seabed, approximately 1,000 to 1,640 feet long and 100 feet wide, rose 30 to 50 feet above sea level overnight along the coast of Japan's Shiretoko Peninsula. Geologists attribute this to a landslide, likely caused by melting ice and snow, which pivoted the underwater area upward. The event occurred without any noticeable tremors or sounds and is not related to recent earthquakes. Marine organisms are still attached to the newly exposed landmass.

Gregory van der Wiel has denied rumors he will leave Paris Saint-Germain, stating he is happy at the club, loves the city and his teammates, and wants to sign a new contract. This comes after a disagreement with manager Laurent Blanc over being dropped for a Champions League match. Despite his desire to stay, PSG is linked with signing Dani Alves, which could affect Van der Wiel's future.

Carlos Tevez wishes to leave Juventus to return to his former club Boca Juniors. Despite having a contract with Juventus until 2016, Tevez has requested to leave this summer. Boca Juniors' president confirms a deal is close but depends on Tevez first terminating his contract with Juventus. Although reluctant to lose their top scorer, Juventus have accepted his decision and are seeking replacements. Tevez's international manager stated the move would not affect his place on the national team.

Bayern Munich defeated Porto 6-1 to overturn a first-leg deficit and advance to the Champions League semi-finals. During the match, manager Pep Guardiola ripped his trousers, exposing his underwear. The goals were scored by Thiago Alcantara, Jerome Boateng, Thomas Muller, Xabi Alonso, and Robert Lewandowski (twice).

A multi-vehicle crash involving three cars on the Brisbane Valley Highway near Fernvale injured ten people, including four children. A 40-year-old man, a 5-year-old boy, a 27-year-old woman, and a 6-year-old girl were airlifted to hospitals with injuries. Six others, including an infant, were taken to a different hospital with minor injuries. One person was trapped and had to be freed by emergency crews using hydraulic equipment. The highway was closed for several hours with diversions in place.

Arsenal midfielder Mesut Ozil showed off a new Apple Watch on Instagram ahead of a crucial Premier League match against league leaders Chelsea. Meanwhile, Arsenal has been boosted by the return of Jack Wilshere from injury. Club legend Ray Parlour believes Wilshere is the future of the club but that his potential is dependent on his ability to stay fit, which has been a problem in recent seasons.

Referee Mark Clattenburg will officiate the Manchester derby at Old Trafford. He has sent off three players from the two clubs this season, with two of those red cards shown to Manchester United players. Manchester United is in good form, having won five consecutive league games and moving a point above Manchester City, adding extra incentive to the match which could decide who finishes second in the league.

Federal MP Bob Katter accused the Queensland Government of racism, stating it viewed Indigenous MP Billy Gordon as a "little black puppet on a string" who would resign after being accused of domestic violence and withholding his criminal history. Katter, who is of Lebanese descent, defended the term by citing his own experiences with racism. Gordon's decision to remain in parliament as an independent has thrown the government into chaos. The statement has been criticized on social media for its terminology.

Dayna Dobias, a 19-year-old from Illinois with cerebral palsy, creates dancing videos to challenge stereotypes and inspire others. She aims to change perceptions that people with disabilities are incapable or fundamentally different, emphasizing that she lives a normal life, drives, and attends college.
