Gateshead and Guiseley drew 1-1 in a National League match. Guiseley took the lead against the run of play in the first half when Jake Lawlor scored. Gateshead equalized in the second half after a defensive error allowed Wes York to curl a shot into the net. Both teams had chances, and the result leaves Gateshead unbeaten in nine matches and Guiseley unbeaten in five.

Bristol Sport Ltd, owner of Bristol City Football Club, plans to replace two stands at its current stadium to increase capacity. This is an alternative to the delayed new stadium project at Ashton Vale. The redevelopment plan was approved by Bristol City Council, and majority shareholder Steve Lansdown stated that, pending a six-week judicial review period, work is scheduled to begin in May.

Cuadrilla suspended its shale gas fracking operations in Lancashire after a 1.5 magnitude tremor, the second earthquake in two months. The British Geological Survey (BGS) stated both tremors shared a similar location and mechanism near the drilling site. Fracking involves shattering shale rocks underground to release gas. Cuadrilla will consult with authorities and analyze data before deciding whether to resume, a process expected to take weeks. The BGS confirmed that injecting pressurized water into rocks, as done in fracking, can cause earthquakes. While controversial, a UK parliamentary committee supports the process with tight regulation.

Angus Carpenter, a Liverpool busker, was found guilty of one count of fraud after playing with a Hillsborough Justice Campaign banner on his bagpipes, giving the impression he was collecting for the charity. He was cleared of two other fraud counts. The charity's chairman stated Carpenter had permission to display the banner but not to collect funds. Carpenter claimed the banner was a tribute and that he was simply busking.

Ipswich Town defeated Queens Park Rangers 3-0 in a Championship match. Grant Ward scored the first goal, Luke Varney scored a second after a goalkeeping error by QPR's Alex Smithies, and Tom Lawrence added a third. QPR offered little attack and hit the post late. The win moved Ipswich up to 14th place, above QPR in 15th. Ipswich manager Mick McCarthy praised his team's response after recent poor form, while QPR boss Ian Holloway criticized his team's lack of mental toughness and defended his goalkeeper.

Luke Wells, 23, performed well in the T20 Blast, scoring 373 runs at an average of 28.69 and a strike rate of 138.66. He stated that the club is moving in the right direction, with coaches creating an elite performance environment that players want to join.

The Reds, fifth in National Two South, beat third-placed Chinnor 29-12 for their second consecutive win. Coach Churcher praised the front row's performance, noting they made over 70 tackles. The team faces seven teams below them and the league leaders in their next eight games. Churcher believes the performance was emotionally dogged but not complete, and the team must build on this win to avoid it being a waste.

A 74-year-old nun was raped during an attack on a convent in Ranaghat on 14 March, where the building was ransacked and money was stolen. Police have arrested a sixth suspect, 28-year-old Nazrul (Nazu), a Bangladeshi citizen, who was identified from CCTV and named by five previously arrested suspects as the rapist. He was arrested at a Kolkata railway station after a tip-off. Of the eight identified suspects, two remain at large.

This passage describes an interactive video featuring Robert Opie, founder of the Museum of Brands, Packaging and Advertising. The video explains reasons for changes in consumer purchases, citing the domestic freezer, washing powder, and cheaper imports. It also explores the changing ownership and rankings of major UK brands. The passage notes the video may not work on older browsers and provides links to non-interactive content.

Two elderly women, one in Sandyhills and another in Stranraer, were tricked by a caller pretending to be from BT technical support. The scammer claimed there were internet problems, gained remote access to their computers, and stole substantial sums of money. Police warn people to be very careful with cold calls, never grant remote access for alleged faults, and never give out banking details over the phone, as legitimate businesses do not ask for this information.

Duffy, 37, has joined Championship side Featherstone on a one-year contract after leaving Swinton Lions. The Scotland assistant coach will lead the team in their final league game. Featherstone's chairman praised Duffy as a fantastic coach who did a remarkable job at Swinton. Duffy's former assistant, Stuart Littler, has replaced him at Swinton.

A rider with head injuries was found unconscious and cold on Sker Beach. A Porthcawl RNLI crew, a medic, and a coastguard helicopter responded. After treatment, she was airlifted to a Cardiff hospital.

A UN conference has designated a specific radio frequency for a global satellite flight tracking system to address gaps in current ground-based radar, which leaves 70% of airspace uncovered. This decision, prompted by the 2014 disappearance of flight MH370, will allow satellites to receive aircraft location data for real-time worldwide tracking. The UN's aviation agency has set a November 2016 deadline for new guidelines requiring planes to transmit their position at least every 15 minutes.

Julian Hernandez, who disappeared at age five, was found at 18 living with his father in Cleveland. His father, Bobby Hernandez, was arrested after an FBI tip, prompted by issues with Julian's college application, led to his identification. The father is charged with tampering with records and is held on $250,000 bail. Authorities had long suspected the father, who allegedly took his son to pre-school in 2002 and then fled.

A fire on 2 March at a site on Duncan Street run by Recovered Fuels Shipping Limited caused travel disruption. The Environment Agency revoked the firm's environmental permit, suspending it from accepting waste, with an appeal deadline of 7 August. The fire service stated the site operator, Asset and Land Group, had been broadly compliant with fire safety law, but the EA took enforcement action after the fire service raised pre-fire concerns. The company must remove all waste from the site, and the cause of the fire is undetermined.

A pro-Kremlin party in Russia, A Just Russia, has proposed two bills linked to the Ukraine crisis. One bill would simplify the process for Russia to annex territories from a neighboring state that is "disintegrating," using a referendum or a plea from local leaders as justification, specifically mentioning Crimea. The other bill creates a fast-track procedure for Ukrainians to obtain Russian passports, waiving fees, residency requirements, and the need to renounce Ukrainian citizenship. This is framed as protecting Russian-speakers from a "brown threat," a reference to fascists. Russian politicians and celebrities have been active in Crimea promoting these measures.

McLaren, a historically dominant Formula 1 team with 12 drivers' and 8 constructors' championships, is currently in a significant performance slump despite having world champion Fernando Alonso. The team's decline began in 2013 with chassis problems and is now due to an underperforming Honda engine, a stark contrast to their dominant partnership with Honda in the late 1980s. The team's history is a cycle of triumph and decline, and after a disastrous 2013, former boss Ron Dennis returned to lead a revival. Dennis and the team believe they have a competitive car and that Honda will improve the engine, predicting a return to winning multiple championships. However, their current results remain poor, and this belief is all they have to support Alonso's quest for a third title and the team's prestigious reputation.

Thomas Baker, 44, was shot and killed outside Stanley Meat Market in Liverpool on 27 January after leaving a gym. Three men have been arrested. Police are searching for a silver VW Polo that fled the scene and are appealing for witnesses captured on nearby CCTV to come forward.

The passage describes five ways to enjoy a spiritual Christmas online. These include: Everyday Church Online, which streams recorded sermons and has a global congregation; the fantasy game Guardians of Ancora, where children complete Bible-themed quests; popular online nativity videos, such as one told through social media updates; the Manga Messiah, a Manga-style e-book of the nativity available in many languages; and the use of social media platforms like Twitter by churches to share spiritual messages.

An eight-day inquiry in Ebbw Vale is considering a request to use 250 hectares of common land for a development, with backers offering 320 hectares of replacement land. Experts disagree on the environmental impact, with Natural Resources Wales questioning the replacement land's value and an ecology report from the developers claiming a biodiversity net gain, which the wildlife trust disputes. The Planning Inspectorate will make a recommendation before Welsh government ministers give the final decision.

Following a report by Novaya Gazeta on 1 April about the detention and killing of gay men in Chechnya, Chechen Muslim clerics adopted a resolution calling for retribution against the journalists, which the newspaper interpreted as a call for reprisals. The report alleged that over 100 suspected homosexual men were detained, with at least three killed, and that detainees were tortured. Chechen leader Ramzan Kadyrov and his spokesman denied the allegations, claiming there are no gay people in Chechnya. The Russian LGBT Network confirmed the report's accuracy and is helping people flee, accusing Russian authorities of ignoring the abuses and threatening to file a case with the International Criminal Court.

Investing Solutions, a letting agency, and Fresh Start Housing, a charity, both founded by Samir Patel and based in the same building, operate a scheme for housing single homeless men. The agency profits by placing multiple tenants in one property and charging each person's housing benefit, resulting in a total payout significantly higher than the rent paid to the private landlord who owns the property. For example, on one property, the agency claimed £2,114 in benefits but paid the landlord £1,150, yielding a large profit. While legal, the practice is criticized by a homeless group as "a new low." A tenant reported living in poor conditions, and Wandsworth Council paid the agency over £2.1m in two years. The company and charity maintain they are independent and that most of the rent money is passed to landlords.

In a final warm-up game before EuroBasket qualifying, Great Britain's basketball team, coached by Joe Prunty, lost to the Netherlands. Key players were Andrew Lawrence with 14 points and Ben Gordon, who scored 13 points with a run of three three-pointers. Despite leading for most of the first three quarters, GB was overhauled in the final quarter. Prunty stated the team lost some intensity and emphasized the need for complete effort in the upcoming qualifiers, starting in Hungary. He was pleased with Gordon's performance.

Conor McGregor has submitted a waiver to the Nevada Athletic Commission (NAC) requesting to use 8oz gloves for his boxing match against Floyd Mayweather, who also wants to use the lighter gloves. The NAC, which requires 10oz gloves for fights at 154 lbs, will debate the request on 16 August, with fighter safety being its primary concern. NAC executive director Bob Bennett approved the fight after studying McGregor, citing his knockdowns of Nate Diaz, his chin, and his age and size advantage over Mayweather, who hasn't scored a knockout in 10 years. McGregor hired boxing referee Joe Cortez, who described a sparring session with Paulie Malignaggi as "out of control," leading Malignaggi to leave the camp.

Fleet Street, the historic heart of British journalism, has seen its last two reporters, Gavin Sherriff and Darryl Smith of the Dundee-based Sunday Post, leave as their London office closes. For centuries, Fleet Street was the pinnacle for journalists, housing nearly every national newspaper. At its height, it was a vital source of public information, with a vibrant culture centered on pubs and bars where journalists socialized and worked. The street's decline began in 1986 when Rupert Murdoch moved his papers to Wapping, leading to a bitter dispute and prompting other newspapers to adopt cheaper, computerized printing technology elsewhere. The area's iconic buildings have since been repurposed, marking the end of an infamous era in British media history.

J.K. Rowling responded to abusive Twitter comments about her political views, stating she believes in standing up to bullies. She faced criticism for donating £1 million to the campaign against Scottish independence and to the Labour party, and was called a traitor. She blocked abusive users she believed were SNP supporters but also engaged with nice SNP supporters, finding common political ground. She joked about a suggestion to burn her books. The SNP won 56 of 59 Scottish seats, becoming the UK's third-largest party.

A University of Edinburgh study found that poverty is a key factor in youth crime and violence. Children from deprived backgrounds were twice as likely to face police action for the same crimes as better-off children and five times more likely to be placed on statutory supervision. Household poverty increased the likelihood of offending and being a victim of crime, even when other risk factors were considered. Boys were three times more likely than girls to be violent, but poorer girls were twice as likely as affluent girls to commit violent acts. Contact with the justice system was found to exacerbate the conditions leading to violence. A separate report noted that despite falling national crime rates, crime remains concentrated in the most deprived communities, which also suffer from chronic health problems and unemployment. The Scottish government maintains that the country is becoming safer and that it is tackling poverty and inequality.

A 25-year-old man, Karl Haugh, was stabbed to death in Kilkee. Robbie Walsh was charged with assault causing serious harm and remanded in custody. It is alleged he was one of three people who entered an estate looking for Mr. Haugh, a fight involving weapons ensued, and Mr. Haugh was stabbed in the back. Two other men arrested were released, with files for the DPP. Police recovered knives, a golf club, and a bloodied blade at the scene.

In May 2014, Sinn Féin MLA Phil Flanagan posted a tweet falsely implying that MP Tom Elliott had harassed and shot people while serving in the UDR. Flanagan deleted the tweet and was ordered by the High Court to issue a public apology, admitting his statement was untrue and without foundation. The court reserved judgement on compensation, and Flanagan's insurance has refused to cover the costs, a decision he is challenging separately. Elliott stated he felt vindicated by the outcome.

Hawick Knitwear, employing over 230 people, has increased its weekly sweater production from 7,500 to 9,500 due to high demand. This growth is driven by strong sales of its newly launched own brand and its established business of supplying private-label clients. The company, owned by Managing Director Benny Hartop, exports to numerous countries in Europe and North America and is optimistic about its future success.

Sylvia Blackburn, a 72-year-old lollipop lady, was seriously injured when Brian Wright, 55, hit her with his car. Wright claims he was blinded by the setting sun and cannot remember if the traffic light was red, though the prosecution states he failed to stop at a red light. He has expressed remorse for his actions. The incident occurred as Mrs. Blackburn was on duty escorting a woman and child across the road. The trial is ongoing.

A NATO anti-submarine warfare exercise, named "Dynamic Mongoose," is underway in response to growing concerns over increased Russian submarine patrols. The exercise involves 10 NATO warships hunting the German U-boat U33, which acts as a simulated enemy. This highlights a significant gap in Britain's defences, as the UK no longer has its own maritime patrol aircraft and has had to rely on allies when Russian submarines are reported near its waters. Russia has invested heavily in its submarine fleet, which is now considered technologically advanced, quiet, and a challenging adversary. The exercise utilizes warships, helicopters, and for the first time, underwater drones to practice locating submarines, a task likened to finding a needle in a haystack. Analysts state the lack of patrol aircraft is a key vulnerability for the UK, making it a "soft touch," and this issue is expected to be addressed in an upcoming defence review.

A severe humanitarian crisis is escalating in South Sudan, with UN officials warning of potential genocide and ethnic cleansing. Since July, violence has spread, causing over 340,000 people to flee to Uganda, a number surpassing Syrian refugee arrivals in 2016. Refugees report systematic killing, rape, and targeting of civilians along ethnic lines, particularly against Equatorians and the Nuer tribe by Dinka forces. The civil war, initially between the Dinka president and a Nuer former vice-president, expanded to the Equatoria region. Uganda is struggling to cope with the massive influx; while it provides land and aid, supplying essentials like water is a challenge. The UN calls for international pressure on South Sudanese leaders to stop the violence, described as a massacre of civilians.

McKenzie, 38, will fight Jahmaine Smyle for the English super-middleweight title on 12 November at York Hall. A former footballer, he turned professional in 2013 and has a record of eight wins and one draw from nine fights. He is the son of former champion Clinton McKenzie and is trained by his uncle, former world champion Duke McKenzie.

A new £33m Bridgwater Community Hospital will replace the outdated 1813 building. Funded by a £330m national investment and local NHS trusts, it will feature 30 inpatient beds, a midwifery unit, a minor injuries unit, and X-ray facilities. The current building is described as cramped, hard to maintain, and unsuitable for patient recovery. The new hospital, planned for Bowers Lane subject to permission, aims for completion by autumn 2014 and is seen as a major improvement for local care.

A man was fatally shot while in or near his black Mercedes on Daniel Hill Terrace in Upperthorpe. Police found him with a chest wound, and he later died in the hospital. The incident occurred during a family celebration at a nearby home, and relatives rushed to help after hearing the gunshot. This shooting is notable as it occurred near the city centre, unlike a recent series of other shootings which have all taken place in the north of Sheffield.

The passage details the activities of three prominent hacker groups in the Ukraine-Russia conflict. The pro-Ukrainian Ukrainian Cyber Troops, led by Yevhen Dokukin, hack Russian government servers, use DDoS attacks on rebel websites, disrupt separatist funding, hijack CCTV and printers for monitoring and propaganda, and leak data. The pro-Russian Cyber Berkut hacks Ukrainian government websites, disrupts elections, leaks military data, and hijacks electronic billboards for anti-Ukrainian propaganda. Anonymous International, a Russian activist group, publishes leaked Kremlin documents, including material related to the conflict, though its methods are unclear. Ukrainian officials deny using hacker-obtained data for military purposes.

Presiding Officer Tricia Marwick and former First Minister Alex Salmond, who are among several MSPs standing down, gave emotional farewell speeches. Salmond reiterated his belief that Scotland is "diverse, not divided" and that there is a consensus for the parliament to assume greater responsibility, though he insisted the Scotland Bill did not fulfil post-referendum pledges. He concluded by stating serving in parliament was the greatest honor. Duncan McNeil, another departing veteran MSP, warned that Holyrood must learn from Westminster's committee system to ensure proper scrutiny and accountability. Annabel Goldie also gave a valedictory speech, joking about her dealings with John Swinney.

The Older People's Commissioner for Wales is launching a review into the quality of life and care for older people in residential care. The review will gather evidence from residents, their families, and friends to develop recommendations for providers and public bodies. It will assess factors like health, social relationships, and the care home environment. While Care Forum Wales supports the review's aims, it expressed disappointment that the advisory panel does not include an expert with direct experience in running or working in a care home.

In the year to June 2016, Harbro Group, an Aberdeenshire-based animal feed manufacturer and Country Store retailer, increased its pre-tax profit to £3.5m despite a slight drop in turnover to just over £100m. The company reported growth in international sales. While acknowledging challenging market conditions and uncertainty from Brexit, the board expressed confidence in the group's resilience.

A man in his 70s was found dead at a house in Little Gaddesden, and police are treating the death as murder. A second man in his 80s was taken to hospital. Detectives are urgently seeking 55-year-old Ian John McLoughlin for questioning and have issued a physical description and details of his clothing, warning the public not to approach him. Police are conducting additional patrols and have asked anyone with information to contact them.

David Lipton of the IMF stated the global economy is at a delicate juncture with a weakening baseline, likely leading to a downgrade from its 3.4% growth forecast. This follows China's weaker-than-expected trade data, where exports fell sharply, creating on-going ramifications for businesses that bet on its growth.

A council is reviewing a new chain ferry service after a problematic launch involving breakdowns, groundings, and a suspension by the coastguard, which damaged cars and hurt local businesses. The ferry crossing will be free until 2 July, and compensation for businesses is under discussion. While a council leader called the start "frustrating and disappointing," a transport councillor attributed the issues to the vessel being a prototype with expected teething problems, noting that electrical and seamanship issues have been resolved and ramp extensions are being made to prevent vehicle damage.

A multi-vehicle crash on the southbound carriageway near the Hindhead tunnel at Bramshott occurred around 07:30 GMT on Thursday. A 32-year-old man died at the scene, and a 33-year-old man from Waterlooville was arrested on suspicion of causing death by careless driving. The road was closed for investigation until early evening.

Matching Models, a London temp agency, faced criticism for job advertisements specifying physical attributes like "brown long hair with b-c cup" and "sexy female driver," which the Equality and Human Rights Commission and women's campaigners called unlawful, appalling, and sexist. The agency's founder defended the practice, stating that looks are important to their clients, citing examples where clients requested specific physical types. An employment lawyer stated such ads are clearly unlawful and discriminatory, potentially leading to unlimited compensation claims under the 2010 Equality Act. The EHRC warned the agency to change its practices and act like a 21st-century business.

A school office assistant in Bangalore, Mahesh, allegedly shot and injured two students at their hostel, one critically. He was arrested after a manhunt and remanded in custody. Gun crime in Indian schools is rare, and the motive is unclear.

Glaad's annual TV report found a record 278 regular and recurring LGBT characters, with transgender characters increasing from seven to 16. However, the group criticized the high number of lesbian and bisexual female character deaths. It also noted a record high percentage of black characters on broadcast television. While progress was acknowledged, Glaad's president stated that numbers are only part of the story.

David Mackintosh, Conservative MP for Northampton South, announced he will not seek re-election ahead of a local party meeting where his candidacy was expected to be opposed. This follows criticism and a police investigation into a £10.25m loan from the borough council, approved when he was leader, to rebuild Northampton Town FC's stadium. The money is missing, and the football stand remains half-built. A majority of his local party executive had said they would vote to deselect him.

In April, police officer Roy Oliver was fired and charged with murder for fatally shooting 15-year-old Jordan Edwards in Balch Springs. Oliver fired a rifle into a car driving away from a party, which was full of teenagers, including the victim's brothers. Police initially claimed the car reversed aggressively, but footage showed it was driving away. Oliver was also charged with four counts of aggravated assault for the other occupants. He is free on bail and faces 5 to 99 years in prison if convicted, which would be the first murder conviction for a Dallas police officer since 1973.

Melania Trump will delay moving to the White House so her son, Barron, can finish his school year, a decision that has drawn criticism but also support. This is rare, as only two other First Ladies did not reside in the White House, though for different reasons. Historically, some presidential families have also prioritized children's schooling, and the White House has been adapted to family life by others, such as the Obamas, who maintained strict family routines. The role of First Lady is ceremonial and public, and while Melania has indicated her priority is her son and an interest in cyber-bullying, there is precedent for other family members, like a daughter, to help with duties.

A 72-year-old man died in Inverness. The Crown Office has instructed the Police Investigations and Review Commissioner to investigate the initial police response to the man's call before his death. Police Scotland is cooperating, and a report will be sent to the Crown Office.

The Met Office issued a yellow wind warning for parts of west Wales, with gusts potentially reaching 75mph, particularly west of the mountains. The unusual easterly direction of the wind could increase its impact, likely causing travel disruption. Affected counties include Conwy, Anglesey, Gwynedd, Pembrokeshire, Carmarthenshire, Ceredigion, and Powys. Overnight gusts brought a tree down in Menai Bridge, closing Telford Road for most of Monday.

The Belfast Giants, coached by Derrick Walser who also scored, beat the Nottingham Panthers 4-3. The game featured several lead changes, with Nottingham's David Ling scoring a late goal. The teams have a rematch scheduled for Saturday. In the league standings, Nottingham leads with 28 points, followed by Sheffield with 27 and Belfast with 25.

Nico Rosberg won the Chinese Grand Prix, extending his championship lead after winning the first three races of the season. Lewis Hamilton, starting from the back, finished seventh after a first-lap collision and car damage led to multiple pit stops. Sebastian Vettel finished second for Ferrari despite a first-lap collision with his teammate Kimi Raikkonen, who recovered to fifth. Daniil Kvyat took third for Red Bull after an aggressive first-lap move that Vettel criticized. Daniel Ricciardo led initially but a puncture dropped him to fourth. Hamilton now faces a 36-point deficit to Rosberg.

Former German footballer Thomas Hitzlsperger publicly revealed he is gay to advance discussion of a topic ignored in football, making him the most prominent player to do so. His announcement was praised by former teammates, football officials, and politicians as a courageous, watershed moment against homophobia. The article notes that German football has struggled with homophobia, with a previous player warning against coming out and another revealing that gay Bundesliga players are too scared to do so. The hope expressed is that Hitzlsperger's decision will break the taboo and lead to greater openness.

Midfielder Steve Sidwell, 34, has helped Brighton achieve promotion to the Premier League and hopes to sign a new contract. He believes the team can stay in the top flight and that his 32 appearances this season, exceeding expectations, have earned him another opportunity to play in the Premier League. Brighton, led by Chris Hughton, has secured promotion and is close to winning the league title.

Blackpool and Colchester United drew 1-1. Blackpool scored first through Jamille Matt, but Colchester equalized from a corner via Kurtis Guthrie. Colchester's Kurtis Guthrie hit the crossbar just before halftime, and Blackpool's Tom Aldred missed a late headed chance. Colchester finished with ten men after Sean Murray received a straight red card for a foul in injury time.

The 29-year-old player Reid, who previously played for Charlton, Bradford, and Preston, made 37 appearances for the Sky Blues last season before their relegation from League One. He could make his debut for Colchester United in an upcoming EFL Cup match against Aston Villa, following their season-opening 3-1 loss to Accrington.

Following the murder of PC Keith Palmer, a permanent UK police memorial is being established at the National Memorial Arboretum. It will bear the names of over 1,400 officers and staff killed on duty over 250 years. The £4 million project, which includes a £1 million government commitment, is intended as a national tribute to police courage and sacrifice and is expected to be completed by 2019.

Manchester United are 15 points clear at the top of the table with eight games remaining after a 1-0 win at Sunderland. Manager Sir Alex Ferguson stated the team's focus is only on the next game, the derby against Manchester City, and praised the players for a record of 25 wins from 30 matches. The team is also close to breaking Chelsea's record 95-point haul. Ferguson confirmed he will make changes for the upcoming FA Cup replay at Chelsea due to injuries sustained at Sunderland, including to Rafael, Anderson, and David De Gea, and to manage the fitness of players like Wayne Rooney. He credited the win to determined defending and courage.

Google Chairman Eric Schmidt defended the company's tax payments in the UK, stating it paid what was legally required (£10m from 2006-2011) and that governments must change tax laws if they want companies to pay more. He called for international tax reform and said politicians, not companies, should set the rules. Meanwhile, MP Margaret Hodge proposed a new committee to oversee major firms' tax arrangements, and EU leaders agreed to tackle tax avoidance through an automatic information exchange. Google has been criticized for routing UK sales through Ireland to minimize its tax bill.

NHS Improvement is pushing to reduce the £3.6bn annual agency staff bill by £1bn. A cap limiting pay rates to 55% above normal shift rates has saved £600m, but the NHS is still 10% behind its target. The regulator announced it will publish league tables on trust performance and collect data on the highest-earning agency staff, citing examples of hospitals being quoted fees far exceeding the cap. The chief executive stated that more progress is needed to curb these expensive costs.

The Longford Town Centre, a symbol of Ireland's economic crash, is seeing signs of a slow recovery according to local traders. One shop owner reports business is improving after diversifying into new product lines. Politicians are divided on the government's economic strategy for the midlands, with the opposition criticizing the lack of foreign investment in Longford. The government points to a planned Center Parcs development that could create 1,000 jobs, though it awaits planning permission. Local traders believe more could be done to help, such as introducing free parking to attract more shoppers.

A cricket tournament concludes on 29 May with eight teams playing each other twice; the top four qualify for play-offs. Key statistics include Warner as the leading run-scorer (294) and McClenaghan with the most wickets (9). Four England players involved are Morgan, Buttler, Billings, and Pietersen. A schedule of matches from 25 April to 29 May is provided.

The number of plastic carrier bags in England has increased by 200 million since 2013, causing environmental problems as they are often not recycled and end up in dumps and rivers. To address this, a 5p charge will be introduced in England from October to encourage reuse, following the success of similar charges in Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland which led to a decrease in bag usage.

Strong winds in Wales caused significant disruption, including a damaged school roof, power cuts for hundreds of homes, and travel delays on trains and major bridges. Irish Ferries cancelled sailings, and the National Trust closed some properties. The weather also led to the postponement of Rhyl's Boxing Day Dip.

Michael Jordan is starring in the film "Black Panther," directed by Ryan Coogler. He expressed excitement about the project and reuniting with Coogler, as well as working with co-stars Lupita Nyong'o and Chadwick Boseman. The film is scheduled for release in February 2018.

The Alexandra Palace Theatre, founded in 1875, is part of a £26.6m east wing restoration project to create a new cultural destination. The project, funded by an £18.8m Heritage Lottery Fund grant, £6.8m from Haringey Council, and a £1m fundraising target by the Alexandra Park and Palace Charitable Trust, aims to refurbish the theatre and BBC studios. The long-unused theatre, which retains much of its original decor, is planned to reopen in 2018 for performances, cinema, comedy, and live music, while the glazed east court will become a public exhibition space.

James Milner, a 30-year-old former Manchester City player, has retired from international football after winning 61 caps for England since his 2009 debut. He was part of the squad for two World Cups and two European Championships but played only three minutes at Euro 2016. Milner, who is England's most capped Under-21 player with 46 caps, scored his only international goal in a 2014 World Cup qualifier against Moldova.

Marcy Smith and her family escaped their house in Glovertown, Newfoundland and Labrador, after it was destroyed by a fire. The fire was started by rubbish burned in the wood stove, a common practice for the family. Her son David woke everyone after seeing the flames while on a FaceTime call; he is credited with saving his mother and sister. The family's dog and cats perished, and the fire alarm did not sound. The community has since donated clothing and other items to the family, who fled in their pyjamas.

The energy drinks giant Red Bull was reportedly considering a £200m offer for West Ham. The current majority owners, Sullivan and Gold, bought their stake in 2010 when the club was valued at £105m and now own over 85%. The club has also been linked with takeovers from Qatari and Chinese groups since moving to London Stadium. Last year, Sullivan stated that while a minority shareholding might be sold to clear debts, he and Gold intended for their children to inherit the ownership.

The MTV Movie Awards, described as not being the Oscars, was a promotional platform for upcoming summer blockbusters. *The Fault in Our Stars* was the big winner, taking best movie, with Shailene Woodley winning best female performance, the Trailblazer Award, and best kiss. Bradley Cooper won best male performance for *American Sniper*, and Channing Tatum and Meryl Streep won for best comedic performance and best villain, respectively. Kevin Hart received the comedic genius award, and Robert Downey Jr. was honored with the Generation Award. Clips from upcoming summer films like *Pitch Perfect 2*, *Trainwreck*, and *Avengers: Age of Ultron* were shown.

St Mirren manager Jack Ross has signed Cammy Smith on loan from Aberdeen, describing him as a brilliant acquisition and a good attacking option. The 21-year-old Scotland Under-21 player, who previously played for Dundee United, has scored five goals this season. St Mirren, who are bottom of the Championship, play Falkirk next.

Northumberland County Council is using warmer weather to deploy Jetpatcher machines, aiming to fill 145 potholes daily for four months. Extra staff will also repair drainage systems and clear gutters damaged by heavy rain.

In December 2016, six Wood Group contractors on EnQuest's Thistle platform off Shetland were exposed to low levels of naturally occurring radioactive material (NORM) while removing pipework without proper protective equipment. The rigging supervisor, Steve Innes, claimed the company failed in its duty of care, leading to cancer fears and ongoing blood tests for the workers. EnQuest stated the exposure level was less than 1% of the reportable limit, but it informed the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and has since taken additional precautionary steps. Wood Group emphasized its commitment to employee safety and conducted medical assessments. The HSE did not investigate as the incident was not reportable under regulations.

The Asian Civilisation Museum in Singapore is returning a 2007-purchased sculpture of the Hindu goddess Uma Parameshvari to India. The museum bought it for $650,000 from the New York dealer Art of the Past, whose manager later admitted to dealing in stolen Indian antiquities. The sculpture is believed to have been stolen from a temple in Tamil Nadu. The return follows discussions with Indian authorities, and while there is no conclusive proof of the theft, the museum is acting on the dealer's confession. The museum will also pursue legal action for compensation.

A magnitude-4.8 earthquake struck 35km north of Lucca, Italy, at a depth of 15.5km. It was felt in several major cities, including Milan and Florence. There were no immediate reports of injuries or damage, but phone lines and power were cut in the epicenter area of Garfagnana, schools were evacuated, and several aftershocks occurred. The quake was described as a "medium-strong" and "fairly shallow" event typical for the seismically active region, which experienced a deadly magnitude-6 quake in the same area the previous May. The passage also references the 2009 L'Aquila earthquake, where six scientists and an official were convicted of manslaughter for providing falsely reassuring statements about seismic risks before that disaster.

A Sheffield man, Austin Grant, successfully grew a fruit in South Yorkshire's climate, which he had previously doubted was suitable. The 62-year-old was overjoyed to see the fruit, which was still attached to the plant and not yet ripe.

Rockstar has delayed the release of its game from January 27th to March 24th to allow for additional testing and polish. The company also announced that online heists will come to consoles before the PC version. For the PC release, screenshots show greater detail, with support for 1080p at 60fps, up to 4K resolution, and triple monitor setups. Minimum PC specifications have been published. Grand Theft Auto V was the fastest-selling entertainment product upon its original 2013 release.

A 76-year-old artist, Simpson, won the £25,000 John Moores Painting Prize for his work "Squint (19)". He had been shortlisted in 1991 and longlisted three other times. The painting, about 7ft tall, depicts a leper squint from medieval churches. Judge Ansel Krut described it as extraordinary, technically subtle, and a "tone poem" that builds meaning over time. Simpson plans to spend the prize money on art materials. The prize, established in 1957, is one of Britain's oldest art awards.

Two Turkish pro-government newspapers, Yeni Safak and Yeni Akit, were attacked simultaneously by masked assailants early on Thursday. The attackers used guns, shattering windows and leaving bullet casings. There were no casualties, and firefighters extinguished a blaze at Yeni Safak. Police have cordoned off the areas and are hunting the assailants, whom no group has yet claimed.

The 24-year-old player, who was under contract with the Stags and spent the first half of the season on loan at Crawley, will join the Mariners on a free transfer on 1 January, becoming Marcus Bignot's first signing for the club.

Arsene Wenger commented on Gareth Southgate, who is the interim England manager and has upcoming matches to secure the permanent role. Wenger believes Southgate is competent and has the chance to prove his quality. Regarding his own links to the England job, Wenger stated he is focused on his current role at Arsenal. He also announced that defender Hector Bellerin will be offered a new contract to secure his long-term future at the club, dismissing transfer speculation. Additionally, midfielder Aaron Ramsey is expected to miss one or two more games due to a hamstring injury.

A local man fell from a cherry picker while working at Fruehauf on Houghton Road at approximately 13:45 GMT on Thursday. Lincolnshire Police and the Health and Safety Executive are conducting a joint investigation, and the company is fully cooperating.

A new charter arrangement will transfer the operation of two freight vessels, the Hellier and Hildasay, from Seatruck back to Serco Northlink, resolving a dispute over seafarers' pay. The RMT union had claimed some crew were paid under £4 an hour, as Seatruck argued the minimum wage did not apply to non-UK residents. Under the new agreement, all crew will be paid at least the minimum wage, with the change taking effect next month.

Ken Dickie died after an incident at Rockley Park. Jamie Mitchell admitted intervening in an argument between Dickie and his mother, with whom Dickie had a relationship. Both men, who had been drinking, had a confrontation. Mitchell pleaded guilty to common assault. He and his mother also admitted attempting to pervert the course of justice by lying to police about the events. They will be sentenced on 6 February.

Rod Temperton, the British songwriter behind Michael Jackson's hits "Thriller" and "Rock With You," has died of cancer at age 66. He was a low-profile figure nicknamed "The Invisible Man." Starting his career in the disco band Heatwave, for whom he wrote "Boogie Nights," he was later recruited by Quincy Jones. Temperton wrote three songs for Jackson's "Off the Wall" and three for the record-breaking "Thriller" album. His work earned him a Grammy and two Oscar nominations, and he was widely praised by fellow musicians as a genius and prolific songwriter.

A team including researchers from Swansea, Exeter, and Reading universities discovered over 450 ancient, large geometrical earthworks, or geoglyphs, in the Brazilian Amazon. These 2,000-year-old enclosures are not villages or defensive structures and were likely used only sporadically, perhaps as ritual gathering places. Unlike other ritual sites, they were likely hidden by the forest canopy. Analysis of soil and plant fossils indicates the surrounding environment was actively managed by prehistoric people, who created a "prehistoric supermarket" by concentrating useful trees like palms rather than burning large forest tracts. This suggests a long-standing human influence on Amazonian biodiversity.

Nick Kyrgios defeated Sam Querrey in straight sets at the Shanghai Masters, advancing to the second round. Despite his recent Japan Open win and a career-high ranking, Kyrgios stated he felt tired and bored during the match, citing poor sleep and a long commute to the venue. He also referenced a fine he received at the same tournament the previous year for a foul-mouthed outburst.

The HPV vaccine, currently given to girls in Wales to prevent cervical cancer, is also effective against head and neck cancers. Charities and medical organizations are urging the Welsh government to also vaccinate boys, citing rising cases of these cancers, which predominantly affect younger men who are often non-smokers. The Welsh government is awaiting official recommendations before making a decision.

Jak Trueman, a 15-year-old from West Calder High School, has died from a rare blood cancer, gamma delta T-cell lymphoma. He documented his fight against the disease on a popular Facebook page, "Jak's Journey," sharing his positive attitude and personal moments. After being told in January that his cancer was terminal and treatment had stopped, he continued to create memories, including briefly attending a school prom held in his honor just before his death. His story inspired widespread support and fundraising for Leukaemia & Lymphoma Research.

Egypt defeated Uganda 1-0 in a match with few chances. Mohamed Salah assisted Abdallah El Said for the winning goal in the 89th minute. Uganda had a goal disallowed for offside. The result means Egypt will play Ghana for the top spot in Group D, while Uganda is eliminated from the tournament. Ghana secured their quarter-final place earlier with a 1-0 win over Mali.

Lancashire County Council has identified a preferred site for a new railway station in Skelmersdale, a large town without a station since 1956. The site is on land from the former Glenburn Sports College and Skelmersdale College, chosen after a comparative study. The council, in partnership with Merseytravel and West Lancashire Borough Council, plans for two direct trains to Liverpool per hour. The location was selected for its size, allowing for future expansion, good highway access, and connectivity. The council will now begin acquiring the land.
Police discovered an elaborate cannabis grow house in a warehouse near Ashbourne on Saturday morning and arrested a man in his late 40s.

A 28-year-old woman in Hamelin was seriously injured after being dragged by the neck through several streets. Her 38-year-old ex-partner from Bad Muender turned himself in to police. Both are German citizens of Kurdish origin. The woman required emergency surgery and was flown to a specialist clinic. The motive is unknown, and police are investigating and seeking witnesses.

A study of 4,600 Australian workers found that women ask for pay raises as often as men, contradicting the "reticent female" theory. However, when they ask, men are 25% more likely to receive a raise. The research, which controlled for factors like job type and parenthood, found no evidence that women avoid asking due to fear of upsetting their boss. Researchers suggest the results point to possible discrimination against women. A positive finding was that among workers under 40, men and women ask for and receive raises at the same rate, indicating a potential shift in behavior for younger generations.

Oxford City Council has been unable to find a suitable new burial site despite spending money on ground investigations. The two remaining cemeteries in Wolvercote and Botley are expected to be full by 2018 and 2021, respectively. The search is hampered by a lack of suitable land, with potential sites being discounted due to size, ground conditions, a high water table, or legal covenants. Once the cemeteries are full, only reopening family plots, using reserved plots, and interring ashes will be possible. The last time burial space was increased in Oxford was in 1932.

The Hebridean Celtic Festival (HebCelt) in Stornoway from 19-22 July will use an augmented reality app. Visitors can scan items like signs to access online content such as videos and band interviews on their phones. This feature enhances the experience for attendees and allows a global audience to interact with the festival, access information, buy tickets, and get a feel for the event. Acts include The Waterboys, Imelda May, and Peatbog Faeries.

The 10-year-old racehorse Many Clouds collapsed and died after winning the Cotswold Chase at Cheltenham. The British Horseracing Authority confirmed the cause was a rare severe pulmonary haemorrhage, stating such incidents can occur in horses with no underlying health issues. Although the horse had a history of post-race ataxia, he showed no symptoms of it on the day of his death. Trainer Oliver Sherwood described him as the "horse of a lifetime."

A 34-year-old defendant named Davina Ayrton, who was previously known as David, was convicted of raping a 15-year-old girl in a Portsmouth garage in 2004. The defendant, who has learning difficulties and has not undergone physical changes, was remanded into custody and is likely to be held in a male prison. The victim, who had consumed a small amount of alcohol, clearly recalled shouting for the attack to stop while two others slept. Ayrton disclosed the attack to a care home worker in 2014.

Novak Djokovic and his Serbian partner were defeated in the Olympic tennis doubles by Brazilians Marcelo Melo and Bruno Soares. This followed Djokovic's earlier singles loss to Juan Martin del Potro. Djokovic, the world number one, had also suffered a surprise defeat at Wimbledon in July but had since won the Toronto Masters.

The World Porridge Making Championship in Carrbridge attracts over 20 competitors from several countries, including Scotland, England, Ireland, Europe, Canada, and the US. Participants can only use chainsaws to carve logs into shapes of animals or people. Last year's winner, Pete Bowsher from Moffat, is returning to defend his title and the Claymore Trophy.

Welsh rugby player Rhys Webb is close to returning from a serious foot injury suffered in September, aiming to be fit for the Six Nations in February. He has renewed his dual contract with Ospreys and the Welsh Rugby Union, turning down other offers to stay with his home region, a decision he believes gives him the best chance to play for Wales.

US border agents near Sumas, Washington, interrupted a drug smuggling attempt, leading to a suspect firing at agents and fleeing. Four people were arrested: Jeffrey Laviolette and Nathan Hall, who were carrying 58lb of ecstasy; and Kali Henifin and Ryan Lambert, who were to transport the drugs to San Francisco. The suspects face conspiracy and drug charges. The area is a known smuggling route.

Childline counselled over 4,500 children for online abuse in the past year, a significant rise from 2011-12, with victims as young as seven. The NSPCC and Childline's president, Dame Esther Rantzen, stress that cyber-bullying is a serious persecution that continues beyond school, requires adult intervention, and does not stop on its own. The report, released for Anti-Bullying Week, calls for schools to take the issue seriously and for children to seek help.

Following a U.S. decision not to veto a UN Security Council resolution condemning Israeli settlements, Israel postponed a vote on nearly 500 new settlement homes in East Jerusalem. The move, requested by Prime Minister Netanyahu's office, was to avoid further straining relations with Washington ahead of a key speech by US Secretary of State John Kerry. Israel, which rejected the resolution and recalled some ambassadors, was angered by U.S. abstention, accusing the White House of orchestrating the resolution, a claim the U.S. denied. The resolution declared settlements a flagrant violation of international law and a major obstacle to peace.

In a BBC interview ahead of the Queen's 90th birthday, Prince William paid tribute to her as a "guiding example" of duty and service. A new stamp featuring four generations of royals was released to mark the occasion. The Queen undertook several birthday events, including visiting a postal office and opening a bandstand. Prince William also addressed recent "work-shy" criticisms, stating he takes his duties seriously but is developing into the role at his own pace with the support of his family. He aims to live as normal a life as possible for now and cited the Queen as his best role model. Further celebrations included the Queen lighting a beacon and a lunch with the Obamas. The republican group Republic criticized the level of media coverage for the birthday.

West Ham United, a Premier League side, defeated League Two's Cheltenham Town 2-0 in an EFL Cup match. Goals from Diafra Sakho and Andre Ayew in the first half secured the win. Despite a respectful performance from Cheltenham, they did not sufficiently test West Ham's goalkeeper. West Ham could have won by a larger margin, with Cheltenham's keeper making a good save and a defender clearing a header off the line. The result ended League Two's representation in the competition.

A 36-year-old hospital radiographer, Aidan McNicholl, died in a motorcycle collision. Andreas Werner, 46, pleaded guilty to causing death by careless driving after failing to see the motorcyclist. He was fined £1,000 and banned from driving in the UK for two years. The victim's family did not want Werner jailed, accepting the crash was a momentary lapse, and Werner expressed remorse.

Imran Khawaja, a 27-year-old from London, is a dangerous British jihadist who fought in Syria with the Rayat al Tawheed group, which is affiliated with Islamic State. He was a prominent online propagandist, posting videos and images of his life, including a gruesome photo of himself holding a severed head. He faked his own death online to sneak back into the UK but was arrested upon arrival at Dover. Khawaja has admitted to four terrorism offences, and his cousin pleaded guilty to assisting him. He was considered so high-risk he was held in a special unit at Belmarsh prison.

Kayden Jackson, 22, scored four goals in 36 appearances for Wrexham last season. He has signed for Barnsley, becoming their third signing ahead of their League One play-off final. Jackson turned down a new contract from Wrexham, and Barnsley's caretaker manager believes his pace and style will suit the team.

Sealed bottles of Vanish detergent are washing up on Cornish beaches after a container, possibly lost from the MV Blue Ocean in May, fell from a ship. The National Trust is clearing them due to the risk of leakage and potential harm to sensitive marine life. The public is warned not to touch the bottles.
A crash on the A9 north of Berriedale in Caithness resulted in several minor injuries. The road was closed with diversions via the A897, and police inquiries are ongoing.

Dorian Dervite, a 28-year-old French centre-back, has signed a new contract with Bolton Wanderers after helping them gain promotion to the Championship. He made 14 appearances last season, contributing significantly towards the end of the campaign. Having joined from Charlton in 2014, he has made 83 total appearances for the club. He is among other players like David Wheater, Gary Madine, and Jem Karacan who have also signed new contracts.

The Liberal Democrats and Labour, who had previously allied to defeat the government on Brexit amendments regarding EU citizens and parliamentary approval, have split after MPs rejected those changes. The Lib Dems wanted to insist on the amendments, while Labour deferred to the Commons. Each party accused the other of bad faith; Labour called the Lib Dem actions "grandstanding" for campaign leaflets, while the Lib Dems accused Labour of enabling a "hard Brexit." Despite this Brexit-related tension, the two parties have a history of cooperating on other issues, and while future collaboration on shared issues is expected, a Labour source predicted "residual tensions" would remain.

Defence is a low electoral priority, with public opinion showing combat fatigue and parties offering little manifesto detail. Despite a more dangerous world, UK defence spending is falling, with the army shrinking and equipment gaps emerging. The UK is set to fall below the NATO 2% GDP spending target, risking its credibility with the US. Further budget cuts are expected, but political commitments to renew Trident and increase equipment spending make savings difficult. The Trident renewal is contentious, with parties divided on maintaining a continuous at-sea deterrent. New aircraft carriers may become a "hollow force" due to crew and aircraft shortages, making it harder for the UK to maintain its global military role.

Barcelona has made an additional tax payment of €13.5 million related to the signing of Neymar, while denying any wrongdoing and insisting their original payment was correct. The total cost of the transfer, including fees and wages, is £106.8m. A Spanish judge is investigating the deal, and former president Sandro Rosell resigned over accusations of misappropriating money. The club made the payment to cover potential divergent interpretations of the contracts and to defend its reputation.

Michael Luciw, a 27-year-old father, was killed in a motorway collision caused by Albert Kenneth Newman, who was driving the wrong way and also died. Mr. Luciw's family and the surviving driver, Andy Harrington, advocate for mandatory driving tests or medical examinations for older drivers to prevent such incidents. The UK's DVLA stated it has no plans for age-based restrictions, citing a lack of evidence that older drivers cause more serious accidents and noting that drivers over 70 must self-report medical conditions. The charity Age UK emphasized the importance of supporting older people to drive safely for as long as possible to maintain their independence.

An independent review of transvaginal mesh implants in Scotland, which concluded the procedures should not be routinely offered for pelvic organ prolapse and recommended better patient information and mandatory reporting of side effects, is itself being investigated. Professor Alison Britton will examine the review process after its controversial final report caused two patient representatives and a consultant to resign, claiming it was watered-down. The health secretary confirmed the recommendations would be implemented but said the Scottish government lacks the power to ban the procedures. Over 20,000 women in Scotland have had the implants, with many suffering complications, and over 400 are taking legal action.

Laura Muir broke Yvonne McColgan's 25-year-old 5,000m indoor record by 14 seconds with a time of 14:49.12. McColgan expressed excitement about her record being broken by a fellow Scot and praised Muir's world-class ability, predicting she could run even faster. She initially raised concerns about the race's validity, as Muir was the only 5K competitor in a mixed race and questioned drug testing protocols. However, British Athletics confirmed the time is expected to be officially ratified, noting that drug tests are not required if there was no doping control at the event. McColgan compared the solo run to her own record-breaking race and emphasized Muir's potential to win world medals with improved race tactics.

Michael Jung of Germany won the Olympic gold medal in equestrian, riding Sam as a replacement horse. France's Astier Nicolas took silver and American Phillip Dutton won bronze. Great Britain's William Fox-Pitt, competing ten months after a serious fall, finished 12th. He led after the first phase but dropped in the standings after a disappointing cross-country performance. Ireland's Jonty Evans finished ninth.

Andy Murray defeated Fabio Fognini in four sets, 6-2, 4-6, 6-1, 7-5, to reach the fourth round of Wimbledon. The match was tense and included a dramatic fourth set where Fognini failed to convert five set points. Murray will next play Benoit Paire. In another result, Johanna Konta also advanced to the second week. Murray acknowledged the match was up and down and he was pleased to avoid a fifth set, which would have required the roof to be closed or the match to resume the next day.

Paramedics attended a sudden death at Joe's Bar in Dungiven on 6 October 2014. Police found people still at the bar, with receipts showing alcohol served until 04:49 BST. The license holder, Colleen O'Neill, was charged with two counts and James Thomas with one count of allowing liquor consumption outside licensing hours. A defence solicitor admitted the laws were not strictly followed. The judge, noting O'Neill's "appalling record," ordered the bar's closure for three months. O'Neill was fined £3,000 and Thomas was fined £1,000.

Mike Nesbitt, leader of the Ulster Unionists, launched the party's manifesto, "Real Partnership," and stated his preference for a post-election partnership with the nationalist SDLP over Sinn Féin. He defended his controversial remarks about vote transfers, denying any regret, and said his position had received support. The party wants the election to be a referendum on the DUP and Sinn Féin's handling of the Renewable Heat Incentive scandal, which it characterizes as incompetence, arrogance, and cronyism. The manifesto includes policies on health, police numbers, infrastructure, LGBT rights, and Brexit.

Northern Ireland's Justice Minister will bring a motion before the assembly to pardon men, both living and deceased, who were convicted of now-abolished sexual offences. This will align Northern Ireland with the "Turing's Law" provisions in England and Wales. The move aims to ensure equal treatment and right past wrongs through a faster process than a full assembly bill.

Laura Muir broke the Scottish 1500m record with a time of 4:19.12, finishing second to Faith Kipyegon. This erases Yvonne Murray's 1994 record and places Muir second on the British all-time list. Muir, who holds both Scottish 1500m and mile records, was pleased with her first race of the season at that distance. She aims to secure a place for the Rio Olympics at the upcoming British trials and will next compete in Stockholm. Muir fits her training around her veterinary studies, having recently completed her fourth year.

In the 2006 London poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko, a Met Police barrister stated the Russian state was likely the plot's sponsor, though not necessarily President Putin personally. The two suspects, Dmitry Kovtun and Andrei Lugovoi, poisoned Litvinenko with polonium-210, leaving a radioactive trail. They had no personal motive, but Litvinenko's defection and attacks on Putin were possible state motives. The suspects deny wrongdoing, remain in Russia, and are unlikely to be extradited for trial.

Following Michael Clarke's retirement, Steve Smith, at 26, has been appointed captain of Australia's Test, one-day, and Twenty20 cricket teams. David Warner, despite past disciplinary issues, was named vice-captain. National selector Rod Marsh praised Smith as a highly-regarded and talented leader and noted Warner's maturity. Smith had previously captained the team in three Tests.

During his leadership campaign, Tim Farron refused to directly answer whether he believed homosexual sex was a sin, instead stating "we are all sinners." He asserted he is "passionate about LGBT-plus rights" and that defending equal marriage would be a top priority, including extending rights for transgender people by addressing the spousal veto. He defended his 2007 vote against the Equality Bill by citing concerns for "protection of individual liberties," but did not specify what those were, while affirming his support for equal legal access for all people regardless of sexuality.

The French pharmaceutical company Sanofi closed its Fawdon manufacturing site in 2015, resulting in 450 job losses. Accord Healthcare will now use the plant for its own pharmaceutical production and hopes to hire many former Sanofi employees. The investment is expected to have a very positive impact on the local economy and strengthen the region's reputation in the science and healthcare sector. Accord is a global firm that develops and distributes over 130 products to about 60 countries.

Three senior officials are leaving the local council: Richard Ellis at the end of his contract, and Ciaran Monaghan and Ewan Sutherland through voluntary redundancy and early retirement. The opposition leader claims this shows the council's inability to retain senior staff and expects more departures. The council's chief executive thanked the three for their service.

Militants attacked a hospital in Kabul, killing and wounding dozens. The so-called Islamic State (IS) claimed responsibility, while the Taliban denied involvement. The assault, which involved explosives and gunmen, was the first time IS directly engaged security forces in the capital, marking a change in tactics. The attack suggests IS may have the resources and training to expand its operations. Over 50 people were wounded, and Afghan commandos killed all four attackers after a hours-long siege.

English rider Guy Martin is quitting road racing on Hondas for the year after a crash and the bike's mechanical problems made the TT a "bloody disaster." He clarified he has not quit racing entirely but has no plans for road races on Hondas. His team withdrew him from the Ulster Grand Prix after he told them the bike wouldn't be competitive. Martin now wants to race classics and "oddball stuff."

The All Progressives Congress (APC) won 19 of 28 declared governor posts, inflicting the biggest defeat on the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) since 1999. The PDP, which also lost the presidential election, was relegated to a regional party, winning only eight governorships mostly in the south-east. The APC made historic gains in the north and retained Lagos, but failed to win any of Nigeria's five oil-producing states, a concern for incoming President Muhammadu Buhari. The elections were marred by violence, though less than in previous years. The PDP's decline is attributed to voter desire for change, defections to the APC, and allegations of corruption and mishandling the Islamist insurgency.

The environmental group Mighty accuses the agricultural trader Olam and its major shareholder, Singapore's Temasek, of enabling unsustainable palm oil practices that contribute to regional haze. Mighty alleges Olam created a secretive market for rogue suppliers and that its activities in Gabon involve bulldozing rainforests. Both Olam and Temasek reject the allegations. Olam defends its "no burn" sourcing policy, acknowledges it buys from third-party suppliers, and is vetting them, a process that will take years. Temasek states it supports no-burn policies but does not direct Olam's operations. The palm oil industry is globally contentious, facing accusations of environmental damage and unfair labor practices.
A restaurant started serving puppy platters after a new law permitted dogs to eat at outdoor restaurant areas.
Fernando Forestieri is a doubt with a knee issue, while David Nugent may return from a groin injury. Jacob Butterfield is hoping for a recall after scoring as a substitute.

Pakistan's ban on YouTube, imposed in 2012 after protests over the "Innocence of Muslims" film, has been lifted. The telecom regulator stated this was because Google launched a Pakistan-specific version of YouTube, providing a process for authorities to request the blocking of offending material. However, YouTube denied that authorities can filter content directly, stating it will only restrict access to videos deemed illegal in Pakistan after its own review and in accordance with its guidelines. While welcomed by many, some activists are demanding greater transparency about the deal's terms.

Domenico Scala, head of Fifa's Ad-Hoc Electoral Committee, faces calls to resign because he shares Swiss-Italian nationality with presidential candidate Gianni Infantino. Liberian FA president Musa Bility argues this is a conflict of interest, citing a rule that requires committee members with such a conflict to step down, as Scala did in the 2015 election when Sepp Blatter was a Swiss candidate. Scala's spokesman contends there is no conflict of interest in the current election because there is no incumbent president and the regulations contain no such provision; Scala's previous withdrawal was a voluntary, precautionary measure. Bility has threatened to take the case to the Court of Arbitration for Sport if Scala does not withdraw. The election to replace Blatter is scheduled for 26 February.

Two men, Daniel Timbers, 29, and Barry Joy, 56, were killed in an explosion at Harford Attachments. Evidence suggests a flashover explosion occurred from a build-up of toxic fumes and an ignition source, causing a fireball. A forensic search has been conducted, and the Health and Safety Executive is investigating.

Tunisia faced potential expulsion from the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations for lodging complaints against the Confederation of African Football (Caf) after a controversial quarter-final loss to Equatorial Guinea in 2015. After a meeting with Caf, Tunisia apologized, resolving the issue. Separately, Morocco's ban from the 2017 qualifiers was overturned by the Court of Arbitration for Sport (Cas), which also reduced a fine. Morocco was originally punished for refusing to host the 2015 tournament due to Ebola fears. Both nations are now in the qualifying draw; Tunisia is in Group A and Morocco in Group F.

Manchester City has been charged for failing to control its players after a mass confrontation in their 3-1 loss to Chelsea. City's Sergio Aguero received a four-match ban for a dangerous tackle, and Fernandinho was banned for three matches for his role in the ensuing scuffle. City manager Pep Guardiola apologized, and the club has until 8 December to respond to the charge. Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas faces no further action.

Wales has some of the worst cancer survival rates in the developed world. A new pilot scheme in Cynon Valley and Neath focuses on patients suspected of having cancer but without urgent symptoms, who often face long waits for diagnosis as they don't fit a specific treatment pathway. This leads to multiple tests over several weeks, risking treatment starting only after the cancer has advanced. The scheme allows 40 GPs to refer such patients to a diagnostic centre for various tests, aiming for same-day assessment and a diagnosis within seven days. Currently, only 35% of patients with "worrying symptoms" in the Cwm Taf area receive a diagnosis. A similar clinic will be established in Neath Port Talbot. The trials were developed after Welsh officials visited Denmark, which improved its cancer survival rates by establishing diagnostic centres. The goal is to provide peace of mind and a faster process, enabling earlier diagnosis. If the six-month Cynon Valley pilot is successful, other local health boards will offer the same service.

England defeated Pakistan by a large margin at Old Trafford to level the Test series. Joe Root was named man of the match for his first-innings 254 and all-round performance, with captain Alastair Cook praising his responsibility at number three. After a poor first Test, Root said he focused on cutting out errors. Analysts credited England's disciplined batting and bowling, while noting Pakistan's broken spirit and poor shot selection. Pakistan's captain Misbah-ul-Haq acknowledged the disappointment but expressed hope his team would work hard to rebound in the remaining Tests.

Warren Gatland is leading the British and Irish Lions in New Zealand, so interim coach Rob Howley is unavailable. Forwards coach Robin McBryde will be the head coach for Wales' summer tour, a role he has filled twice before. The Welsh Rugby Union is finalizing the appointment of assistant coaches. WRU officials believe this opportunity for Welsh coaches to work in different environments, especially the challenging Lions tour to New Zealand, will develop them and benefit Welsh rugby in the future.

Hull City came from behind to beat Southampton 2-1, ending a six-game losing streak. Southampton took an early lead with a Charlie Austin penalty, but Hull's fortunes changed after losing two strikers to first-half injuries. Substitute Robert Snodgrass, returning from injury, equalized and then provided an assist for Michael Dawson's headed goal within two second-half minutes. Hull's goalkeeper David Marshall made crucial late saves, and Sam Clucas produced a remarkable goalline clearance in added time to secure the win.

A motorcyclist was killed in a collision with a tractor on the B1191 near Woodhall Spa at approximately 14:15 BST. The motorcyclist was local, and the tractor driver was unhurt. Police are appealing for witnesses, and the road was closed between the B1192 and A158 junctions.

Macedonian President Ivanov cancelled an investigation into abuse of power claims from covert recordings to "put an end to the agony" before early elections. The opposition and EU officials condemned the move, with the EU stating it jeopardized Macedonia's membership ambitions. The crisis began in 2015 when opposition leader Zoran Zaev released recordings allegedly showing government corruption, vote-rigging, and murder cover-ups. The government denies the accusations and claims Zaev is trying to destabilize the country.

Following Bob Bradley's sacking, Curtis and Paul Williams will manage Swansea's next match. The club aims to appoint a new manager quickly, with Paul Clement as the preferred candidate. Curtis expressed concern about the difficulty of avoiding relegation and the even greater challenge of returning to the Premier League if they are relegated, citing the Championship's increased strength. He believes the club has lost its identity, the "Swansea Way," since Michael Laudrup's departure in 2014, due to frequent managerial changes and a failure to adequately replace key players. Despite this, Curtis thinks the current squad is capable of avoiding relegation and ensures new players understand the club's history and the importance of staying up.

Dagenham & Redbridge were relegated to the National League after a 3-2 loss to Leyton Orient. Despite goals from Jamie Cureton and Clevid Dikamona, Armand Gnanduillet's winner confirmed their drop. Dagenham, who have the worst goal difference in League Two and have struggled defensively and offensively, will be managed by John Still in their bid for promotion next season. The victory keeps Leyton Orient's play-off hopes alive, leaving them two points from the spots. This comes after their player-manager Kevin Nolan was recently removed, with interim manager Andy Hessenthaler stating the team must win games to reach the play-offs.

Steven Gerrard, the former Liverpool captain, is returning to the club as a youth coach in February for his first job since retiring. Manager Jurgen Klopp endorsed the appointment, noting Gerrard's ambition to be a future manager and his need to learn the role. Gerrard, who had a 19-year playing career and won multiple trophies with Liverpool, recently retired after playing for LA Galaxy. He turned down the MK Dons manager job, feeling it was too soon, and is working towards his Uefa A coaching licence.

Morton defeated Alloa 4-1. McManus scored the opening goal, Ross Forbes doubled the lead, and a Kyle McAusland strike brought Alloa back before half-time. McManus scored again and Denny Johnstone added a late goal to secure a comfortable win for Morton.

Ofsted has found children being taught in squalid conditions in unregistered schools, with three in Birmingham now closed. The Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, believes these cases are the "tip of the iceberg" and is concerned about the risk of abuse and radicalisation. Anyone running an illegal school could face up to 51 weeks in jail. While many of the 18 schools investigated are in Muslim communities, the crackdown will apply to all religious groups. The government is funding a team of inspectors to investigate such schools and is consulting on plans for more regulation. The Education Secretary has asked Ofsted to prepare prosecution cases and has stated that a single day in an unregistered school is unacceptable.

Lilliard Gin is based at the Born in the Borders visitor centre in Jedburgh and is a small-scale operation using one of the UK's smallest stills in a cowshed. It aims to capture the local flavour of the Scottish Borders by using regional botanicals from the Teviot valley. The distillery is a companion to the on-site Scottish Borders Brewery and is the first new distillery in the region in nearly 200 years. The gin is named after Lilliard, a legendary female figure from the 1545 Battle of Ancrum Moor, reflecting both the landscape and the distillery's strong female production team.

Gary Green, who was more than twice the legal alcohol limit, reversed a tractor into Harry Whitlam on private land, killing him. Green was jailed for 16 months and two weeks after admitting a health and safety offense, as the incident occurred on private property. Harry's mother stated the family has been changed forever and hopes to remember the good times. The HSE inspector described Green's behavior as reckless.

Luis Suarez's appeal to the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) partially succeeded. His four-month ban from all football-related activities was modified; he is now allowed to train with his new club, Barcelona, and play in friendly matches for both club and country. However, his nine-match competitive international ban and his suspension from official matches remain in effect. CAS ruled the original total ban was excessive, but FIFA's sanctions were otherwise generally confirmed. Suarez, a repeat offender for biting, is likely to make his competitive Barcelona debut in late October.

Richard Blake-Smith and his partner Anna won a race by beating a Lithuanian couple. They trained for a week and were pushed hard by their competitors. The race involved a 380-meter course with haystack hurdles, a steep slope, and water pistols. It was open to all couples, not just married ones, and featured various carrying combinations. The winners will compete at the World Championships in Finland.

The paper car tax disc system will be replaced by an electronic system in October 2014, allowing payment by monthly direct debit. Minister Stephen Hammond stated this would change job roles at the DVLA and reduce the need for some positions, but any reductions would be managed through redeployment to other areas, not redundancies. This assurance was welcomed by Mike Hedges, who believed it would comfort DVLA employees despite fewer job opportunities.

Hungary's government, led by Viktor Orban, is refusing to change three laws criticized by the EU: tight controls on asylum seekers, a higher education law threatening the Central European University, and draft legislation targeting NGOs. The government considers these domestic issues and says Poland will veto any EU attempt to strip Hungary of its voting rights. The EU has warned of potential action, while thousands of Hungarians have protested the laws.

Emma Watson will play Belle, with Dan Stevens as the Beast and Luke Evans as Gaston, in Disney's live-action "Beauty and the Beast." The cast also includes Ewan McGregor as Mrs. Potts, Kevin Kline as Maurice, and Josh Gad as LeFou. Directed by Bill Condon, filming begins in May at Shepperton Studios for a 17 March 2017 US release.

Adrian Gill, a prominent and celebrated Sunday Times columnist, has died. He had been diagnosed with a widespread cancer, which he described as the "full English," and was undergoing chemotherapy. The Sunday Times editor called him a "giant among journalists" and the "heart and soul" of the paper, praising his wit, dazzling writing, and compassion.
