Gill was known for his brilliant but often controversial writing style, which sometimes provoked outrage. He overcame dyslexia to build his career, often dictating his copy. He was married twice, first to author Cressida Connolly and then to Amber Rudd, with whom he had two children. His illness prompted his engagement to his long-term partner, Nicola Formby, with whom he also had two children.

Mongolian rapper Amarmandakh Sukhbaatar (Amraa) was allegedly attacked after a performance in Ulan Bator, leaving him in a coma for about 10 days with serious brain injuries. The suspected attacker is a Russian diplomatic officer. The rapper had performed wearing a traditional Mongolian robe embroidered with a swastika, a pre-Hitler symbol of eternity in Mongolia, which his father defended as not being a hate symbol. The Russian embassy is investigating but called local press reports "distorted." Mongolian police stated the suspect was not detained because the injury was not considered serious, denying it was due to diplomatic immunity. The rapper's representatives denied reports he shouted "Heil Hitler" at the show.

On Monday, members of the group Plane Stupid staged a protest on the northern runway of an airport at 03:30 BST, opposing expansion plans. Several protesters were charged with aggravated trespass and entering a restricted area. They are due in court on 19 August, and police will review airport security.

In a County Championship match, Glamorgan scored 220, built around Nick Selman's century of 101. Gloucestershire's seamers, Matt Taylor and Craig Miles, took regular wickets in bowler-friendly conditions. Gloucestershire then faced a difficult batting period in the evening, leaving the match evenly poised. Selman commented on his return to form after a poor run, while Taylor was pleased with the bowling performance.

Craig Hughes, 33, was arrested after making online threats to a crisis center while drunk, admitting to planning a false police report to ambush and shoot officers on the Dee Estuary. He has a previous firearm conviction and was on bail for a separate firearms case at the time, for which he was later cleared. Hughes, who was remanded in custody, claimed he never intended to carry out the threats.

Surrey scored 255-7 in their innings, propelled by a 130-run partnership between Davies and Ben Foakes. Yorkshire's chase of 256 was derailed by a three-wicket burst from Stuart Meaker, which included the key wickets of Jonny Bairstow and Gary Ballance. Despite 68 from Tim Bresnan, Yorkshire were all out for 236, losing the match. Yorkshire's captain expressed disappointment that his team fell short in a crucial game, while Surrey's captain praised the match-winning partnership and his team's collective effort.
A 56ft converted trawler, 6 miles west of South Stack, radioed for help at 07:00 BST as its pump was failing. The RNLI lifeboat provided a pump and towed the vessel to Holyhead.

Middle-distance runner Laura Muir will miss the 2018 Commonwealth Games due to a scheduling conflict with her final-year veterinary medicine exams. The 24-year-old Scot, who recently set a personal best in the 5,000m at the World Championships, is prioritizing her degree. She is, however, targeting the World Indoor Championships and believes she has the potential for two or three more Olympic Games.

Liverpool are struggling to replicate last season's form due to a significant drop in goals after selling Luis Suarez and losing Daniel Sturridge to injury, with their new strikers lacking both goals and work-rate. The team's intensity and high-pressing game have diminished, and they are no longer scoring many first-half goals. Defensively, they remain weak and lack a leader, despite heavy investment. Pundit Robbie Savage believes they are miles away from a title challenge and that a top-four finish should be considered a success. For the upcoming Chelsea match, he suggests dropping defender Dejan Lovren and selecting Fabio Borini for his energy, but still predicts a loss as Chelsea are on a "different planet." He also discusses Steven Gerrard's future, stating the player is still vital for Liverpool but faces a mental and physical battle to extend his career.

A £45m campus will be built in Kilmarnock, housing primary, secondary, and Gaelic schools, and a childcare centre. East Ayrshire Council will ask the McIlvanney family for permission to name it after the Kilmarnock-born writer, William McIlvanney. He was a former English teacher, the "Godfather of Tartan Noir," and author of the Laidlaw trilogy, who was passionate about education.

A sea mine from the 1940s or 1950s was discovered near Gourock, prompting the evacuation of three streets and safety advice for residents within 500 meters. An exclusion zone was established on the river and at sea, causing ferry disruptions. The Royal Navy moved the deteriorated mine, which had an unknown amount of explosives, to a safer location for disposal. Authorities stressed the evacuation was precautionary and thanked the public for their patience.

UK Sport has allocated £345 million for the 2020 Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games, a £2 million decrease from the Rio cycle. The funding cuts have led to several sports, including archery, fencing, and badminton, losing all financial support, despite badminton winning a bronze medal in Rio. Cycling's funding was also cut by over £4 million. UK Sport has set medal targets of 51-85 for the Olympics and 115-162 for the Paralympics, aiming to maintain the historic success achieved in Rio. The decisions were made to prioritize sports with the highest medal potential, a strategy defended by UK Sport and the sports minister. Some team sports, like basketball, have criticized the approach, arguing it neglects their development. Funding for newly added Olympic and Paralympic sports is yet to be confirmed, with £9 million still to be allocated.

A six-storey hotel and two assisted-living apartment blocks will replace three Victorian hotels in Bournemouth's East Cliff conservation area. The council approved the plan seven to three, citing tourism benefits and that the old buildings were no longer functional, despite objections from English Heritage and others who argued the development's scale would cause severe harm to the historic area.

Off-duty soldier Pte Matthew Boyd, 20, was beaten to death by Jake Vallely during a night out in Brecon. Vallely, who had been on a seven-hour drinking binge, punched the soldier and continued the attack after he fell to the ground. He then dragged Boyd's body away and fled. The attack occurred on 8 May as Pte Boyd was returning to his barracks. A friend of Vallely's, Aaeron Evans, was cleared of manslaughter as he was not present during the assault. Vallely will be sentenced on 8 December. Police described the killing as a "despicable act" that shocked the community, and Pte Boyd's family paid tribute to him as a loving and promising young man whose loss has left an unfillable void.

Andrew Travers, Barnet Council's chief executive, left by "mutual agreement" following a major polling error on election day where voters were turned away because their names were missing from the lists. An independent investigation has been launched to review the incident and the arrangements for the upcoming EU Referendum. The council apologized and offered emergency proxy votes, but voters questioned the fairness of the result. Deputy chief executive John Hooton will serve as temporary replacement.

Gateshead defeated Wrexham 2-1. Josh Gillies scored first for Gateshead with a free-kick, but Wrexham equalized before half-time through a Sean Newton set-piece. Ryan Bowman headed in a cross for Gateshead's winning goal. Gateshead's manager credited his team's improved second-half passing, while Wrexham's manager was disappointed with his team's second-half performance and missed chances.
The 2014 Global AgeWatch Index ranks the social and economic welfare of older people in 96 countries, with Norway as the top country and Afghanistan as the worst, followed by Mozambique.

The OneWeb project, a joint venture between Airbus and OneWeb, aims to create a global broadband internet constellation of at least 600 and eventually over 2,000 satellites. To achieve this, Airbus has revolutionized satellite manufacturing by adopting high-volume, low-cost assembly line methods, aiming to produce satellites for under a million dollars each. The first assembly line is in Toulouse, with another planned in Florida. The satellites will be launched in large batches using over 20 Soyuz rockets, with the goal of having nearly 300 in orbit by late 2020/early 2021. OneWeb has raised $1.7bn and claims a first-mover advantage over competitors like SpaceX. The project is licensed by the UK Space Agency and has committed to aggressive debris mitigation, including de-orbiting satellites within two years and including hardware for potential active removal. While this new manufacturing model is disruptive, Airbus acknowledges that bespoke, "gold-plated" satellites will still be needed for specialized missions.

Scottish Finance Minister John Swinney stated that UK government spending cuts are placing unprecedented pressure on Scotland's budget, projecting a 12.5% real-terms reduction by 2019-20, with over £1bn in cuts still to come. He committed to protecting schools, hospitals, and police from these austerity measures. The UK government responded that Scotland will have £390m more to spend next year and that its block grant is secure, criticizing the Scottish government for grievance over constitutional issues. Scottish Labour criticized the government's budget plans as posturing and called for a long-term budget with different tax decisions.

Standard accessible toilets are inadequate for many people with severe disabilities who require carer assistance, hoists, or changing benches. Campaigners are calling for Changing Places toilets—larger facilities with enhanced equipment—to be made compulsory in new, larger public buildings, as current UK building standards only recommend them. This lack of suitable facilities causes significant stress, isolation, and feelings of devaluation for affected individuals and their families, forcing them to change on dirty floors. While some venues have successfully installed these toilets, logistical and financial barriers often prevent their inclusion in existing buildings.

Italian consumer groups have filed an antitrust complaint with the European Commission, accusing McDonald's of abusing its market dominance by forcing franchisees to pay excessive rents and fees and sign long contracts, which allegedly limits competition and raises prices. McDonald's defends its practice of sharing risks and rewards with franchisees. The complaint is supported by unions, and the European Commission will study the submission to decide on an investigation.

A social media campaign, #prayforjosh, was started by Bangor Elim Church to support 13-year-old Joshua Martin from Donaghadee, County Down, after he was diagnosed with cancer on Christmas Eve. The campaign went viral, with a church update being shared widely and seen by over 79,000 people globally. A mystery donor paid for a billboard with the hashtag to be erected in Holywood. The campaign has generated worldwide support for Josh and his family.

The UK government plans to close Brecon Barracks as part of a military reorganization in Wales. Local MP Chris Davies condemned the closure, citing the barracks' historic significance since 1805, its role in the local economy, and high unemployment in the area. He is launching a petition against the decision. The Defence Secretary announced a new specialist light infantry centre will be created at St Athan, and the closures of Cawdor Barracks and a Sennybridge depot were confirmed. While Labour's Shadow Defence Secretary agreed with restructuring, she warned of the "gnawing uncertainty" closures cause for local communities.

A House of Lords report warns that the UK fishing industry, which heavily supported Brexit to escape the EU's Common Fisheries Policy, risks being marginalized in wider Brexit negotiations despite its small economic contribution. The industry hopes to regain control of UK waters, but the report highlights complications: most fish stocks are shared with the EU, the UK relies on the EU market for exports, and continued market access may require trade-offs, such as allowing EU boats to fish in UK waters. The report also states that some elements of the CFP should be retained, and leaving the EU could create four separate fisheries management regimes in the UK. Despite the risks, many in the industry remain optimistic about the opportunities Brexit presents.

Edward Snowden, a former CIA technical worker, leaked documents revealing extensive US government surveillance programs. The NSA had massive access to phone records, internet data, chat logs, and social networking information through a program called Prism, which allegedly provided "backdoor" access to servers of major tech companies like Google, Facebook, and Apple. The US government confirmed collecting millions of phone records and defended the programs as vital for national security, arguing they prevent terrorism. Officials stated that only suspected individuals are targeted, but critics and privacy advocates expressed concern over the scale of the surveillance and the potential for privacy violations, especially since data stored by US companies can be accessed by US authorities under laws like the Patriot Act, affecting users worldwide.

OpenAI is a research venture backed by Elon Musk, Peter Thiel, Infosys, and Amazon Web Services, with $1 billion pledged, though only a small fraction will be spent initially. Its goal is to advance digital intelligence for the benefit of humanity, free from financial obligations. While scientists like Musk and Stephen Hawking have warned that AI could be an existential threat by surpassing humans, other experts believe the threat is remote. OpenAI aims to ensure AI is safe and broadly distributed.

L/Bdr Ben Parkinson, seriously injured in a 2006 Afghanistan bomb attack, carried the Olympic torch in 2012. Despite a brain injury that initially took his speech, he walked with the torch using crutches and an assistant. His nomination highlighted his determination, unchanged personality, and his work raising money for military charities like the Pilgrim Bandits. After the event, he received thousands of Facebook friend requests, overwhelming the 5,000-friend limit, and an outpouring of public support through emails and post. His mother described him as elated by the response. Facebook suggested he use a public page or subscribe feature instead of a personal profile.

In 2011, the U.S. poverty rate was 15%, with 46.2 million Americans in poverty, remaining unchanged after three years of increases. The real median household income dropped by 1.5%, and income inequality, measured by the Gini index, rose by 1.6% for the first time since 1993. The percentage of Americans without health insurance fell to 15.7% from 16.3%. The previous year, 2010, had seen a record high poverty rate of 15.1%.

Jos Buttler, a short-format specialist, signed a new deal with Lancashire in 2013, keeping him at the club until 2019. He holds the record for England's three fastest ODI centuries. Lancashire's coach praised his talent, his role in winning the T20 Blast, and his positive presence in the squad. After playing in the Indian Premier League, Buttler will return to Lancashire for a T20 game.

Four decommissioned Type 22 frigates are for sale in Portsmouth Harbour, with no preservation bids submitted. The government aims to sell at least one to a UK ship recycler to test the industry's capacity. Bids are being finalized, with a decision expected in spring. MP Penny Mordaunt supports UK recyclers but also advocates turning one ship into a diving reef for tourism. The Ministry of Defence seeks the best financial return and will not comment on bids due to commercial sensitivity. These frigates were versatile combat ships with a crew of 280.

Since 1987, racial and political tensions in Fiji have caused instability and international isolation. A 1987 coup by indigenous Fijians overthrew an Indian-dominated government, leading to a constitution that granted political supremacy to indigenous Fijians and subsequent economic harm. Another coup in 2000 held the ethnic Indian prime minister hostage, further damaging the economy and Fiji's reputation. Tensions culminated in a 2006 military coup. In 2009, Fiji was suspended from the Commonwealth for a lack of democratic progress but was reinstated after agreeing to and holding elections in 2014. The population is divided between indigenous Fijians, who now form a small majority, and Indo-Fijians, with minimal mixing and deep segregation. Fiji's diverse economy relies on sugar, tourism, mining, and services but is hampered by trade and budget deficits, making it a large per capita recipient of aid.

Syria missed a deadline to hand over its chemical weapons stockpile, blaming attacks on a shipment by "terrorist groups" and stating it is committed to the UN-backed plan despite the war. The US expressed concern over the slow progress. Meanwhile, the Syrian government denied US accusations of using barrel bombs on civilians in Aleppo, despite activist groups reporting hundreds of casualties. The government also denied that rebels had seized a central prison in Aleppo, though opposition groups claimed control after freeing detainees.

The Man Booker Prize shortlist for 2014 features six authors: three British (Howard Jacobson, Ali Smith, Joshua Ferris), two American (Karen Joy Fowler, Joshua Ferris), and one Australian (Richard Flanagan). The favourite to win is Neel Mukherjee's "The Lives of Others," a family saga set in 1960s Calcutta. The other shortlisted books are Jacobson's futuristic "J," Smith's dual-narrative "How To Be Both," Ferris's "To Rise Again at a Decent Hour" about a dentist and online identity, Fowler's bestselling "We Are All Completely Beside Ourselves" about a unique family, and Flanagan's WWII love story "The Narrow Road to the Deep North." This is the first year the prize is open to all authors writing in English. The winner will be announced at a ceremony in London.

A celebrity, PJS, is appealing to the Supreme Court to maintain an anonymity injunction preventing The Sun on Sunday from publishing an account of his alleged extramarital activities. The Court of Appeal had lifted the ban, ruling that because the story was already widespread online and in other countries, confidentiality was lost and a permanent injunction was unlikely. An interim injunction remains in place until the Supreme Court hearing, where it will decide whether to hear the appeal and, if so, rule on its outcome. PJS argues for his right to privacy, while the newspaper argues the injunction is ineffective.

Fosse Park, a shopping center near the M1, was purchased for £345.5 million. The new owners are planning improvements to address parking, traffic congestion, and the site's tired appearance, which includes the backs of buildings currently visible. Both the council and the owners see this as an investment to enhance the area's quality and facilities.

The live-action "Beauty and the Beast" film's release in Malaysia was delayed for a content review due to a "gay moment" involving the character LeFou. The Malaysian Censorship Board later approved the film for a P13 rating with a minor edit to that scene, as homosexual activity is illegal in the country. Cinema chains offered refunds for pre-purchased tickets, and the decision to review the film was met with public criticism.

Many landlords in Southampton are not applying for the required House of Multiple Occupation (HMO) licence, which costs around £1,000, despite facing fines up to £20,000. The council estimates 1,500 unlicensed HMOs exist. A housing adviser notes tenants in such properties often fear eviction and live in poor conditions due to a lack of affordable homes. Licensing applies to specific areas of Southampton designated in 2013 and 2015. While most landlords cooperate, the council has prosecuted one firm and 13 individuals.

Following the Irish election, Fine Gael and Fianna Fáil are negotiating to avoid a second election. Fianna Fáil will facilitate a minority government but not support its program, with water charges being a major point of disagreement. Fianna Fáil wants to abolish the charges immediately, while Fine Gael supports them. A commission on the future of Irish Water is being considered.

The ferry Sorrento caught fire on a car deck while traveling to Valencia, forcing a full evacuation of passengers and crew onto lifeboats. They were rescued by another ship, the Puglia, and are being taken back to Palma de Mallorca. At least three people were injured, one seriously, and the ship is at risk of sinking. The cause of the fire is unknown.

The Electoral Commission reported concerns about duplicate voter registrations and potential double voting, a criminal offence, following the 2017 general election. A record 46.8 million people were registered, with a high turnout of 68.7%. The online registration system, used by the majority, is not linked to the separate databases of local electoral registers, making it impossible to check for duplicates. This led to an estimated 30-70% of the 4.9 million applications being duplicates, creating administrative burdens. The Commission recommended linking the systems and providing online verification. Labour warned against making registration harder for students and others who may legitimately need to be registered at two addresses, while agreeing that voting twice in a general election is a serious offence.

Lawrence Phillips, a former University of Nebraska and NFL star, died by suicide at age 40 while in prison. His football career, which included playing for the Rams, Dolphins, and 49ers, was plagued by off-field troubles. After his NFL career ended, he was convicted of multiple assaults, including driving into a group of teenagers and assaulting a former girlfriend, resulting in a prison sentence of over 30 years. He was awaiting trial for the murder of his cellmate at the time of his death. His former coach described him as intelligent but troubled by anger issues and personal demons.

Private Derby XXX, a Swaledale ram and the mascot for the Mercian Regiment, was promoted to lance corporal for good behaviour at an event in Chester. He is the 30th ram in a mascot lineage dating back to 1858. As a soldier, he has an army number, is paid for rations, and takes holidays during mating season. His public appearances include switching on Christmas lights in Ashbourne and meeting Prince William.

Liverpool defeated Borussia Dortmund 4-3 in a dramatic Europa League quarter-final, overturning a two-goal deficit with a last-minute winner from Dejan Lovren. The victory, inspired by manager Jürgen Klopp's philosophy of turning "doubters into believers," evoked memories of the club's historic 2005 Champions League comeback. The match featured an electric atmosphere at Anfield, with Liverpool's resilience overcoming a brilliant Dortmund side. The win advances Liverpool to the semi-finals, moving them closer to a potential trophy and qualification for the Champions League, while also showcasing Klopp's successful imprint on the team.

Following a meeting on EU negotiations, UK minister David Davis stated the government would keep Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland updated through regular meetings and a "two-way information flow." He described the meeting as constructive. Scottish minister Michael Russell welcomed the involvement but criticized the UK government's lack of transparency on its strategic intentions, specifically regarding single market or customs union membership, which he called essential for Scotland. The Scottish government will also oppose the UK government's appeal in the Supreme Court regarding the triggering of Article 50.

A flock of 13 cloned sheep, including four that are genetically identical to Dolly the sheep, are being studied to determine if cloning causes premature aging. The research, led by Professor Kevin Sinclair, involves exhaustive health tests for age-related conditions like osteoarthritis, cardiovascular disease, and diabetes. This is to address concerns that cloned animals might inherit "age-memory" from their donor cells, potentially leading to health problems at a younger age. While Dolly died at six-and-a-half with osteoarthritis, these clones, now nine or ten years old, currently appear to be in good health. The study's results, which could significantly impact the future of cloning, are due to be published.

Shutter Speed, trained by John Gosden and ridden by Frankie Dettori, won the Musidora Stakes on soft ground. She will next race in the French Oaks at Chantilly, while stablemates Enable and Coronet will run in the longer Epsom Oaks. In the same race meeting, Tasleet won the Duke of York Stakes. Gosden is undecided about running his colt Cracksman in Thursday's Dante Stakes due to the soft ground and the short 16-day gap before the Derby.

The pound experienced significant volatility, falling against the dollar, euro, and yen, as investor uncertainty, measured by a volatility index, hit levels not seen since 2008. This was driven by polls showing the Leave campaign gaining ground ahead of the EU referendum, reducing the implied probability of a Remain vote. Analysts predicted increased market volatility as the vote approached. Hedge funds were short-selling the pound, and Asian stock markets fell sharply. The FTSE 100 also closed lower. Leave campaigners argued the pound's drop was a return to March levels and that a weaker currency benefits exporters.

The Iron are sixth in the National League, one point outside the play-offs, after a loss to Barrow that extended their losing run to three games. Manager Cowley acknowledged the challenge of conceding early after a long journey but remained positive, calling the team's season so far remarkable. He emphasized they are a part-time team facing their toughest challenge but are embracing it.

A significant change will transfer planning decision powers from the Stormont Planning Service to local councils in April 2015, putting elected politicians in charge. Supporters see this as a positive democratic move allowing local development plans. However, critics, citing past discrimination in the 1960s, warn of potential favoritism and close developer-politician relationships. Friends of the Earth calls for rigorous transparency and a code of conduct, while the debate on political donation disclosure continues due to security and relevance concerns.

A one-year-old cat named Teenie was shot three times with an air gun, requiring her leg to be amputated. The Scottish SPCA and the cat's owner condemned the attack and urged witnesses to come forward. The incident prompted the Scottish SPCA to call for the urgent licensing of air guns, a measure the Scottish government had previously consulted on. However, that consultation found 87% of respondents opposed the licensing plan, which would require a legitimate reason to own an air gun.

Christian Benteke has signed a long-term contract with Liverpool, becoming their second most expensive signing. The 24-year-old Belgian striker, who scored 49 goals in 101 games for Aston Villa, was signed to address Liverpool's lack of goals last season. Manager Brendan Rodgers added Benteke, along with other forwards Danny Ings and Roberto Firmino, to revive the team's attack. Former Villa manager Paul Lambert believes Benteke, a "brilliant number nine," will succeed with good service. Former Liverpool striker John Aldridge is also optimistic, citing Benteke's presence, strength, and aggression as assets the team has been missing.

A study found no clear evidence that tablet devices improve academic results, but their use in schools is rapidly increasing. Tablets are used in about 68% of primary and 69% of secondary schools, with the highest use in academies. The number of tablets in schools is expected to double between 2014 and 2016. While researchers cannot isolate technology as a cause for improved attainment, head teachers report a positive impact, including increased pupil motivation and family involvement. The study also highlights how immersed young people are in technology, with many using internet-connected devices in bed for social media. A separate study suggested touch-screen computers are useful for helping boys and poorer pupils learn to read. A head teacher advocate argues tablets create a sense of empowerment for pupils and prepare them for the modern world.

The exhibition "Growing Up in the City" at the Museum of Liverpool features 25 photographs from the 1880s to the 1990s, depicting the changing experiences of childhood in the city. The images capture children at play, during special occasions, and also at work, providing a social history that includes both positive and difficult aspects of childhood. Curator Kay Jones selected the photos to show how life for children has changed while also highlighting universal experiences.

Torquay United (the Gulls) have signed two players. Centre-back Myles Anderson, 27, joined from National League rivals Barrow and could play against them on 18 February. Striker Ruairi Keating, 21, was recommended by Micky Adams and his move is pending international clearance. Manager Kevin Nicholson described Anderson as a needed leader and Keating as young and hungry. The team is four points above the relegation zone with one win in their last six games.

Bolivia has passed a law permitting 12-year-olds to work with parental authorization, defended by the government as a necessary measure reflecting the country's poverty and reality, where over 500,000 children already work. The law also sets harsher punishments, including a 30-year sentence for child homicide. While the International Labour Organisation sets a minimum working age of 14 for developing countries and is studying the law for potential breaches, Bolivia's government argues it balances international treaties with the need to eradicate extreme poverty.

A 50-year-old woman, Rosie O'Donnell, had a heart attack at home after helping someone. She looked up "women's heart attack symptoms" online, which included nausea and aches, and took aspirin. She did not call emergency services. The next day, a cardiologist inserted a stent into a 99% blocked artery, a type of heart attack known as the "widow maker." On her blog, she warned women to know the symptoms and call 911.

Che Labastide-Wellington was stabbed and killed at a party in Kenton after a group of youths tried to gain entry. A 16-year-old was also stabbed and is in stable condition. Police believe Che was not involved in the initial altercation but was targeted later. A 21-year-old man has been arrested on suspicion of murder, two boys aged 15 and 16 were arrested and bailed, and a 14-year-old was arrested for possession of an offensive weapon.

A Welsh team visited Denmark to study its reformed cancer diagnosis system, implemented after poor survival rates were linked to long waiting times. The Danish model has three pathways: a fast-track for clear cancer symptoms; diagnostic centers for patients with non-specific symptoms to receive comprehensive testing and avoid delays; and "yes-no" centers for minor symptoms to quickly rule out serious disease. The system, which operates within existing resources, has improved organization, collaboration between GPs and specialists, and survival rates, with Denmark now catching up to other Scandinavian countries.

A new team at Powys council will take over the role of issuing warnings and banning orders against dishonest estate agents or those breaching the Estate Agents Act, replacing the disbanded OFT. Powys will receive £170,000 annually for this work. Complaints will still be made to local trading standards, who will prosecute and refer relevant cases to Powys.

A plan to reshape the NHS workforce by having nurses and pharmacists take on extra tasks, such as filling in for doctors, has been approved. A Nuffield Trust review supported the move to address staff shortages and the changing nature of patient care, but noted funding for training is required. Unions and the British Medical Association warned against using this as a quick, cheap fix, cautioning it must not replace doctor training or compromise the expertise doctors provide.

A collision on the Lower Bristol Road in Bath led to the A36's closure from 03:00 GMT until 14:00 GMT, causing significant travel disruption. Investigations into the crash are ongoing. First bus services experienced delays but were partially restored, with the company aiming for a full service for the evening commute and thanking the public and staff.

A dispute exists between Tidal Lagoon Power (TLP) and Natural Resources Wales (NRW) over the environmental impact of the Swansea tidal lagoon project. NRW estimates the lagoon would cause annual deaths of 21% of salmon and 25% of sea trout, citing the "best available evidence." TLP disputes these figures, calling them unrealistic and lacking a clear scientific basis, and claims its own modeling shows a worst-case scenario of 2% fish mortality. TLP also states NRW refused to share its methodology. NRW strongly disagrees with the criticism, asserting it has shared extensive information and methodology with TLP and is confident in its evidence. The UK government is reviewing the project's viability, while the Welsh Government is supportive but seeks clarity from the UK government.

Northern Ireland's Enterprise Minister announced the creation of a new industry-led agri-food marketing body, to be developed by the Agri-Food Strategy Board. Modeled on Scotland Food and Drink, the body aims to provide strategic leadership and improve coordination of marketing for the sector, which supports nearly 100,000 jobs. While the Agriculture Minister welcomed the move as positive for export-led growth, she noted it could have implications for other organisations, including her department, and looked forward to further discussions.

The Woodland Trust is creating Brackfield Wood in the Faughan Valley as part of a four-year UK-wide project to plant millions of native trees commemorating the millions who died in WW1. On a specific Saturday, the public is invited to help plant 40,000 trees, a tribute to the 40,000 from Ireland who lost their lives. The aim is to create a woodland with wildflowers where wildlife can thrive and people can visit. The trees will serve as a lasting tribute to the Irish soldiers, families, and loved ones affected by the war.

Hilary won the Theakstons Old Peculier Crime Novel of the Year Award for "Someone Else's Skin," a thriller about domestic violence and honour crime that was praised as emotionally powerful, finely written, and well-plotted. Sara Paretsky received an outstanding contribution award for her 23-year career creating the groundbreaking female private investigator VI Warshawski, a character who changed perceptions of female protagonists. Paretsky also founded Sisters in Crime to support female crime writers. The awards were presented at the Harrogate crime writing festival.

Cricketer Mitch Santner will return to Worcestershire for the 2017 season after an injury in his second game for the county in 2016 cut his previous stint short. The team's director of cricket stated his absence was a major blow to their qualification hopes. Santner, a left-arm batsman and spinner, will rejoin after the ICC Trophy in June, hoping to make an impact. Separately, the county also signed Australian bowler John Hastings as their main overseas player for 2017.

Barry Pring was killed in 2008 in Kiev when a speeding car with stolen plates hit him as he hailed a taxi. A UK coroner recorded a verdict of unlawful killing, stating the evidence was overwhelming. His wife, Ganna Ziuzina, who was 19 years younger, had left the scene to retrieve a glove. The inquest heard she tried to claim his assets days after his death, sold his possessions, and was having an affair. Mr. Pring's family and a friend believe he was murdered in a staged accident so she could inherit his money. Ukrainian police have an active, but not actively pursued, murder inquiry.

Charlie Fearns, a boy from Merseyside, urgently needs experimental T-Cell Therapy in Seattle, USA, as it is unavailable in the UK after his third relapse. An anonymous donor has paid for the treatment after his first transplant failed, which his parents described as overwhelming and for which they are extremely grateful. The family received financial clearance from the hospital and expects to learn the treatment date soon.

Apple has enhanced its iCloud security following the theft of celebrities' intimate photos, closing a loophole that allowed third-party software to download backups even when two-step verification was enabled. The new security measure, which remains an opt-in feature, now requires a verification code for iCloud access on new devices, blocking the previous method used by Elcomsoft's software. While the software's owner acknowledged the fix is secure, he expressed concerns about users losing their 14-character recovery key. Security experts argue that two-factor authentication should be the default setting for all major tech companies, not just an option. Apple's CEO stated the company plans to more aggressively encourage users to enable this feature and use stronger passwords.

A deal is being discussed for Mark Wright to buy 20% of Billericay Town FC and become a club director. The club, recently taken over by multi-millionaire Glenn Tamplin, is eighth in the Isthmian League Premier Division. Tamplin has stated he is comfortable investing £10,000 a week, and the club has signed former England player Paul Konchesky.

MP Iain Wright has written to Mike Ashley, requesting he give evidence before the Business, Innovation and Skills select committee about working practices at his company's warehouse. The committee had declined Ashley's invitation for a private meeting, insisting on a public hearing at Westminster. Ashley has until 21 March to agree to one of the offered dates or the committee may pursue a complaint of contempt with the House of Commons. Sports Direct has previously pledged to review worker rights.

A report titled "Putin. War," initiated by the murdered opposition politician Boris Nemtsov and completed by his associate Ilya Yashin, accuses President Vladimir Putin of waging war in Ukraine to boost his popularity. It compiles publicly available evidence, including testimony from Russian soldiers who admit they were directed into Ukraine by Russian generals, not separatists, and details the human and economic cost of the conflict. The report documents military units and weaponry, and calculates Russian spending. Despite this evidence, the authors acknowledge the difficulty of distribution and public outreach in Russia, where many are aware of but accept their country's involvement, and where previous critical reports by Nemtsov failed to galvanize significant protest.
A 34-year-old man, Craig Nelson, was found dead with head injuries at the Woodhead Tunnels in Derbyshire. A 41-year-old man and a 23-year-old woman have been arrested in connection with his death.

Carwyn Jones, the Welsh First Minister, criticized the UK government for not consulting devolved administrations on the draft of the Article 50 letter, calling it a "lack of respect." In response, Welsh Secretary Alun Cairns defended the process, stating the government must act for the whole UK. While the Prime Minister's letter promised a "significant increase" in devolved powers, specific powers like farming and economic aid were not detailed. There is also uncertainty over whether funding will follow these powers after 2020.

Two cars were damaged in an attack on police officers carrying out duties in the Nursery Drive and Parkhead area of Newry on Friday night. A senior police official condemned the mindless attacks on officers and the community, and an appeal was made for parents to know their children's whereabouts.

Mr. Charney, the founder of American Apparel, was ousted as CEO following employee complaints and accusations of misusing company funds. The board stated he would not return, citing court filings with evidence of illicit emails and racially derogatory taunts that violated company policy. Charney sued the company for defamation, and his lawyer called the accusations false and an invasion of privacy. The board argued no company would hire him due to the risk. A restraining order was granted preventing Charney from making negative statements about the company or trying to remove board members.

The Great Britain (GB) basketball team will play a home game against Greece at the Copper Box in London. This is GB's only home game before the FIBA EuroBasket 2017 tournament. GB lost to Greece earlier in the month, but three Greek players will be missing for this rematch. The game will be broadcast on BBC iPlayer and the BBC Sport website. After this, the team will travel to a tournament in Poland for their final warm-up games.

The author recounts being one of the first journalists to handle the iPhone at its 2007 launch, facing criticism for the BBC's prominent coverage. He initially regretted comparing its significance to the Model T Ford but now believes the comparison is valid. The smartphone has been the transformative technology of the last decade, putting powerful computers in over two billion people's hands and disrupting industries like photography. While other phones had similar features, the iPhone's attractive user interface was the key innovation that began the mobile connected era.

A series of cat deaths in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, has been confirmed by the RSPCA as poisonings from a toxic substance, identified in at least one case as antifreeze. Seven-month-old Meereen died, bringing the total to at least five cats in recent weeks. The RSPCA is uncertain if the poisonings are accidental or deliberate and is appealing to the public to safely store and clean up chemicals like antifreeze and pesticides.

Despite agreeing to implement harsh austerity measures it once opposed, the Syriza government faces no public protests in Greece. This calm may precede the revelation of Prime Minister Tsipras's significant concessions to secure an €86bn bailout. His popularity remains high even though his standoff with creditors led to both fiscal and monetary austerity, creating a severe economic squeeze that will further impoverish Greeks. The new bailout will only succeed if creditors, especially Germany, offer substantial debt forgiveness to provide hope for recovery, avoiding triumphalism over Greece's capitulation.

Actor Ross Kemp is making a brief return to the BBC soap "EastEnders" as Grant Mitchell for the final episodes of Dame Barbara Windsor's character, Peggy Mitchell. Peggy is being written out of the show after her character's cancer returns, and she will die from the disease in scenes to be screened in the spring. Kemp, a close friend of Windsor, stated he could not turn down the opportunity to reunite the Mitchell brothers with their mother one last time. Executive producer Dominic Treadwell-Collins confirmed the return, noting it will show the brothers facing the loss of their mother and reuniting with old loves.

Lance Corporal Trimaan "Harry" Dhillon was found guilty of murdering Alice Ruggles after stalking and becoming obsessed with her. Her parents described knowing it was Dhillon when police informed them of her death and expressed deep guilt for not taking the threat more seriously, having reassured their daughter and dismissed another daughter's warning. The parents have established the Alice Ruggles Trust to raise awareness about the dangers of stalking. Dhillon was sentenced to a minimum of 22 years in prison.

The UK government has delayed signing the final contracts for the £18bn Hinkley Point C nuclear power station, despite the French firm EDF approving the funding. The government announced a surprise review of the project just hours after EDF's board vote, causing uncertainty. EDF's CEO cancelled a trip to the site following the announcement. The project, which is expected to provide 7% of the UK's electricity, is one-third financed by Chinese investors. Critics have raised concerns about escalating costs, environmental damage, and EDF's financial capacity, which has led to internal resignations. Supporters warn further delays risk future energy supplies and climate commitments.

A new divorce application form in England and Wales asks for the name of the person a spouse committed adultery with, though guidance states it is not normally necessary. Family lawyers are concerned the prominent question will encourage people to name the third party, which increases conflict, complexity, and potential costs, and can delay proceedings. While the Ministry of Justice states there is no obligation to provide the name, lawyers report many clients want to involve the new partner, a move that is frowned upon by judges.

The UK is a major wood importer, and the Welsh forestry industry, worth over £450 million annually, faces a conflict between commercial and environmental priorities. The industry group Confor warns that Wales has lost significant commercial forest area since 2001 and that current planting rates of 90 hectares per year are far below the 20,000 hectares needed to meet long-term timber demand. The Welsh government aims for a balanced strategy that supports the economy, environment, and social access, but commercial foresters believe environmental goals are prioritized, creating a bureaucratic system that hinders the creation of new commercial woodlands.

A boy was seriously injured after being struck in Coatbridge on Bank Street near Langloan Primary School. Emergency services were called around 16:40, and the boy was taken to Queen Elizabeth University Hospital in Glasgow.

Russian Defence Attaché Capt Oleg Kornienko presented Ushakov medals to British veterans of the Arctic Convoys, which supplied the Soviet Union during World War II. The convoys were extremely perilous, facing German attacks and harsh Arctic conditions, resulting in the loss of over 100 ships and thousands of Allied seamen. The UK Foreign Office initially blocked the Russian award, citing rules against foreign medals for events over five years old, but made an exception in 2013, allowing President Putin to present the first medals. The Russian Embassy stated the convoys were a material expression of the wartime alliance that provided crucial weapons.

A report by HM Inspectorate of Probation found significant problems in the enforcement of unpaid "community payback" sentences for offenders. Key issues included major delays in starting work and offenders not facing consequences for non-attendance, with one case cited of only 16 hours completed in 17 months. Inspectors made 15 recommendations for improvement, noting that the sentences were often viewed merely as punishment rather than an opportunity for rehabilitation. While some high-quality work was praised, the overall management was deemed not good enough. The Ministry of Justice accepted all the report's recommendations and stated it was taking urgent action to implement them, emphasizing that it is unacceptable for offenders to skip court-enforced work.

A newspaper called a wealthy comedian a "hypocrite" for campaigning for an economic revolution to help the poor while living in a luxury home, an accusation he frequently faces. When questioned about his own expensive London property, he called a reporter "a snide" and walked off. The comedian has previously acknowledged the charge of hypocrisy, admitting he is rich and must change personally, including by sharing wealth. However, he argues that personal change is insufficient without systemic change to address economic disparity and ecological disaster, and that the focus on his hypocrisy is an attempt to keep the issue of inequality off the agenda.

Dr. Craig Venter, a biologist and entrepreneur, accelerated the mapping of the human genome through a competitive, private approach that drew criticism from the scientific community. His career was shaped by a sense of urgency from his service in Vietnam. Key achievements include developing faster gene sequencing methods, publishing the first complete genome of a free-living organism, and, through his institute, creating the first synthetic life form, Synthia. He has also led a global project to sequence marine microbes. Despite controversy, his work aims to use synthetic biology for industrial applications and environmental solutions.

A survey of 1,000 parents in England, commissioned by the School Food Trust, found that four out of five children who ate school lunches tried new foods there that they had not tried at home, with half of parents reporting their children then requested these foods at home. The most popular vegetables were carrots, sweetcorn, and peas, while aubergine, chickpeas, and spinach were among the least popular. The research was initiated after concerns that parents provided packed lunches due to children being fussy eaters. Experts noted that school meals, which now follow strict nutritional guidelines, help children try new foods through peer pressure and offer healthier, more varied options than in the past. About 40% of primary school children in England eat school lunches.

Álvaro Morata, a 23-year-old Spanish striker at Euro 2016, moved from Real Madrid to Juventus in 2014. The transfer included a buy-back clause for Real, reportedly up to €30m. In two years with Juventus, he scored 27 goals, won two Serie A titles and two Coppa Italias, and played in two Champions League finals, scoring in the 2015 final. He began his career at Real Madrid, making his debut at 18 and scoring 10 goals for the club.

Harry Wilson rejoined Nottingham Forest from Celtic for £2.5 million in August 2013. He was released in May and is currently without a team. In his second spell at Forest, he made 51 appearances. The 30-year-old has also played for Preston North End and Notts County.

Tesco is making an orderly exit from the US market by selling its loss-making Fresh & Easy chain to Yucaipa, a private equity firm run by Ron Burkle. As part of the deal, Tesco will loan the new business around £80m, and 4,000 of the 5,000 employees will transfer. The remaining 50 stores will be closed, costing Tesco £150m, though part of that is a loan that may be repaid. Tesco has the option to buy a stake in the business if it becomes profitable.
The athlete faced racial abuse but overcame it and, after considering representing France, is now aiming for a medal at the 2016 Rio Olympics.

A new inventory of French Alps glaciers shows their area shrank from about 375 sq km in the late 1960s/early 1970s to about 275 sq km in the late 2000s, a 26% loss over 40 years. The retreat has accelerated since the mid-1980s and is not uniform, with the greatest losses occurring in the southern massifs like Belledonne and Ecrins. This is attributed to the south's lower mountain elevations and different climatic conditions, including less precipitation and cloud cover compared to the northern Mont Blanc Massif.

The Scotland women's national football team is on the verge of qualifying for a major tournament, leading their qualifying group with five wins. A crucial match against Iceland, who are also unbeaten, will likely decide the group winner. Player Claire Evans expressed the team's desperation to qualify after recent near-misses. She believes the growing number of Scottish players gaining experience in top foreign leagues, including herself in Germany, is benefiting the national team by bringing new skills and competitiveness.

Stuart Campbell, a Scottish independence blogger, was arrested in England for alleged online harassment following a complaint from a woman in London about tweets over a two-year period. He was released on bail. Campbell stated the allegations concern only non-threatening tweets and accused the media of using innuendo. Police confirmed they are investigating the allegation.

Peta has called for Skegness to replace its Jolly Fisherman mascot, arguing it represents cruelty to fish and suggesting a new fish logo with the slogan "Skegness - A Happy Plaice." The mayor of Skegness, Carl Macey, stated that while all suggestions are welcome, he believes the mascot is widely loved and not seen as promoting animal cruelty. He expressed doubt that there would be much support for the change, noting the council would review the idea but that "if it isn't broken we won't try and fix it." The original Jolly Fisherman poster was commissioned in 1908 by the Great Northern Railway.

Scotland defeated Georgia in a rugby match, scoring six tries to Georgia's two. After conceding an early try to Georgia's Vasil Lobzhanidze, Scotland took control, racing to a 24-11 halftime lead with tries from Tommy Seymour, a penalty try, Sean Maitland, and Stuart Hogg. Hamish Watson scored soon after halftime. Georgia scored a second try through Lobzhanidze from a dominant scrum, but Scotland finished strongly with Hogg scoring his second try from a counter-attack. Greig Laidlaw kicked multiple conversions. Scotland's coach Vern Cotter praised the first-half performance and his team's pragmatic management of the game.

Widnes defeated Castleford in a rugby match, taking a 14-6 half-time lead and extending it to 38-12 in the second half. Despite a late surge of three tries from Castleford in four minutes, Widnes held on to win. The result moved Widnes above Wakefield into seventh place, while Castleford remained in sixth after their fourth consecutive home league defeat.

Fawzi al-Odah, a 37-year-old Kuwaiti held at Guantanamo Bay since 2002, has been released and returned to Kuwait. A US review board determined he was no longer a significant threat, though he had been detained on suspicion of links to al-Qaeda and the Taliban, which he denied. He had challenged his detention in the US Supreme Court. As part of his release terms, he must spend a year in a Kuwaiti rehabilitation center. His release reduces the Guantanamo population to 148. President Obama has repeatedly promised to close the facility.

The viral video "PPAP" (Pen-Pineapple-Apple-Pen) is performed by DJ Piko-Taro, a fictional character played by Japanese entertainer Kazuhiko Kosaka. The song's bizarre concept came from the performer singing while playing with the items. The video, featuring a catchy beat, silly lyrics, and a simple dance, became a global phenomenon after being uploaded to YouTube and shared on Facebook, where a 9GAG post garnered over 44 million views. While it was dubbed the next Psy internationally and spawned many tributes, it did not trend significantly on Japanese social media and received little coverage from mainstream Japanese news.

Thousands attended London's Anzac Day commemorations, including a dawn service at Hyde Park Corner and a parade of up to 400 people to the Cenotaph. Anzac Day marks the first major WWI battle for Australian and New Zealand forces, specifically the Gallipoli campaign, a bloody eight-month allied operation against the Ottoman Empire. A service was also held at Westminster Abbey, where the tradition in London began in 1916. The events are important for expatriates and visitors to honor the sacrifices of their countrymen. The ceremonies featured wreath-laying, prayers, and the national anthems of New Zealand, Australia, and the UK.

David Clarkson, 30, has rejoined St Mirren and may debut against Alloa. He states he is fully fit and ready to play, having maintained his fitness with the U20s. A former Scotland international, Clarkson has nearly 400 senior club appearances. St Mirren are currently eighth in the Championship.

The turkey firm Bernard Matthews was sold to Ranjit Boparan. Unions received guarantees that all current workers' agreements and pension arrangements would be honored under the new ownership. The new owner plans to restore profitability through greater investment, cost savings, and using spare capacity to process chicken in addition to turkeys.

A new chain ferry in Cowes has experienced significant problems since its launch, including breakdowns, groundings, and vehicle damage, leading to its suspension. The council leader acknowledged the "frustrating and disappointing start" and announced the ferry service would be free until 2 July. A project review has been ordered, and ramp extensions are being manufactured to prevent vehicle scraping. While the transport councillor described the issues as "teething problems" with a prototype, local businesses are suffering trade losses and have asked about compensation, which the council says is up for discussion.

A House of Lords report warns that the UK fishing industry, which heavily supported Brexit to escape the EU's Common Fisheries Policy, risks being marginalized in wider Brexit negotiations despite its small economic contribution. The industry hopes Brexit will allow it to regain control of UK waters, but the report highlights significant challenges. Most fish stocks are shared with the EU, and continued tariff-free access to the EU market for UK fish exports may require allowing EU boats to fish in UK waters. The report also states that some elements of the CFP should be retained, and leaving the EU could create four separate fisheries management regimes in the UK. Despite these risks, the fishing industry remains optimistic about the opportunities Brexit presents.

Timothy Geaney, a teacher, was convicted for possessing indecent images of young boys between 2004 and 2014. Following his conviction, he was given a community payback order, placed on the sex offenders register, and ordered to attend a program for sex offenders. A disciplinary panel of the General Teaching Council Scotland found his conduct fundamentally incompatible with teaching, citing the pattern of offending over a long period and a high likelihood of recurrence. He was removed from the teaching register and prohibited from reapplying for two years.

A fire on 2 March at a site operated by Recovered Fuels Shipping Limited caused travel disruption. Despite the fire service stating the site operators were "broadly compliant" with fire safety law, the Environment Agency revoked the firm's environmental permit after the service raised concerns. The company has until 7 August to appeal and must remove all waste from the site. The cause of the fire remains undetermined.

Syria missed a deadline to hand over its chemical weapons stockpile, blaming attacks on a shipment by "terrorist groups" and stating it is committed to the UN-backed plan but is hampered by the ongoing war. The US expressed concern over the slow progress. Meanwhile, the government denied using barrel bombs on civilians in Aleppo, contradicting activist reports of hundreds killed, and denied that rebels had seized a prison, despite claims from opposition groups that they freed thousands of detainees.

England defeated Pakistan by a large margin in the second Test at Old Trafford to level the series. Joe Root was named man of the match for his first-innings 254 and his unbeaten 71 in the second innings, with his performance described as his best Test innings. England's captain Alastair Cook also scored centuries. Pakistan's batting was criticized for poor shot selection and a lack of confidence, with only two players passing 50 in the series so far. While England's performance was highly praised, some commentators believe the series will remain very competitive.

The Older People's Commissioner for Wales is launching a review into the quality of life and care for older people in residential care. The review will gather evidence from residents, their families, and care providers, focusing on health, social relationships, and the care home environment. The commissioner aims to highlight both good and poor care and develop recommendations for improvement. Care Forum Wales supports the review's aims but has expressed disappointment that the advisory panel does not include an expert with direct experience of running or working in a care home.

Paul Sheerin, a 39-year-old former Aberdeen midfielder, has been appointed as a coach at Aberdeen, replacing Neil Cooper. He was previously the player-manager at Arbroath since 2010, where he guided the club to its first national trophy, the Scottish Third Division title and promotion in 2011. Arbroath were relegated to Scottish League Two in the 2013-14 season. Aberdeen's chief executive stated the appointment followed a comprehensive process and that Arbroath's chairman was understanding of Sheerin's desire to return.

Following Bob Bradley's sacking, Curtis and Paul Williams will manage Swansea's next match. The club aims to appoint a new manager quickly, with Paul Clement as the preferred candidate. Curtis expressed that relegation would be a significant threat, making it difficult for the club to return to the Premier League, as the Championship is stronger and Swansea may not retain its best players. He believes the club has lost its identity, the "Swansea Way," since Michael Laudrup's departure in 2014, citing frequent managerial changes and a failure to adequately replace key players. Despite this, Curtis thinks the current squad can avoid relegation and emphasizes to new players the club's history and the importance of staying up for the local area.

Dr. Craig Venter, a biologist and entrepreneur, accelerated the mapping of the human genome through a competitive race, drawing criticism from the scientific community. He later led the J. Craig Venter Institute to create the first synthetic life form, Synthia. His unconventional and ambitious approach, developed after a life-changing experience in the Vietnam War, included founding private companies and using novel gene-sequencing methods. Despite controversy, his work has had significant impact, with potential applications in industry and environmental remediation.

A Sutton Trust report warns that England's apprenticeships are often low quality and too short compared to other European countries like Germany. Fewer than 200,000 of the 520,000 annual starts are at Level 3 (A-level equivalent), and most apprenticeships are for people over 25. The report calls for a radical expansion to 300,000 new starts per year, with the majority being Level 3 or higher and lasting at least three years. It criticizes England's complex vocational system of 18,000 qualifications and states that a lack of good apprenticeships limits young people's job prospects. The Department for Education says it is already reforming apprenticeships to increase their rigor and standards.

British Paralympian Sarah Storey won a cycling event in Nottwil, Switzerland, finishing over two minutes ahead of Anna Harkowska. The 37-year-old, who is Britain's most decorated female Paralympian with 22 medals (11 gold, 8 silver, 3 bronze), is aiming for success at the next Paralympics. She has competed in six Games across both cycling and swimming, winning four golds in London 2012 and a total of 21 world titles. Storey began her career in swimming in 1992 before switching to cycling in 2005.

Hereford United has been expelled from the Football Conference due to severe financial problems. Despite multiple deadline extensions, the club failed to pay its £148,000 debt to football creditors. This followed a dramatic final-day escape from relegation, which was ultimately rendered meaningless. The club, recently taken over by Tommy Agombar, had been struggling with significant debt, including unpaid player wages and a tax bill. As a result, Chester, the club they originally sent down, have been reinstated to take their place.

James Milner, a 30-year-old former Manchester City player, earned 61 caps for England, making his senior debut in 2009. He was part of the squad for two World Cups and two European Championships but played only three minutes at Euro 2016. He announced his retirement from international football, wishing success to the team under Sam Allardyce. Milner also holds the record for most England Under-21 caps (46) and scored his only international goal in a 2014 World Cup qualifier against Moldova.

Conductor and early-music scholar Christopher Hogwood has died after an illness. He was the founder of the Academy of Ancient Music (AAM), which he directed for 30 years and with which he made over 200 recordings, including a landmark cycle of Mozart symphonies and Handel's Messiah. Hogwood was a highly influential figure in the early-music movement, working with major orchestras globally and holding academic positions at Cambridge and Harvard. Colleagues remembered him as a generous, genial, and clever man whose legacy continues through the musicians he mentored and the AAM, which flourished after his tenure.

A boy from Northern Ireland has been unable to attend a special school because all such schools in his area are at capacity. His mother had to leave her job to care for him after he was removed from mainstream school. The family was given no timeframe for a place, and the boy is isolated and confused. They have now been told an assistant has been hired and he may start soon. His mother worries the over-subscribed system will affect other families. The Education Authority declined to comment on the case but stated it is reviewing the need for special school places to assist with placements from 2016.

The Welsh Rugby Union (WRU) is making a takeover bid for the Newport Gwent Dragons rugby team, whose home is Rodney Parade. The football club Newport County, fellow tenants at the ground, have a lease with primacy of fixtures until 2023 and expect this contract to be honored. The WRU's takeover will be voted on by rugby club shareholders on 9 May. A potential conflict exists as the WRU plans to install an artificial surface, which is against Football League rules. Meanwhile, Newport County are fighting to avoid relegation from League Two.

The country was recently declared free of the Ebola virus, which killed nearly 4,000 people. The speaker, a former child soldier kidnapped by the RUF rebels during Sierra Leone's civil war, described the atrocities he committed and witnessed. After escaping and being jailed, he was rehabilitated by a preacher. When Ebola struck, his organization, Lifeline Nehemiah, responded with a three-part effort: educating over 10,000 people about the virus, providing food support to 11,000 people, and setting up an Ebola treatment unit that saved many lives. He now works to invest in young people to build a better future.

A public fundraising campaign successfully saved the Wedgwood Museum's collection of 80,000 items from being auctioned to pay a pension debt. The collection, which was at risk after the pottery firm's collapse, will remain on display in Staffordshire. The Art Fund, which led the campaign, will gift it to the Victoria and Albert Museum, which will then loan it back to the Wedgwood Museum.

A deal is being discussed for Mark Wright to buy 20% of Billericay Town FC and become a club director. The club, currently eighth in the Isthmian League Premier Division, was recently taken over by multi-millionaire Glenn Tamplin, who invests £10,000 a week. They have also signed former England player Paul Konchesky.

Bank of England Governor Mark Carney announced he would extend his term by one year, rather than the full three years to 2021. This decision was driven by personal, not political, reasons. His family is planning to return to Canada in 2018 for their children's education, and he felt he could only extend his stay in the UK for an additional year. This one-year extension will allow him to oversee the completion of the Article 50 Brexit negotiations, after which a new Governor will take over.

Blackpool and Colchester United drew 1-1. Blackpool scored first through Jamille Matt, but Colchester equalized from a corner via Kurtis Guthrie. Both teams had chances to win, with Blackpool's goalkeeper Sam Slocombe making several key saves and Tom Aldred missing a late header. Colchester finished the match with ten men after Sean Murray received a straight red card for a foul in injury time.

The Healthy Me programme, developed by Action Mental Health, teaches P6 and P7 pupils in Northern Ireland how to cope with change and stress, particularly the transition to secondary school and the transfer test. The programme consists of interactive workshops that promote emotional wellbeing, teach coping strategies like breathing exercises, and encourage seeking help. It also provides basic teacher training. A school coordinator noted the programme helps alleviate anxiety in both children and parents. The initiative is seen as a positive step, with the chief inspector of schools emphasizing the need to strengthen young people's resilience against modern life's complex challenges.

The disused Fawley power station's 198-meter chimney is planned to be the centerpiece of a £1bn "merchant city" redevelopment, making it the tallest attraction south of the Shard. The oil-fired station, commissioned in 1971 and capable of powering one million homes, closed in 2013. The development, for which outline planning permission is due, includes a marina, housing, restaurants, and fast ferry links. Developers argue the existing chimney is a signature piece that can be transformed into a spectacular attraction with relatively little investment.

At the Hong Kong championships, British cyclist Joe Latham won a bronze medal in the men's event, while Elinor Barker had previously won silver in the women's scratch. The men's team pursuit lost the bronze to Italy, and the women's team pursuit finished fifth. Olympic gold medallist Katy Marchant was eliminated in the first round of the women's sprint but remains scheduled for further events.

Actor Ross Kemp will briefly return to the BBC soap EastEnders as Grant Mitchell for the final episodes of the character Peggy Mitchell, played by his close friend Dame Barbara Windsor. Peggy's character, who recently returned to reveal her cancer had returned, will be killed off in the spring. Kemp's return will reunite the Mitchell brothers, Grant and Phil (Steve McFadden), with their mother for the last time. Executive producer Dominic Treadwell-Collins stated this reunion will allow the actors to showcase their best performances as the brothers face losing their mother.

Tottenham Hotspur suffered a disappointing away defeat to Liverpool, with manager Mauricio Pochettino criticizing his team's lack of desire and readiness to fight for the Premier League title. He stated that if Chelsea extended their lead to 12 points, it would be a significant problem. Statistics show Spurs have a poor away record against top-six teams, winning only once in their last 17 such matches. An analyst noted the team's defensive disarray and suggested a tactical change to a back three, highlighting a contrast between their strong home form and poor away performances.

The All Progressives Congress (APC) won 19 of 28 declared governorships, marking the biggest defeat for the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) since 1999. The PDP, which also lost the presidential election, was relegated to a regional party, winning mostly in the south-east and the Niger Delta but losing key northern states. The APC retained control of Lagos but failed to win any of Nigeria's five oil-producing states, a concern for incoming President Muhammadu Buhari. The elections were marred by violence, particularly in the south, though overall they were more peaceful than in previous years. The PDP's decline is attributed to voter desire for change, defections to the APC, and allegations of corruption and mishandling the Islamist insurgency.

The Hebridean Celtic Festival (HebCelt) in Stornoway, Isle of Lewis, from 19-22 July, is offering a new augmented reality app. Visitors can use the app on phones and tablets to trigger online information, videos, and band interviews from signs and posters. This feature aims to enhance the experience for on-site visitors and also allows people worldwide to interact with the festival, access information, buy tickets, and get a feel for the event's atmosphere. Acts include The Waterboys, Imelda May, and Peatbog Faeries.

Several Birmingham academies, including Park View and Nansen Primary, are having their funding agreements terminated after being rated inadequate by Ofsted. Oldknow Academy and Golden Hillock School were also warned they could lose funding. The government cited failures to promote students' development, improper vetting of external speakers, and segregation of boys and girls. An anonymous head teacher described a coordinated campaign by parents to undermine her authority. Ofsted's chief reported a "culture of fear and intimidation" in some schools, aimed at imposing a faith-based ideology. The schools and some parents have challenged the reports, alleging inspector bias.

Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe was sentenced to five years in an Iranian prison for allegedly plotting to topple the government. Her husband, Richard Ratcliffe, criticizes the UK government for inaction and describes her appeal hearing as a "secret trial." He believes she is being used as a diplomatic bargaining chip. Zaghari-Ratcliffe has been held in solitary confinement, felt suicidal, and went on a hunger strike. Her two-year-old daughter remains in Iran with her grandparents after her passport was confiscated. The outcome of the appeal is unpredictable and could result in her sentence being quashed, reduced, or increased. Amnesty International UK considers her a prisoner of conscience.

In July 2012, Vincent "Vinnie" Barker died from a build-up of fluid in his brain. Optometrist Honey Rose is on trial for gross negligence manslaughter. The prosecution alleges her failure to detect his swollen optic discs during a routine eye test and refer him for further investigation was criminal, as his death was preventable. Ms. Rose denies the charge.

Clive Weatherhogg was found guilty of coercing a woman into sexual activity with a man he found online, filming the acts, and sending an explicit clip to the victim's sister on Christmas Day. He was also convicted of causing the sister and father to view sexual images and of abusive behavior. The judge stated the sentence must reflect society's abhorrence for his conduct, and he was assessed as a moderate risk to re-offend. The case was moved to the High Court for sentencing due to its greater powers.

Ireland scored 165-5 in a T20 match against Afghanistan, with notable contributions from Stuart Thompson (56), Gary Wilson (41*), and William Porterfield (39). Afghanistan reached the target of 171-4 with two overs to spare, led by Samiullah Shenwari (56) and Mohammad Shahzad (47). Ireland's captain Porterfield felt they fell 15-20 runs short and their bowling execution was lacking. The teams were scheduled for a second T20, and Ireland was missing bowler Boyd Rankin due to injury.

Barcelona has made an additional tax payment of €13.5 million related to the transfer of Neymar, while denying any wrongdoing and maintaining their original tax payment was correct. The club stated the new payment was to cover divergent interpretations of contracts and defend its reputation. A Spanish judge is investigating the transfer, which has an alleged total cost of £106.8m, far higher than the initially stated £48.6m. The club's former president resigned over accusations of misappropriating money. It is unconfirmed if the case will be dropped.

The bodies of British tourists David Miller and Hannah Witheridge were found murdered on a Thai beach. Two Burmese migrant workers were charged and allegedly confessed, though Thai police deny reports they later retracted these confessions. UK detectives reviewed the investigation, prompted by concerns over DNA verification and suspect mistreatment, and have returned to compile a report for the victims' families. The suspects face charges of murder, rape, and robbery and could receive the death penalty.

Virtual reality (VR) is being used in various unexpected ways beyond entertainment. The UK's National Autistic Society and Alzheimer's Research UK created VR films to help the public understand the sensory overload of autism and the challenges of dementia, respectively. In retail, Ikea developed a VR kitchen app that was very popular, even when users just threw virtual meatballs. Healthcare uses VR for training surgeons, treating phobias like arachnophobia, and helping soldiers with PTSD. In education, Google's Expeditions takes students on virtual field trips, and other apps are being developed to improve language skills by immersing users in virtual environments. While seen as a powerful tool to engage students, the cost of VR hardware remains a challenge for widespread adoption in schools.

The "black box" from the Russian Su-24 jet shot down by Turkey was opened in Moscow, but the head of the Russian investigation stated flight information appeared to be missing. The incident has caused a crisis in relations, with Russia imposing sanctions and demanding an apology. Turkey claims the jet was in its airspace, while Russia insists it was over Syria. The jet was downed on November 24; the pilot and a rescue marine were killed, while the navigator was rescued.

The Scotland women's national team is on the verge of qualifying for a major tournament, leading their group with five wins. A crucial match against Iceland, who are also unbeaten, will likely decide the group winner. Player Lisa Evans expresses the team's determination to avoid the heartbreak of previous near-misses in qualification. She highlights the benefit of having many squad members playing in top foreign leagues, which brings different experiences and improves the national team. With the best runners-up also qualifying, Scotland is in a strong position to reach the finals.

A review for Scotland's Commission on Local Tax Reform found there is no "magic bullet" to fix the council tax system, which has had built-in problems since its introduction. The review noted that a property tax, used by most OECD countries, is stable but causes confusion over whether it is a tax on wealth or a charge for services and is seen as unfair as it is not linked to current income. A local income tax is perceived as fairer but creates difficulties for local authorities due to fluctuating income and less flexibility to set local rates. The commission, which considers the current system unfair, will hold a public consultation and report its findings in the autumn.

Apple has strengthened iCloud security by making two-factor authentication mandatory for accessing iCloud backups, a change that blocks a specific forensic tool from Elcomsoft that was used to steal celebrities' photos. While the security feature is now more comprehensive, it remains an opt-in choice, leading experts to argue it should be the default setting. The process requires a code from a trusted device or phone number to access an account from a new device, and a 14-character recovery key is available if the trusted device is lost.
