The owner of Elcomsoft confirmed his software can no longer bypass the new security, which also sends an email notification when a backup download starts. He expressed concerns that the recovery key is hard to remember and could be lost or stolen, but another expert downplayed this risk and reiterated that two-factor authentication should be the default for all major tech companies. Apple's CEO stated the company plans to more aggressively encourage people to use the feature.

In the May European elections, UKIP won, spending £2,956,737, while the Conservatives spent slightly more at £2,980,815. Labour, which came second, spent £1,027,339. The Liberal Democrats spent £1,580,575 but lost 11 of their 12 MEPs. The cost per vote was highest for the Lib Dems (£1.45) and lowest for Labour (26p). The Green Party and SNP were also among the six highest-spending parties, with a combined total campaign expenditure of £9,347,087. All parties except Labour spent more than they did in the 2009 campaign.

Two players have joined Torquay United (the Gulls). Centre-back Myles Anderson, 27, was signed after his contract with Barrow was cancelled, and he could play against his former club. Striker Ruairi Keating, 21, was recommended to manager Kevin Nicholson. Anderson is described as a leader, while Keating is young and hungry. Torquay is currently four points above the relegation zone.

The 10-year-old racehorse Many Clouds collapsed and died after winning the Cotswold Chase at Cheltenham. The British Horseracing Authority confirmed the cause was a severe pulmonary haemorrhage, a rare event that can occur in horses with no underlying health issues. Although the horse had a history of post-race ataxia, he showed no symptoms of it on the day of the race, and the report concludes his death was due to this rare haemorrhage and not his previous condition.

Presiding Officer Tricia Marwick and several veteran MSPs, including Alex Salmond and Duncan McNeil, gave emotional farewell speeches as they stood down from the Scottish Parliament. In his address, Alex Salmond reiterated his belief that Scotland is a diverse but not divided country, and that there is a consensus for the parliament to assume greater governing responsibility. He welcomed new powers for Holyrood but said they fell short of pre-referendum pledges. Duncan McNeil, in his speech, warned that Holyrood must learn from Westminster's committee system to ensure proper scrutiny and accountability. Annabel Goldie also gave a light-hearted farewell speech.

Emma Watson will play Belle in a live-action "Beauty and the Beast" film, with Dan Stevens as the Beast and Luke Evans as Gaston. The cast also includes Ewan McGregor as Mrs. Potts, Kevin Kline as Maurice, and Josh Gad as LeFou. Directed by Bill Condon, filming begins in May at Shepperton Studios for a 17 March 2017 US release.

The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is announcing its decision on whether to bring charges against 23 suspects related to the 1989 Hillsborough disaster, where 96 fans were unlawfully killed. The decision, to be revealed to victims' relatives, follows investigations into the causes of the disaster and the subsequent police conduct. Families of the victims, who have endured a long struggle, are seeking accountability for the event.

Chelmsford Prison is experiencing numerous incidents of contraband, including mobile phones and synthetic cannabis, being thrown over the wall by packages, according to residents and a former inmate. A local witness reported seeing this happen four times in two weeks. The Ministry of Justice acknowledges staff work hard to stop contraband and that new laws impose two-year sentences for smuggling packages, but admits more must be done. While a former inmate claimed drones are used, the Ministry said there is no evidence of drones at the Chelmsford site.

Sylvia Blackburn, a 72-year-old lollipop lady, was seriously injured after being struck by a car driven by Brian Wright outside a school. Wright, 55, admits hitting her but denies causing serious injury by dangerous driving. He claims he was blinded by the setting sun and cannot remember if the traffic light was red. The prosecution states he failed to stop for a red light while Mrs. Blackburn, who was wearing appropriate clothing, was crossing the road. Wright expressed remorse for his actions. The trial is ongoing.

Middle-distance runner Laura Muir will miss the 2018 Commonwealth Games due to a scheduling conflict with her final-year veterinary medicine exams. The 24-year-old Scot expressed disappointment but prioritized completing her degree. She recently set a new outdoor personal best in the 5,000m at the World Championships and is targeting the World Indoor Championships. Muir believes she has the potential for several more Olympics in the future.

In December 2000, 22-year-old Trevor Deely disappeared after a Christmas party. A new search involving excavations of a three-acre woodland site in Chapelizod, Dublin, began. Gardaí are renewing their appeal to identify an unidentified man in black seen talking to Deely on CCTV outside his workplace and later following him. Enhanced footage was released earlier in the year, but the man has not yet come forward.

Juan Martin del Potro, returning from injury and ranked 165th, defeated Stan Wawrinka in a four-set match at Wimbledon. This is Del Potro's first Grand Slam since 2014 after three wrist operations. In the same half of the draw as Andy Murray, Nick Kyrgios also advanced to the third round after a five-set victory over Dustin Brown. Kyrgios will next play Feliciano Lopez, who came from two sets down to win his match. Other winners included Tomas Berdych and Jo-Wilfried Tsonga.

Tunisia faced potential expulsion from the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations for lodging complaints against the Confederation of African Football (Caf) after a controversial quarter-final loss to Equatorial Guinea. After a meeting with Caf, Tunisia apologized, resolving the dispute. Separately, Morocco had a ban on participating in the 2017 qualifiers overturned by the Court of Arbitration for Sport (Cas), which also reduced a fine against its football association. Morocco's original ban was for refusing to host the 2015 tournament due to Ebola fears. Both nations are now in the qualifying draw for the 2017 finals.

McLaren, a historically successful Formula 1 team with 12 drivers' and 8 constructors' titles, is currently in a competitive slump despite having two world champions, including Fernando Alonso, driving for them. The team's decline began in 2013 with chassis problems and is now due to an underperforming Honda engine, a stark contrast to their dominant partnership with Honda in the late 1980s. The team's history is a cycle of triumph and decline, and current boss Ron Dennis believes they are on the verge of a comeback, with a strong car and an expected Honda engine improvement set to challenge Mercedes' dominance and win future championships.

Paramedics were called to a sudden death at Joe's Bar in Dungiven on October 6, 2014. Police found people still at the bar hours later, with receipts showing alcohol was served until 04:49 BST. The bar was ordered to close for three months. License holder Colleen O'Neill was charged with two counts and fined £3,000, while James Thomas faced one count and was fined £1,000. The judge described O'Neill's record as "appalling" and the case as one of the worst he had encountered. A defence solicitor admitted licensing laws were not strictly followed and the premises were not run properly.

Stephen Curry broke his own NBA record for most three-pointers in a season, scoring 45 points to lead the Golden State Warriors to a 116-105 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers. In another game, the Chicago Bulls overcame a 19-point halftime deficit to beat the Miami Heat 89-78, dealing a blow to Miami's playoff hopes. Pau Gasol had 16 points and 15 rebounds for the Bulls.

YouTube star Bas van Velzen, a Dutch free-kick specialist, tricked Liverpool players Mario Balotelli, Fabio Borini, Rickie Lambert, and Lazar Markovic by posing as a competition winner. The players were surprised when he revealed his true skill during a free-kick masterclass. Van Velzen enjoyed pretending to be unskilled and seeing their reactions. He also surprised Balotelli by unveiling the forward's infamous slogan.

A Canadian study found that women with a BRCA1 gene mutation who had their ovaries removed (oophorectomy) after a breast cancer diagnosis reduced their risk of dying from breast cancer by 62% and from all causes by 65%. The protective effect was immediate and lasted 15 years. This benefit was significant for BRCA1 carriers but not for those with a BRCA2 mutation. The study's authors suggest oophorectomy should be considered as part of initial treatment discussions for BRCA1 carriers with early-stage breast cancer.

A married couple, Derek and Tina Lowe, were struck and killed by an Amtrak train on Easter morning in Durham, North Carolina. The train, carrying 166 uninjured passengers, was delayed for nearly three hours. An acquaintance suggested the couple may have been homeless and were using a grocery cart to cross the tracks.

Carlos Toro, a 66-year-old former mid-level member of the Medellin cartel, worked as an unpaid undercover informant for the DEA for 27 years with the promise of US citizenship. His information was crucial in prosecuting major figures like cocaine lord Carlos Lehder and former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega. Now retired due to declining health, the DEA has not granted him citizenship and refused to help after he went public, leaving him in the US illegally and facing deportation. Toro fears he will be killed if sent back to Colombia. A former DEA handler supports him, stating Toro deserves to stay, but he remains in legal limbo without a green card, passport, or social security benefits.

The U.S. internet regulator ICANN is investigating Canadian company Vox Populi Registry Ltd. for its use of the new '.sucks' domain. The company is accused of extracting high payments from celebrities like Kevin Spacey and companies to protect their reputations by purchasing domains like youtube.sucks and visa.sucks. Vox Populi charges trademark holders $2,499 per year for these domains before public release. An advisory panel has called the practice a predatory "shakedown scheme." ICANN has asked U.S. and Canadian regulators to determine if Vox Populi's actions are illegal, which could put the company in breach of its contract.

A baby boy's body was found in a Norfolk pond in 1988. The case remained unsolved for 27 years until a review led police to exhume the body. Using advanced DNA technology, they identified and located the mother. She admitted to concealing the pregnancy and stated the baby was stillborn. She had placed the body in the pond. Police ruled out foul play. The baby, originally buried as "unknown," was reburied with a headstone naming him Peter. The mother was arrested for infanticide, but the charge was dropped; she remains on bail for possible charges of failing to register a birth and preventing a lawful burial.

A taxi driver, Michael Young, was ordered to pay compensation to his passenger, Kristopher Hicks, who suffered severe brain injuries after jumping from the moving vehicle. A High Court judge ruled that Young had unlawfully imprisoned Hicks after mistakenly believing he would not pay the fare and driving him back to the taxi rank as a lesson. The judge found Young's actions created a significant risk, but also applied a 50% reduction in the damages, which are expected to be hundreds of thousands of pounds. Hicks requires lifelong, round-the-clock care from his mother due to his injuries, which include epilepsy and cognitive problems.

Tornado sirens sounded in Kansas as storms produced multiple reported tornadoes, including one near Goddard and others in southwestern Kansas. A possible tornado may have touched down in Potosi, Missouri, causing wind damage, flooding, and property damage. CNN's severe weather expert noted the particular danger of nighttime tornadoes. More storms were forecast for Thursday in the Midwest, Mississippi River Valley, Tennessee River Valley, and near the southern Great Lakes.

Luke Rockhold and Lyoto Machida are preparing for a middleweight fight in New Jersey. Rockhold plans to be the aggressive "bull" to counter Machida's evasive "matador" style, believing he can exploit weaknesses in Machida's game and dominate him on the ground and on the feet. He respects Machida's career and fighting style but is confident in his own abilities. Machida is also confident, stating that with the right strategy and preparation, he can win the fight. Both fighters believe the winner of this bout deserves a title shot.

An 85-year-old pilot, Chris Georgaklis, made a belly landing at Aero Acres Residential Airpark in Fort Pierce, Florida, after forgetting to deploy the landing gear. The aircraft skidded on the runway, with its propellers striking the ground. The pilot then applied full throttle and took off again. Despite the damage, he flew the plane 100 miles to Fort Lauderdale and landed safely. The incident, attributed to human error, is under investigation by the FAA.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini is disappointed with Yaya Touré's performances this season but has vowed to support the midfielder until the end of the campaign. The club is reportedly willing to listen to offers for Touré in the summer. Pellegrini dismissed suggestions that Touré needs a rest. Meanwhile, City faces West Ham without injured captain Vincent Kompany. Goalkeeper Joe Hart stated the players have let the manager down and take responsibility for poor results. In other news, West Ham manager Sam Allardyce has warned his left-back Aaron Cresswell, a reported target for City and Chelsea, not to make the same mistake as other English players who moved to big clubs and saw their playing time diminish.

Domenico Rancadore, a convicted Sicilian mafia member, will remain in the UK after his extradition to Italy was halted. His seven-year sentence, imposed in 1999 for Mafia association, was declared extinguished under Italian law because the time period for enforcement had passed. An Italian court officially withdrew the European arrest warrant. Rancadore had lived in the UK for over 20 years under an alias while fighting extradition. The Crown Prosecution Service admitted to an administrative error that caused delays, but stated this did not significantly impact the final outcome.

Mr. Mole, AP McCoy's mount in the Grade One Celebration Chase at Sandown, is a 7-2 co-favorite alongside Special Tiara and Sprinter Sacre. This will be McCoy's last ride in a Grade One race, and it was after a victory on Mr. Mole in February that he announced his retirement. The seven-runner race also includes Somersby.

Virginia Trimble Ritter's daughter, Marcia, was raped and murdered in 1975. Her body was found 33 days later, but for decades Ritter avoided seeing the crime scene photos. In the last year, she decided to view them and was horrified by her daughter's injuries, stating she now wants revenge. The case remained unsolved for 33 years until Jerome Sydney Barrett was convicted in 2009 through DNA evidence and sentenced to 44 years for the murder.

Rory McIlroy believes it is "unthinkable" he will not win the Masters to complete the career Grand Slam, a feat achieved by only five other golfers. He considers his 2011 final-round collapse at Augusta the most important day of his career, as it taught him crucial lessons that helped him win subsequent majors. McIlroy views the golf course as a sanctuary from external pressures and hopes to win multiple green jackets, stating that securing the first one is the most important step.

Four rainbows appeared over New York after heavy rain. In rural China, hiring exotic dancers for wakes is being cracked down upon. The #kyliejennerchallenge trend involves lip plumping by sucking on a jar. A 102-year-old woman, Alice Barker, revisited her past with filmmakers. A prom-posal referencing bombs caused controversy, with accusations of racism. Ewan McGregor will play Lumiere in 'Beauty and the Beast'. Johnny Depp appears in the 'Black Mass' trailer. A pregnancy announcement referenced "The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air," and a military dad photobombed his son.

Last year, 272 children in England were hospitalized with disabilities from foetal alcohol syndrome, but experts warn the actual number is likely far higher. WHO research suggests at least 1 in 100 UK babies, or about 7,500 annually, could suffer from learning, behavioural, and physical problems due to alcohol exposure in the womb. The condition is described as an enormous, under-diagnosed problem. The government advises pregnant women to avoid alcohol or limit it to two units no more than twice a week, but some experts recommend complete abstinence.

Shaun McKerry, a repeat offender with a history of crime, was jailed for six years for attempting to rob a store. He threatened an assistant with an axe but was tackled by the shop owner, Sab Dhillon. During the struggle, Dhillon's wife, Sam, hit McKerry twice with a baseball bat, helping to disarm him. Police arrived and arrested him.

Four Royal Navy sailors—Joshua Finbow, Simon Radford, Craig Stoner, and Darren Smalley—are charged with the gang rape of a woman in her early 20s at a Canadian naval barracks in Halifax, Nova Scotia, following an alcohol-fuelled party after an ice hockey game. They have been granted bail with conditions requiring them to stay in Nova Scotia, surrender their passports, live at the Stadacona naval base, and remain employed by the Royal Navy. They are charged with sexual assault causing bodily harm and group sexual assault, offences punishable by up to 14 years in prison, and are forbidden from contacting the victim and witnesses.

A mother, Valerie Jackson, was reported to police for child abuse by a stranger who mistook her four-year-old son RJ's rare disease for burns. RJ has Netherton's syndrome, an extremely rare condition affecting only about 70 people worldwide, which makes his skin appear red, scaly, and inflamed. The family must regularly apply creams to his skin to manage the painful symptoms. The incident with the police is one of many challenges they face, including public taunts, being denied entry to a play center, and general ignorance about the condition. Despite these difficulties, Jackson describes her son as a beautiful, happy, and bubbly boy.

Controversial "Are you beach body ready?" advertisements by Protein World, featuring a bikini-clad model, are being removed from the London Underground. Transport for London (TfL) stated the removal was scheduled after the three-week advertising period ended, but also acknowledged public complaints and would consider the reaction for future ads. The ads had sparked a significant backlash, with over 50,000 petition signatures and 216 complaints to the Advertising Standards Authority, with critics arguing they promoted an unhealthy and sexist body image. Protein World defended the campaign, stating its goal was to promote health and fitness, and reported receiving violent threats, including a bomb threat.

Rail firms are planning significant fare hikes, including an 87% increase on a London to Cotswolds route, just days after the general election where party leaders pledged to freeze fares. Prime Minister David Cameron has personally intervened, requesting First Great Western review its decision for a route through his constituency. Other examples include a 24.5% increase on a Stafford to Liverpool route. The train companies defend the changes, with First Great Western stating it is to standardize pricing and Virgin Trains claiming its overall increase is below the industry average.

A 66-year-old former soldier, John Young, was blinded in one eye after a brick was thrown directly at him when he opened his front door to confront vandals who were throwing stones at his Oldham home. The attack occurred as he and his new wife were writing wedding thank-you cards. Police are investigating but state there appears to be no motive, suggesting it may have been youths "messing around." The couple is now moving away as they no longer feel safe.

Derbyshire wicketkeeper Tom Poynton has signed a one-year contract extension until the end of 2016, rewarding his successful return from injury. Poynton missed the 2014 season due to leg injuries sustained in a fatal road accident that killed his father. After an ankle operation, he made his comeback during the pre-season tour of Abu Dhabi. The club's elite performance director praised Poynton's exceptional character and tireless work in his recovery.

A five-year-old boy, Harley Renshaw, has been declared cancer-free after a year-long battle with neuroblastoma, a rare and aggressive childhood cancer that had spread to his kidney, neck, lungs, and bones. His treatment included intensive chemotherapy, an operation, a stem cell transplant, and radiotherapy. To cope, he decorated his radiotherapy mask like a Ninja Turtle, which helped him feel brave. His story gained widespread attention, and he received gifts from Nickelodeon. He has been awarded a Little Star Award and is now the face of a charity campaign for childhood cancer research.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood advises 19-year-old Jack Grealish to focus on his club career before deciding his international future, which is between the Republic of Ireland and England. Sherwood believes Grealish must first secure his place in Villa's first team, and the international decision, which is solely up to the player, should come later. Grealish's father agrees, stating his son must continue performing well for Villa and that the international choice will be difficult. Grealish is expected to make his decision at the end of the season.

Private jet travel is a growing, multi-trillion dollar industry. Landing fees for private jets vary significantly, with some of the most expensive airports being unexpected hubs. The three most expensive airports are in Japan: Haneda, Narita, and Kansai. Other surprisingly expensive airports include Bristol (UK), Darwin (Australia), Dublin, and Salzburg (Austria). The only US airport in the top ten is LaGuardia in New York. The busiest and most expensive times to fly coincide with major events like the Super Bowl and the Monaco Grand Prix.

A video of Katie Gallegos's dog, Cooper the Labrador, eating a McDonald's ice cream cone in one bite has been viewed over seven million times. While his smaller companion, Daisy, licks the treat slowly, Cooper always eats very quickly. Although some viewers criticized feeding dogs ice cream, Gallegos, who runs a dog resort, defends the occasional treat, stating Cooper is a healthy athlete and her previous dog lived to 19. The dogs also enjoy "pup-uccinos," which are just whipped cream, from Starbucks.

Gary Locke has been appointed Kilmarnock's permanent manager on a three-year contract. He initially joined as an assistant and took over as interim manager in February. Since then, he has lost only one of his seven games in charge.

A Florida mother, Jessica Kemp, accused Seminole County Elementary of threatening to suspend her five-year-old autistic son, Logan, for wearing essential oils from doTERRA, which she applies to help him stay calm and focused. The school claimed the smell was a distraction to others. Despite receiving a letter from the school board stating the oils created a problem, the Lake County school district later said they would not suspend Logan, calling it a health issue.

A fire on Wednesday afternoon destroyed 90 condos in the Sandpiper beach-side apartment complex in Westhampton. The blaze, which caused the building to collapse, was so intense it melted paint off nearby buildings and was visible from three miles away. Twelve fire crews responded but could not enter the building. The cause is under investigation, with one claim it started near a parked car. A resident and the building manager, who lost everything, described the scene. The complex is used as a holiday home between May and November.

The Queen, nearly 89, was seen riding her black Fell pony, Carltonlima Emma, in Windsor Great Park. She has ridden since age four and is a lifelong horse enthusiast who breeds several breeds, including Fell and Highland ponies. The Queen is known for never wearing a riding helmet, preferring a silk headscarf, reportedly to avoid disrupting her hair. She rides less now due to a knee injury but remains active with her horses. The passage also details the history of the Fell pony breed, noting its ancient origins, use by Romans and Vikings, and its current popularity as a riding horse.

A 55-year-old Brisbane man, Leon Yeaman, was killed by a single punch from his 28-year-old neighbour, Phillip Pama, during a dispute over loud noise. Pama, a shift worker who was trying to sleep, confronted Yeaman about the commotion. Pama's defence stated he threw a punch "blindly" while being pushed. Yeaman was pronounced dead at the scene. Pama, a married father of three with no history of violence, was charged with manslaughter and granted conditional bail. The case will return to court on May 18.

Yulia Simonova, a 52-year-old music teacher, was arrested for attempting to hire a hitman to torture and murder her 15-year-old former pupil, Damian Vanya, after he ended their relationship. In a police sting operation, an undercover officer posed as a hitman and filmed Simonova agreeing to pay 100,000 rubles (£1,400) for the killing. She gave specific instructions for the boy to be brutally beaten, have his limbs broken, and bleed to death, stating she wanted to "finish him" herself. Simonova was charged with attempted murder and faces up to 15 years in prison.

Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho has a strong faith, praying and speaking with God daily, but never about football. He strives to separate his professional and family life, describing himself as a good family person and friend. He and his family have worked as ambassadors against hunger with the World Food Programme.

Bob Barker, the former host of "The Price is Right," returned to the show for the first time in eight years on April 1. The 91-year-old hosted the first pricing game before turning the duties back over to the current host, Drew Carey.

An off-duty Secret Service agent, Arthur Baldwin, was arrested in Washington D.C. on a felony charge of attempted burglary and destruction of property after allegedly trying to break into a house. The Metropolitan Police arrested him on a residential street. The Secret Service revoked his security clearance and placed him on leave. His arrest and a separate misconduct investigation into a supervisor are the latest issues for the agency, which is also being probed for an earlier incident involving two officials who drove into a secure White House area after drinking.

A freelance photographer, Atif Saeed from Lahore, Pakistan, risked his life to photograph a male lion. He left his car and lay on the ground just 10 feet away from the animal to capture its character. The sound of his camera's shutter alerted the lion, which aggressively jumped towards him, forcing Saeed to scramble back to the safety of his car. He later reflected that it was a very close encounter and he would not attempt it again.

NYPD is seeking to identify an unnamed woman, believed to be 25-45 years old, who died on a Brooklyn street on March 22. She had no ID but a distinctive tattoo on her right leg of a heart with a rose and the name "Monique." Police released images of the tattoo and are awaiting a cause of death. The public is asked to contact NYPD Crime Stoppers with information.

A New Zealand couple, Hannah and Alex, built a two-bedroom, solar-powered home on the back of a 1986 flatbed truck after returning from the UK and being unable to afford property. The project took about a year and a half and cost $25,000. Their wood and steel home is now located on a lot in Nelson, where they live nearly self-sufficiently with solar power, a wood stove, gas appliances, and water from a nearby spring.

A study found that kindergarten children who shared iPads in class scored significantly higher on early literacy tests than those who had their own device or no iPad at all. Students using shared iPads scored about 30 points higher. The researcher concluded that collaborative learning around the technology, not just the device itself, was the key factor, suggesting schools should reconsider how tablets are used in early grades.

A two-legged piglet from China, born without hind legs, has become an internet sensation. It has mastered walking and balancing on its front trotters, as seen in a popular online video. The piglet, owned by a farmer in Sichuan province, happily lives with its four-legged siblings and has drawn visits from local villagers.

During the IndyCar Grand Prix of Louisiana, a pit crew member for Dale Coyne Racing, Todd Phillips, was injured when Francesco Dracone's car spun exiting the pit box on lap 25, clipping Phillips' leg. Phillips received stitches at the infield care center and was released. Dracone did not finish the race.

Milton Vieira Severiano, 32, murdered his wife, dancer Cicera Alves de Sena, 29, in Rio de Janeiro. After a violent argument, he was captured on CCTV dragging her, smashing her head into concrete 11 times, and punching her 10 times. He then shot her in the face five times at point-blank range. The attack occurred just four days after their wedding, and Severiano confessed he killed her because he was jealous of men looking at her. After the murder, he stole a car but was arrested after crashing it. Police found four handguns, a shotgun, and a bulletproof vest in the vehicle. He now faces life in jail.

Sarah Wilson, author of "I Quit Sugar," revealed in an interview that her severe anxiety, combined with stress, thyroid disease, and feeling isolated without a husband or children, drove her to a point where she could not see a way out and nearly took her own life. She believes anxiety and depression are linked and that acknowledging this is key to tackling the rising rate of Australian women affected by anxiety.

An Oregon woman, Elena Curtin, who was seven months pregnant, beat her boyfriend's ex-girlfriend with a crowbar after finding the woman using heroin in her bathroom and refusing to leave. Prosecutors dropped the second-degree assault charge, stating her actions were "completely justified" under Oregon law which allows force against an intruder who won't leave. Curtin avoided a potential six-year prison sentence, gave birth, and has since moved on from the relationship.

A pit bull named Gemma, filmed at home in California, was given treats by her owner, who tricked her by including a piece of broccoli. Gemma reacted with disgust, chewed the broccoli, and then spat it out onto the floor. The text expresses hope that the children she lives with will not copy her behavior and will eat their vegetables. Other videos show Gemma sleeping and spending time with her family.

HSBC apologized after a link on its official website directed visitors to a pornographic page. The link was for a Young Entrepreneur Awards page that was scrapped in 2011, and the web address was not renewed, allowing the porn site to take over the URL. The bank removed the hyperlink, denied any association with the external site, and insisted its website and internet banking services remained secure.

A 13-year-old Maryland boy named Marcus called 911 and remained calm for 11 minutes after a fire trapped him and his 9-year-old sister, Aaliyah, in a second-floor bedroom of their Clinton home. He gave firefighters directions to their location, soothed his sister, and reminded her to stay low and breathe. Firefighters entered by breaking a window and rescued both children. Marcus, his sister, and three other family members who escaped on their own were taken to hospitals with non-life-threatening injuries. A fire chief described the rescue as a heroic effort.

Photographs show blue fluorescent algae illuminating Jervis Bay on Australia's east coast, described as a beautiful supernatural scene caused by millions of plankton emitting light. A similar event occurred at Sydney's Manly Beach in 2014. An expert explains the glow is from Noctiluca scintillans, a single-celled phytoplankton that blooms in spring and autumn and uses the light as a defense mechanism.

New genetic tests can determine the aggressiveness of a breast cancer tumor, potentially sparing patients with a low risk of recurrence from chemotherapy. These tests analyze genetic markers from a tumor sample after surgery, providing a risk score. For some women, the risk is as low as 5%, making chemotherapy an unnecessary treatment with difficult side effects. While currently private and costly, experts hope the NHS will adopt the tests, as savings from avoided chemotherapy could offset the cost. This allows patients to make an informed choice rather than routinely undergoing the grueling treatment.

Over 25 women have been airlifted from Royal Navy ships due to pregnancy, including five from HMS Ocean and one from HMS Illustrious. A strict "no touching" rule at sea suggests pregnancies were conceived before boarding or during leave. Separately, nearly 100 female soldiers were evacuated from Afghanistan for pregnancy between 2006 and 2013, and 102 from Iraq, as military rules ban expectant mothers from war zones.

A drone carrying a small camera, smoke flares, and a plastic bottle with traces of radioactive cesium was found on the roof of the Japanese Prime Minister's residence. The amount of cesium was not immediately harmful. The discovery raised government concerns about the potential for drone terrorism at future major events like the Olympics. This occurred on the same day a court approved the restart of two nuclear reactors, a move unpopular with many Japanese. Police are investigating the incident, and officials stated the need to review drone regulations to prevent such threats.

Lu Xincai, a security guard in China, takes his 84-year-old mother, who has Alzheimer's, to work with him on his motorbike every day because he fears she will get lost if left alone. He ties them together with a sash for safety during the four-kilometer journey, which takes an hour. His employers, a bank, provide her with a room, and he checks on her frequently. He does this out of a sense of duty, feeling he must care for her as she once cared for her children.

A major study found that heavy drinking in the U.S. increased by 17.2% between 2005 and 2012, and binge drinking also rose. These increases are largely driven by women, whose binge drinking rates grew at a much faster rate than men's. In 2012, 8% of Americans were heavy drinkers and 18% were binge drinkers. Researchers attribute the rise to changing social norms making it more acceptable for women to drink, an influx of affluent professionals in certain areas, alcohol becoming cheaper, increased advertising, and the weakening of alcohol control policies.

UN officials warn that doctors are performing too many Caesarean sections without medical necessity, risking the health of women and babies through potential complications, infections, and death. The ideal rate is 10-15%, but in England, the rate is over 25% and has more than doubled since the 1990s. This WHO warning contradicts current NHS guidelines, which allow the procedure for reasons like a mother's anxiety about childbirth. Caesareans also carry a higher financial cost than natural births.

Michelle Filkins, 44, was arrested on April 17 after the owner, Mark Conklin, found her in his Edgartown summer home. She is charged with breaking and entering, larceny over $250, and malicious destruction of property. Filkins allegedly lived in the house for at least a week, broke a window to enter, and sold the owner's belongings in a yard sale. Stolen items included furniture, lamps, a grill, and a painting. She was arrested when she tried to return to the home after initially fleeing. Police are asking anyone who purchased items to return them.

Bella Crooke lost her unlocked iPhone, which was handed in to Albury police. Officers used the phone to post humorous selfies and puns on her Facebook page to locate her. They posted photos of the phone in a holding cell and replied to her friends' messages. Bella retrieved her phone without having to give her name, as the officers recognized her from Facebook. She found the approach funny and has since put a password on her phone.

A five-day-old hippo calf was killed after being caught in a fight between two adult male hippos in South Africa's Isimangaliso Wetland Park. The mother watched as one of the brawling males grabbed the calf in its jaws, threw it into the air, and dragged it through the water. The calf died from its injuries hours later.

A three-bedroom apartment in London's expensive Knightsbridge area is on the market for £575,000, a fraction of the price of neighboring homes, because it has only three years remaining on its lease. The "unmodernised" property requires renovation. The cost of the short lease is comparable to the area's rental rates. However, if a buyer pays an estimated £3.35-£4.5 million to extend the lease to 90 years, the modernised property could be worth over £6 million. A second, larger maisonette is also for sale under the same conditions. The freeholder is believed to be the Welcome Trust, and estate agents report very high interest in the rare opportunity.

A computer outage at 8,000 Starbucks stores in the US and Canada forced the closure of some locations and prompted others to give away free drinks and baked goods. The register glitch, caused by a failure during a daily system refresh, prevented credit card payments. The issue began Friday evening and was resolved overnight, with stores expected to reopen for business as usual on Saturday. The outage occurred just one day after Starbucks reported record quarterly earnings.

According to an officer from the Wales Extremism and Counter Terrorism Unit, terrorists are undergoing training and radicalization in rural areas of west Wales, specifically in Ceredigion, Powys, and Pembrokeshire. Individuals involved participate in seemingly ordinary community activities but have an ulterior motive. Historical examples include extremists training in the Brecon Beacons in 1998, the 7/7 bombers rafting in Bala, a Cardiff-based terror plot in 2010, and Michael Adebowale, convicted of murdering Fusilier Lee Rigby, having studied at an institute in Llanybydder. Community intelligence is considered vital for authorities.

A rare Omura's whale, a species previously feared extinct and first scientifically described in 2003, was found washed up on a remote beach in Western Australia. This is the first recorded sighting of the species in the state and only the second in Australia. The juvenile female was identified through DNA profiling. The discovery is significant for scientists, as it provides an opportunity to learn more about the poorly understood species, which is typically found in tropical waters like those of Indonesia and the Philippines. The whale's skeleton will be recovered for future scientific study and potential museum display.

A Texas businesswoman argues that Hillary Clinton should not be president because female hormones could lead to irrational decisions like starting a war. The article counters that male hormones have historically impaired leaders' judgment and that women leaders take fewer unnecessary risks. It asserts the real issue is not biochemistry but a well-established gender bias against women in the workplace, which is a greater barrier to female leadership. This bias, both overt and covert, limits women's potential despite their qualifications. The article concludes that gender equality benefits everyone, leading to stronger companies, families, and the economy.

Veteran actor Robert Hardy, 89, is auctioning over 200 antiques from his personal collection for an estimated £100,000 as he downsizes his home. The collection reflects his interests in military history and classic literature and includes a hand-painted diorama of the Battle of Agincourt, a longbow, furniture, paintings, books, and other historical items. Hardy is known for his roles in *All Creatures Great and Small*, as Winston Churchill in various dramas, and as Cornelius Fudge in the Harry Potter films. The auction is being handled by Dominic Winter Auctioneers in Gloucestershire.

Michael Scott Shemansky is a suspect in the murder of his mother, Sandra Shemansky, 57, in their Winter Garden home. He failed to appear for a supervised visit with his son on the day she was found dead. Shemansky has a history of bipolar illness, a prior battery on law enforcement conviction, and was going through a divorce, which neighbors believe may have pushed him over the edge. He was last seen fleeing on foot without provisions or medication, and authorities are searching for him.

The city of Eugene, USA, was awarded the 2021 IAAF World Championships. The IAAF Council bypassed the usual bidding process, citing a unique strategic opportunity to host the event for the first time in the USA. Eugene had previously failed in its bid for the 2019 event, which went to Doha. The IAAF president stated the decision was made to access a key market with support from public authorities, the private sector, and the public. A 2007 championship in Osaka was also awarded without a bidding process.

Leonie Granger, an aspiring model, was jailed for 16 years for the manslaughter of professional gambler Mehmet Hassan. She lured Hassan after meeting him at a casino, then left his flat door unlocked for her boyfriend, Kyrron Jackson, and an accomplice, Nicholas Chandler. The two men tied up Hassan, kicked him to death, and ransacked his home for cash. Jackson and Chandler were convicted of murder and jailed for life. The judge described the attack as "pitiless and wicked." Granger was found to have targeted Hassan because he was a "soft target" who carried large amounts of cash.

Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fàbregas is experiencing a significant dip in form in the second half of the season, continuing a trend noted by his former club Barcelona. After a brilliant start where he amassed 15 Premier League assists and looked set to break Thierry Henry's record, his contributions have declined, with only one assist in his last five club games. This slump was evident in a recent international match where he performed poorly. Despite Chelsea being on track to win the Premier League, there are concerns about his durability and fatigue. However, with nine games left, there is hope he can rediscover his form to help secure the title.

West Ham United are in talks to sign 17-year-old Jamaican forward Deshane Beckford after a successful trial. He has impressed coaches and has other offers from Belgian clubs. Separately, West Ham announced their season tickets for the Olympic Stadium will start at £289, making them the cheapest in the Premier League as they aim to fill the 54,000-seat venue for the 2016-17 season.

Police have dropped an investigation into the assault of huntsman Mike Lane, despite video evidence and a dossier containing names and car registrations of suspected saboteurs. Lane was beaten with iron bars, kicked in the head, and suffered concussion, broken teeth, and memory loss. The attack occurred during a legal hunt using an artificial scent. Wiltshire police stated the case was shelved due to insufficient evidence and will only be re-opened if new evidence emerges. The victim and hunt supporters have condemned the decision as "pathetic" and "disgraceful," claiming the police did not do enough. The Countryside Alliance is campaigning to ban face coverings for hunt saboteurs to help identify criminals.

Adam Gadahn, an American-born spokesman and prominent English-language propagandist for al Qaeda, was killed in a U.S. counterterrorism operation in January. Known as "Azzam the American," he converted to Islam, moved to Pakistan in 1998, and rose through al Qaeda's ranks. He appeared in numerous videos threatening attacks on the West, urging lone-wolf attacks, and criticizing U.S. presidents. Indicted for treason in 2006, he was on the FBI's most wanted terrorists list. In the operation that killed another al Qaeda operative, a U.S. hostage, Warren Weinstein, was also accidentally killed.

A five-year-old Chinese boy named Mai Zizhuo has become an internet sensation in China due to a viral video showcasing his extraordinary basketball skills. He has been playing since age two and a half, and the video shows him scoring multiple hoops and dribbling two balls simultaneously without losing rhythm. His talent has attracted a huge fanbase in the basketball-loving country, with many netizens expressing amazement and disbelief, while others compared their own skills unfavorably to his.

Tom O'Carroll, a former leading member of the Paedophile Information Exchange (PIE) which campaigned to legalize sex with children and incest in the 1970s and 80s, has joined the supporters of the media pressure group Hacked Off. He attended a Hacked Off rally in Parliament to lobby for state-regulated press oversight, a move that is considered an embarrassment for the group. The rally was chaired by John Cleese and was open to the public.

The Bondi Icebergs club pool was drained on Thursday to serve as a catwalk for the Ten Pieces label during Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week Australia. The unisex collection, designed to be worn in 20 different ways, was presented in the empty pool and along the break wall with the ocean as a backdrop. The show was attended by guests on the balcony and observed by passers-by on a warm, sunny day. Ten Pieces is headed by Maurice Terzini, who is also the restaurateur for Icebergs.

Amir Khan visited a safari park in Northern California with his wife and daughter. He announced his next boxing match will be against Chris Algieri on May 30, choosing not to fight Kell Brook, Adrien Broner, or Keith Thurman.

Mohammed Abu Khdeir, a 16-year-old Palestinian beaten and burned alive by three Israelis, had his name placed on Israel's official memorial for fallen soldiers and terror victims. His family and an Israeli terror victims' organization, Almagor, objected to his inclusion. Following the complaints, the National Insurance Institute of Israel decided to remove his name from the memorial wall.

A young boy repeatedly tries to use his cat's belly as a pillow, chasing it around the garden. Each time the boy lies on the cat, it moves away. After several attempts, the cat goes indoors. A later video shows the boy feeding the cat treats, indicating they have reconciled.

A witness in a Philadelphia police corruption trial, Robert Kushner, lost his job as a varsity basketball coach after testifying. He stated that officers on trial stole $81,000 and marijuana from him during a 2007 arrest. The private school, unaware of his history, fired him after his testimony revealed his past drug dealing and subsequent arrests in 2007 and 2011. Kushner expressed remorse, stating the 2007 incident was a past "bad phase." The six officers face charges including racketeering, with their defense arguing the case relies on testimony from dishonest drug dealers.

An explosion at a paraxylene (PX) chemical plant in Zhangzhou, China, injured six people and caused a major fire. The blast occurred in an oil storage facility due to a leak, but no toxic spill was reported. Over 600 firefighters controlled the blaze. The plant, which produces a reportedly carcinogenic chemical, had a previous explosion in 2013 and was relocated from Xiamen in 2007 following public protests over pollution concerns.

Aston Villa teenager Jack Grealish insists he will not pull his socks up despite referees telling him to, as wearing them low over his children's-sized shinpads is a lifelong superstition. He made his first Premier League start in a 3-3 draw against QPR and was pleased the manager had faith in him, hoping to earn more starts.

Bobbi Kristina Brown has "global and irreversible brain damage" and remains unresponsive, according to her grandmother and a medical source. While she is no longer in a medically induced coma and has been moved out of the ICU, she does not respond to visitors. Her father, Bobby Brown, stated her condition had improved and she had opened her eyes, but the family attorney clarified the quality of her future life after a long rehabilitation is unknown.

Russia leads Germany 2-0 in their Fed Cup tie. Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova saved a match point before defeating Sabine Lisicki, and Svetlana Kuznetsova earlier beat Julia Goerges in straight sets. Russia needs one win from Sunday's three matches to reach the final and secure its first Fed Cup title since 2008.

Residents of New South Wales are warned to brace for more floods and damage as another storm, an east coast low, is predicted to hit later in the week, potentially bringing heavy rain from Thursday to Saturday. The State Emergency Service (SES) is concerned this will hamper ongoing clean-up efforts from last week's storm, with over 4,000 of 24,196 jobs still incomplete. The SES is particularly worried about the already hard-hit Hunter region. Meteorologists indicate the main impacts of intense rain and strong winds will be on coastal areas in the state's north-east, but the system is expected to be different and move more quickly than the previous one.

Model Nina Moric denied Italian media reports that she attempted suicide. She stated on Instagram that she was hospitalized due to low blood pressure causing a fall at home, resulting in bruising. While her boyfriend was quoted confirming a suicide attempt, Moric insisted the claims were false and that she was recovering from a domestic accident. The reports also referenced a past alleged overdose in 2009. Moric was previously married to paparazzo Fabrizio Corona, who was jailed for blackmailing celebrities.

As the British public anticipates the birth of Prince William and Kate's second child, a poll reveals a preference for a baby girl, with Diana being the most favored name in honor of William's late mother. For a girl, the names Alice and Charlotte are also popular, while James is the top choice for a boy. A majority of Britons also support William's decision to take six weeks of paternity leave.

A suicide bomber attacked protesters in Khost, Afghanistan, killing 17 people and wounding 64, including a local lawmaker. The protesters were marching against the provincial governor. The Taliban denied responsibility for the attack, and no other group claimed it.

Dani Alves will leave Barcelona after his agent confirmed he rejected the club's final contract offer, a three-year extension contingent on him playing 60% of matches. The 31-year-old right-back, who won four Spanish titles and two Champions Leagues in seven years, was unable to agree on a new deal.

Pablo Osvaldo, on loan at Boca Juniors, has publicly urged Italian legends Andrea Pirlo and Francesco Totti to join him. He believes their playing style is a good fit for the club and that Boca fans would be ecstatic to see them play at La Bombonera.

Amateur jockey Lewis Ferguson, 18, suffered only a minor cut on his nose after a spectacular double somersault fall from his horse at Wincanton, which became an internet sensation. He was back riding the next day, undeterred by the incident, and described the fall as a blur and the most impressive he had seen. Ferguson considers himself lucky, has received good-natured banter from fellow jockeys, and gained hundreds of Twitter followers from the event.

Rugby player James Haskell posted a photo on Instagram of himself dressed as Iron Man to coincide with the release of the movie "Avengers: Age of Ultron." The London Wasps captain has had a varied career, playing for the club from 2002-2009 before spells with Stade Francais in France, the Ricoh Black Rams in Japan, and the Highlanders in New Zealand. He returned to Wasps in 2012, where he has since made over 100 appearances for the club, and has earned 57 caps for England.

The wide-leg trouser is a key trend for SS15, offering an alternative to the skinny jean. This look, which has made comebacks since the 1970s, can be intimidating but is achievable with the right styling. The key is to wear high heels to elongate the leg and pair the trousers with a simple top to maintain proportion and avoid being overwhelmed by fabric. Denim is cited as the easiest way to adopt the trend, as seen on the Gucci runway, while brands like Celine and Stella McCartney offered dressier versions. High-street options are also available from Topshop and Finery London.

The University of Michigan reversed its decision and will proceed with screening "American Sniper" after initially canceling it due to student objections. Over 200 students had petitioned against the film, believing its depiction of the Iraq War was negative towards the Middle East, while a counter-petition supported the screening. A university vice president stated canceling the film was a mistake that conflicted with the school's values of free expression and student choice. An alternative screening of "Paddington" will be offered for those who do not wish to attend.

Two French tourists on Rottnest Island, Australia, used a lighter and aerosol spray to set a quokka on fire on April 3. The animal survived but was singed. The men, aged 18 and 24, were evicted from the island, questioned by detectives, and charged with animal cruelty. They are due to appear in court on April 17.

A 102-year-old former dancer, Alice Barker, who performed in New York nightclubs like the Cotton Club in the 1930s and 1940s, had never seen footage of herself dancing. With the help of a film historian, she was shown a compilation of her early music videos, which delighted her as she had lost all her memorabilia over the years.

The tradition of washing one's own car on a Sunday is declining in Britain. A study found that a third of men and three-quarters of women have never washed their own car. Reasons include less free time due to Sunday shopping and televised football, the popularity of inexpensive hand car washes, and the large size of modern vehicles like 4x4s. Few people now ask their children to wash the car for pocket money. Car washing is most common during holidays, and the frequency varies by location and car brand.

Martin Skrtel praised Steven Gerrard's significant impact and leadership at Liverpool, describing him as one of the world's best players and synonymous with the club. While acknowledging that Liverpool will be different without Gerrard, who is leaving for LA Galaxy, Skrtel believes the team has players who can replace him with the right support. Both players are set to return from a three-match ban for the FA Cup semi-final against Aston Villa.

At age 75, Jack Nicklaus scored a hole-in-one on the fourth hole during the Masters Par-3 contest at Augusta National, playing with Gary Player and Ben Crenshaw. This was his first ace at Augusta. The day saw a record-tying five holes-in-one, including two from Camilo Villegas, but Kevin Streelman won the contest. Nicklaus, the 1963 and 1986 Masters champion, is one of five golfers to achieve the career Grand Slam.

Tornado sirens sounded in Kansas as storms produced multiple reported tornadoes, including one near Goddard and others in southwestern Kansas. A possible tornado may have touched down in Potosi, Missouri, causing wind damage, flooding, and property damage. A CNN expert warned that nighttime tornadoes are the most dangerous. More storms were forecast for the Midwest and Mississippi and Tennessee River Valleys for the following day.

Robert Bates, an Oklahoma reserve sheriff's deputy, pleaded not guilty to second-degree manslaughter for fatally shooting Eric Harris, claiming he mistook his gun for a Taser. The judge allowed Bates to go on a Bahamas vacation, which the victim's family called an act of apathy. The family's lawyer alleges Bates was unqualified but received preferential treatment due to his donations and friendship with the sheriff, an allegation the sheriff's office denies. Bates' lawyer released training records to prove his qualifications. Two other deputies involved in the arrest were reassigned due to threats.

Conor McGregor is preparing for a UFC featherweight title fight against champion Jose Aldo on July 11 in Las Vegas. Ahead of the bout, he revealed a new tiger tattoo on his stomach. McGregor claims Aldo lacks the same motivation to win that he possesses, a point he emphasized during a promotional tour in Dublin by grabbing Aldo's belt in front of his home supporters.

Australian Prime Minister Tony Abbott downed a schooner of beer in about six seconds at a football function, drawing criticism from anti-drinking campaigners. A professor stated the act glorified binge drinking and promoted a problematic culture linking masculinity and heavy alcohol consumption to being a "true blue Aussie bloke." Critics argued a prime minister should set a better example, while the health minister defended Mr. Abbott, pointing to his overall fitness.

Indiana is experiencing a significant HIV outbreak in Scott County, with 120 confirmed and 10 preliminary cases, primarily among intravenous drug users of the painkiller Opana. Governor Mike Pence approved a temporary 30-day needle exchange program to curb the outbreak, which has distributed thousands of clean syringes. The program's future is uncertain as Pence and some lawmakers oppose such exchanges on anti-drug policy grounds, though health officials support them as a harm-reduction measure. Legislation is being considered to allow needle-exchange programs in other high-risk counties, but funding is a concern due to a federal ban on public funding for these programs.

An Arsenal fan made his girlfriend, Saskia, take a 50-question exam about his football club. She scored 87% (43.5/50), earning an 'A' grade, which he rewarded by not breaking up with her. The test was formatted like a school exam and included questions about players, history, and rival clubs. Her boyfriend marked it in red pen, providing critical feedback and drawing an angry face for wrong answers. Saskia posted the test on Twitter, where some users praised the boyfriend as a "legend" and called Saskia "proper gf material," while others criticized him for taking it too far.

Carlos Toro, a 66-year-old former mid-level member of the Medellin cartel, worked as an unpaid undercover informant for the DEA for 27 years with the promise of US citizenship. His information was crucial in prosecuting major figures like drug lord Carlos Lehder and former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega. Now retired due to declining health, the promised citizenship has not been granted, and he faces deportation. Toro, who is living illegally in the US and cannot collect Social Security, fears he will be killed if sent back to Colombia. A former DEA agent who worked with him says the government's failure to help is "bureaucracy at its worst."

A 14-year-old girl in India is fighting for her life with severe burns after setting herself on fire. She took this action after allegedly being gang-raped by five men from her village when she went outside her home. Her family reportedly told her to keep the attack quiet. The accused men have been arrested. This incident occurs amid heightened sensitivity in India regarding sexual assault, following other high-profile cases like the gang rape and murder of Jyoti Singh, which sparked widespread protests and a ban on a related documentary.

Manchester United manager Louis van Gaal is dreaming of beating rivals Manchester City in the upcoming derby, a victory that would significantly improve United's chances of finishing third in the league. However, he will be without Robin van Persie and Luke Shaw, whom he deems not fit enough to play. Van Gaal emphasized the need to control aggression, a lesson from the previous 1-0 loss to City, and is looking forward to the home support at Old Trafford.

Arsenal and Liverpool fans staged a 10-minute walk-in protest at the Emirates Stadium against high ticket prices, coordinated by their respective fan groups. This followed the Premier League's announcement of a £5.14 billion TV rights deal. Tickets for the match started at £64, which protesters called "extortionate." Banners inside and outside the stadium, such as "£5bn and what do we get? £64 a ticket" and "football without fans is nothing," highlighted the disconnect between the lucrative TV deal and rising costs for fans. Organizers warned that high prices risk losing a generation of working-class supporters and stated that further protests were planned.

A newborn baby, Star Reader, was diagnosed with the life-threatening liver condition biliary atresia. After an unsuccessful operation to unblock her bile ducts, a liver transplant became her only chance of survival. Neither of Star's parents was a suitable donor, but her mother's twin sister, Shanell, proved to be an ideal match and donated part of her liver. The transplant, performed in November, was successful. Star has since made a good recovery, though she will require lifelong medication and monitoring.

Chelsea players Eden Hazard, Nathan Aké, Loïc Rémy, and Willian participated in a multi-round football challenge for Audi. Hazard and Aké won the first two rounds, which involved kicking balls into a car boot and playing over the top of an Audi R8. Open Garden's FireChat app enables off-grid messaging using wireless mesh networks created between phones via Bluetooth or Wi-Fi, without needing an internet or mobile signal. Researchers from the University of Manchester have produced the largest high-definition map of dark matter, covering 0.4% of the sky. Created as part of the five-year Dark Energy Survey (DES), the map uses data from the Dark Energy Camera on the Victor M. Blanco Telescope in Chile. It was constructed by analyzing the shapes of 130 million galaxies, using gravitational lensing to detect dark matter's invisible presence, which makes up most of the universe's matter. The map shows clumps of dark matter (red) and sparse regions (blue), aligning with visible galaxies and supporting theories of galaxy formation. The ultimate goal is to create a 3D map covering 12.5% of the sky by 2018 to study dark energy and test cosmological theories.
